SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received flu vaccination without incident.  About 10-15 minutes later client returned with her child who said she was feeling light headed. School nurse was requested for interpretation and she asked client to sit down. Pulse 102 BP 118/78.  Briefly complained of heart palpitations . Client stated her symptoms were not severe but because she was driving with children in car she wanted to make sure she was okay to drive. Client refused to lay down but sat and said she had not eaten for  few hours.  Also stated she has had a similar reaction to vaccines in the past.  After about 10 minutes client felt better and good enough to drive and left with instructions to follow up with medical care if symptoms returned.

Approximately 24 hours after receiving the flu shot, the child developed hives in a dispersed pattern all over his body.  Within 5-6 hours, the hives became more prevalent and pronounced, covered more surface area - particularly the face, arms, legs, and trunk, became extremely itchy and uncomfortable.  At that time I, his mother, gave him Children's Benedryl 7.5ml orally.  After the medication took effect, the hives slowly diminished, the itching ceased and he felt better. There were no signs of respiratory distress or indications of life-threatening signs/symptoms, no rapid heartbeat, dizziness, weakness, or generalized swelling of the face / throat. The pediatrician has been notified via the patient portal system.  The pharmacy where the vaccine was given has also been informed via phone call.

Low lying placenta; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 21-Oct-2019, concerning a 28-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 206 lbs, height: 65.3 inches and body mass index (BMI): 34, enrolled in a prospective observational study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.  The subject's current conditions included genital herpes, hypertension, seasonal allergies and high body mass index (BMI 34). Concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (minerals NOS, vitamins NOS) for pregnancy, nifedipine for hypertension, Allegra (fexofenadine hydrochloride) for allergies, vitamin B6 and vitamin D2 as supplements.  The subject's obstetrical history included four previous pregnancies with two full term live births, one spontaneous abortion and one elective abortion. No birth defects were reported. Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 28-Apr-2019, the estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 02-Feb-2020. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 13-Jun-2019, 25-Jun-2019, 08-Jul-2019 and 03-Sep-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.   On 01-Oct-2019, at gestational age of 22 weeks, the subject was administered Afluria (QIV) [influenza vaccine; batch number: P100118566, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiry date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  On an unspecified date, an unknown amount of time after vaccination, low lying placenta was noted.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event 'low lying placenta was not reported.   The case was assessed as serious and the reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  Company comment: The subject experienced placenta praevia associated with the suspect product Afluria (QIV). Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at gestational age of approximately 22 weeks of gestation. Temporal relationship is implausible because location of the placenta is determined at implantation (first 3 weeks of gestation). Causality was confounded by use of concomitant drugs, Allegra (fexofenadine hydrochloride) and nifedipine. Causal relationship between the suspect product and exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company conventions. Causal relationship between the suspect product and the event placenta praevia is assessed as not related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced placenta praevia associated with the suspect product Afluria (QIV). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client presented to flu clinic for vaccination. Client stated she had never received a flu vaccination.  She stated she had never reacted to any former vaccines.  Denied any allergies to medications. Within 1-2 minutes of administering the vaccination, client felt dizzy, light-headed, short of breath, faint and her chest felt tight. PB 106/84; HR 78 R 22. "I feel like I will be having an asthma attack." She proceeded to use her inhaler. She is also insulin dependent diabetic. Glucose level was checked and was 200. She also stated she thought a headache was started. Rechecked her vitals again: BP 106/82; Resp 24, HR 80. It was recommended to client to let nurse call EMS but she refused. Reviewed paper document showing the difference between psychological fright and anaphylaxis in Policy Manual and she agreed that it was more than likely the psychological fright as the symptoms were slowly improving. Client chose to leave the clinic area but nurse recommended that she have co-worker take her to ER if her symptoms worsened and did not continue to improve. Nurse also recommended she have her flu shot next year at a physician's office.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Symptom Timeline:   Tuesday, October 15    Received the Flu Vaccine late afternoon  Wednesday, October 16  Sudden onset of Erectile Dysfunction      Loss of Libido      Feelings of Malaise      Racing Heart  Thursday, October 17  Noticed decreased muscle strength at workout  Saturday, October 19  Dis-located BOTH shoulders doing handstand  (He has been doing handstands regularly in his ?core? workouts at the gym.)       Went by ambulance to the ER  (ER Doctors suggested he see a Rheumatologist regarding possible connective tissue disorder such as ?Hypermobile EDS?. Appointment scheduled for November 27)  Sunday, October 20   Informed us of his symptoms  Monday, October 21   Went to Health Services / Did Blood work      (Started taking Vitamin D3 & B12 Supplements)  Tuesday, October 22   Began experiencing slight tremors      No improvement of other symptoms  Wednesday, October 23  Appt. at Health Services to review Blood work      Shoulders sore but doing well      Back pain on right side (kidney stone?)      Found blood in urine ? sending to lab      Additional Blood work being done      Drank lots of fluids throughout evening  (Lab results from Monday showed normal Testosterone Level, Calcium level of 10.2, Vitamin D level low?)  Thursday, October 24  Back pain gone in the morning      Urologist Appointment at 3:45      Urine test showed no blood      Exam completely normal       (The Urologist, Dr feels the sudden onset of these symptoms was due to the Flu Vaccine and shared that he has heard of other examples of people getting sick from this 2019 Vaccine)   (Dr emailed and asked patient to come back in on Friday at 2:15 for more lab tests because they didn?t do everything. She also doesn?t think it is Subacute Thyroiditis because the thyroid is normal size and not tender).  Friday, October 25   Doing more lab work at 2:15       Saturday, October 26  Received third set of Lab results      Dr recommended hydrating more       (Creatinine level high (1.39) and A/G Ratio high (2.4), Calcium level still 10.2)       Back Pain now on left side  (In email from Dr she stated: ?I think something self-limited is going on, like a virus or reaction to the flu vaccine?)    Sunday, October 27, 2019  Slight improvement in some symptoms      Consult with Dr scheduled for 10/28  Monday, October 28, 2019  2:30 Exam and consult with Dr      Exam was normal      More blood work to rule out Lyme or Mono      Will re-check Creatinine level and Calcium level      Asked about checking Nitric Oxide levels?  (Discussed symptoms of Nitric Oxide deficiency matching the symptoms that patient has presented since the flu vaccine: Fatigue, Low Workout Potential, Less Stamina, Erectile Dysfunction, Decreased Libido, Poor Memory, Irritability, Depression, Anxiety, Insomnia and High Blood Pressure)  (Shared an article that I found titled: ?Vaccina virus-induced inhibition of Nitric Oxide production? and another article that said losses in Nitric Oxide signaling are major contributors to ?accelerated renal stone formation?)   (Dr felt it was highly possible that this was a reaction to the flu vaccine. We told him that we planned on reporting this and he felt that was a good idea.)  Tuesday, October 29, 2019  Feeling ?okay? today  Wednesday, October 30, 2019 Lab results back and note from Dr  (Lyme test was Negative;, Mono test shows he had mono in the past and most likely is immune to getting it again; Creatinine level was back to Normal; Systemic Markers for Inflammation or Autoimmune issues were Normal).  (Contacted Law Office to file Report to Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) and also file a claim with the National Vaccine Injury Compensation Program.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came into the office for a nurse visit for his first Hep A and first HPV vaccine per PCP Vaccines were administered in opposite arms  After vaccines were given, I went over VIS and return dates for #2 of each vaccine Noticed patient was getting clammy and pale Asked if he was ok Eyes glassed over and rolled into the back of his head Patient then leaned forward becoming limp, I was able to catch him and lay him down on exam table Patient began full body convulsing and drooling  I turned him onto his left side and called for Dr. to assist Convulsions lasted approx 10 seconds Dr. entered room and patient regained consciousness He was dazed and confused Unsure who we were and asked for space We gave him space as he regained consciousness Dr. stayed with patient and his mom while I got him a cup of water Mom denies prior history of seizures, fainting or reactions from vaccines  Patient drank water and felt better Dr. (patient's pcp) came in to see patient and follow up was made for next week Mom will call if there are any concerns or questions in the meantime  Patient walked out of office unassisted and stable
LAB_DATA: Patient is returning to office for eval with PCP on 11/4/2019 at which time tests will be ordered if PCP finds this necessary

The child's grandmother and myself had to hold onto him to keep him  from sliding off exam bench. Client regained consciousness slowly and  stated he didn't remember what happened.  Vitals were taken and were WNL. When client appeared to be fully recovered, he left with his grandmother,stating he felt fine.

No Follow-up Needed as long as improving. 10/30/19 This is a 4 year old male that presents with concerns for reaction to vaccination. He was given his varicella, Kinrix and MMR vaccines 2 days ago. Mother noticed the night of his vaccines that he was developing some erythema and warmth around his left thigh where the vaccines had been administered. He had no other trouble breathing. He had no diarrhea or emesis. She gave some Motrin and let him relax overnight. In the morning he had a couple other areas of rash on his chest and back. He states that the area was itchy and kind of sore, so mother called out triage line and at the time he did not have any other symptoms. No fever, no work of breathing or anything like that, so they were recommended to give some more Motrin and to followup today. Today the area is slightly larger than she saw last night. She had outlined it the night before and it is still warm but the patient is not complaining of any soreness at this time. He does state that it is itchy. He is having no other symptoms today and the areas of rash that were on his abdomen and back appear to be improving. O: Temperature is 97.9. General: Patient is awake and alert sitting up on the clinic table in no acute distress. Eyes: PERR bilaterally without conjunctival injection. ENT: Bilateral tympanic membranes are clear of erythema or bulge. Tympanostomy tubes are in place. Nares are patent without rhinorrhea. Throat is clear of erythema or exudate. CV: Heart is regular rate and rhythm without murmurs, rubs or gallops. Respiratory: Lungs are clear to auscultation bilaterally without wheeze or crackle. Abdomen: If obese and soft and nontender with good bowel sounds in all 4 quadrants. Skin: On the left thigh surrounding the area of his previous vaccination there is an area of erythema and warmth. It is a large patch about 5 cm x 6 cm. It has an irregular border. It is slightly outside the line that mother marked last night. There is no tenderness to palpation of the area. It is nonfluctuant. There are no other rashes or lesions noted on his body. A/P: This appears to be a local reaction most likely to the varicella vaccine that was placed in that leg. As he did not have a previous reaction before and has no intention to have that vaccine again as he has gotten his 2, this is unlikely to happen again. I recommended that they do some Benadryl 12.5 mg every 6 hours as needed to see if that helps and this should help this go away. Strict return precautions were given regarding any fluctuance of the area, fevers or other symptoms. We will also report this to the vaccine registry.

Guillain Barre syndrome; Information has been received from a lawyer referring to a male patient of unknown age. Information about concurrent condition, history condition and concomitant medication was not reported. On or around 22-FEB-2018, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route, lot# and expiration date unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (date not reported), the patient suffered right upper weakness, tingling, numbness and dizziness and was diagnosed with Guillain Barre Syndrome. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event Guillain Barre Syndrome was not recovered and causal relationship was assessed as related.   The lawyer considered the event Guillain Barre Syndrome to be disability.   Upon internal review, the event Guillain Barre Syndrome was determined to be medically significant.

Within 30 minutes of receiving the Shingrix injection, the patient experienced symptoms of a relapse of tick fever. He had chills, fever, body aches and was in bed for 2+ days. He also had severe pain in back, unlike his usual back problems. When I (his spouse) looked 2 days later he had red spots following nerve tracts of center back. That is where the pain was concentrated. The spots did not blister or weep. He recovered in 4 days.
Developed soreness in left arm.  Experiencing pain in shoulder and neck area the next day.  Hurts to turn my head/neck.  Cramps when I turned my head/neck.  This pain and soreness has continued.

States she got the shot on the 17th and it didn't bother her at the time but by 11pm the next night it started hurting and when she woke up the next morning she felt like her R shoulder was dislocated she couldn't lift it or move it much. She was icing it and taking warm showers and letting the water run on it, she was taking Alieve for the pain but nothing was really helping it. She states  the pain is a little less the past 2 nights she has been able to sleep.

Within the same week as receiving the PNEUMOVAX 23 the patient experienced cellulitis; This initial spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist, referring to a 66-year-old female patient. Her pertinent medical history included hypertension and diabetes mellitus. Her concomitant therapies included unspecified medications as treatment for hypertension and diabetes. The patient's historical conditions were not reported. The patient had no, previous drug reactions or allergies.  On 10-SEP-2019, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) administered intramuscularly (dose/frequency reported as 25mcg/5.5ml) , lot number R018735 expiration date 06-APR-2020, as prophylaxis (reported as "routine") (anatomical injection site was not reported).         Afterwards, on an unspecified day in September 2019 (also reported as "within the same week as receiving pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23)") the patient experienced cellulitis. It was reported that 2 days after the cellulitis appeared, the patient sought medical attention, went to a walk-in clinic and was prescribed cephalexin 500mg and prednisone 5mg, as treatment for the event. No laboratory diagnostics or studies were performed to the patient.  On an unspecified date in 2019, the patient fully recovered from the event of cellulitis.  The causality assessment between pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) and cellulitis occurrence was not provided.  It was reported that cellulitis was not a disabling, life-threatening, cancer or overdose event. The patient did not required hospitalization due to this event. Upon internal review, the event of cellulitis was determined to be medically significant.  By request of the reporting pharmacist, an investigation was started for the reported lot number.

About 30 min after receiving shot, she called and reported symptoms of bilateral facial tingling, numbness in upper teeth and lip, and metallic taste in her mouth. I asked her to report back to my office and she was there almost immediately. As I was questioning her, the symptoms persisted and as I was about to check vitals, she stated she felt like she was "going to pass out." She sat for another minute or two and was able to walk assisted by me to the ER. Once in the ER vitals were stable and symptoms of facial tingling, and numbness in teeth and upper lip persisted, and she developed an headache. An IV was started and she was then given IV steroid, The Dr. verbalized was not concerned about analphylactic reaction. She was monitored and then released to home after a few hours of monitoring. The next day she reported new symptoms of delayed speech, which was evident when I saw her in person. She came to work and I took her to the ED to be evaluated once again. She had CT scan and was tested for Lyme Disease. CT was negative and Lyme test was unequivocal. She followed up with provider the next day (10/3). Symptoms of delayed speech persisted, and she was referred to neuro. 10/4 she had MRI and neurologist stated this was all due to Lyme and not related to Flu shot. Follow-up with PCP the following week it was revealed to patient she did not have Lyme, and symptoms were due to flu shot. It remains under investigation by Agency to determine if this was caused by flu shot or reaction to something else.

The thumb of right hand started aching. Woke me up during the night, too. By morning (10/24/2019), hand was swollen, especially area above thumb, which was also red and raised. Using fingers or thumbs was extremely painful. Lasted all day; a bit better by 10 PM. Next morning, pain much less but still achy; able to use hand again. Still red above thumb; finger swelling less by 2 PM. This happened with the first dose of Shingrix on 7-25-2019, with symptoms beginning 7-27-19. Then I had the vaccine in my left arm and problems began in my left hand, especially the thumb. I saw a doctor for that one at the walkin clinic on 7-29-19; I told her I thought it was the Shingrix causing it. She had me x-ray it anyway, which showed no problem. I purposely had the 2nd dose in my right arm, to see if it would cause the problem on that side or whether it had been a coincidence caused by something else. No coincidence! I anticipate that my hand will slowly return to normal, as happened in July. I decided to report this, since it is not listed as a possible side effect in any literature I've read. (I used to conduct research studies using medications, so I know how important this is). This first vaccine was also made by glaxo-smith-kline, Lot # B5HP5.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: SIRVA

Received the employee required flu vaccine on 9/20/19 at the Occupational Health Office. By 9/22/19, reactions started to occur. Reactions consisted of rash: hives, itching, redness, swelling, inflammation, and severe pain of the chest, neck, and face. From these symptoms, I was unable to sleep or function in daily life because of pain and other symptoms mentioned starting on 9/22/19. This rash and the symptoms interfered with work and then ability to wear hospital OR gowns during the scrub rotation of the Program. The gowns rubbed against the rash on my neck which further aggravated the rash.   I went to primary care doctor on 10/3/19 to get evaluated and for lab to be drawn. Labs tests showed increase in lymphocytes and eosinophils- the primary care doctor concluded an allergic reaction to something in my body.  On 10/4/19 I took the day off because of how severe the allergic reaction was. On 10/4/19 I went to the allergist first thing in the morning with the same reactions as mentioned plus had a hoarse and sore throat due to the extensive inflammation around the neck/throat area. Allergist prescribed Prednisone 40mg for 5 days and a steroid cream- Triamcinolone Acetonide Ointment 0.1% as needed for rash. Took prescribed Prednisone for 5 days, and 2 days later, rash returned: hives, itching, redness, swelling, inflammation, dryness, and severe pain of the chest, neck, and face. Side effects of Prednisone was severe (insomnia) that it was not recommended to take again along with the side effects of the steroid cream (extremely dry/painful skin). Allergist recommended patch testing to see if any chemicals or metals that may be reacting to my body. Patch testing was available after waiting 2 weeks after the last dose of Prednisone so the steroids will not interact with the results of the patch testing.  Patch testing was placed on 10/28/19, first patch test read and removed on 10/30/19, and final read on 11/1/19. Results from the patch testing showed allergic response to Thimerosal. In addition, took off work on 10/29/19 due to lack of sleep from the rash and symptoms of the rash (hives, itching, redness, swelling, inflammation, and severe pain of the chest, neck, and face).  I have been taking Benadryl and Claritin to try to ease the symptoms with little luck. I went to another allergist on 10/29/19, and he prescribed montelukast, zyrtec, and hydralazine to help with the inflammation, allergic reaction, and sleep (but with little luck, the symptoms of the effects of the flu shot still persists).   Rash has continued to this day and has spread to other areas of the body- entire face/ears, traps, upper back, and arms (starting around 10/14/19). The rash and effects of the flu shot is still currently affecting everyday life including effecting work (concentration/ coming in to work/ wearing OR scrubs and normal clothing) and ability to sleep at night. The lack of sleep interferes with work as well. As mentioned, the rash is currently still very itchy, red, swollen, dry, with inflammation, and severe pain of the chest, neck, and face.
LAB_DATA: CBC- LYMPHOCYTES INCREASED, EOSINOPHILS INCREASED PATCH TESTING- THIMEROSAL

Shot was extremely painful; Arm was sore; Swelling; Warm to the touch; Red Spots / they were red with swelling; Spots were the size of quarters and they were painful, warm to the touch and sensitive; Spots were the size of quarters and they were painful, warm to the touch and sensitive; area was light pink; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in a adult female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain, pain in arm, swelling, skin warm, erythromacular rash, painful rash, sensitive skin and skin discoloration. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain, pain in arm, swelling and skin warm were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the erythromacular rash, painful rash, sensitive skin and skin discoloration were unknown. The shot was extremely painful and her arm was sore that day. 1 day after receiving Shingrix, the patient had three red spots that appeared and they were red with swelling. The other 2 spots were the size of quarters and they were painful, warm to the touch and sensitive. The first day the area was light pink. The second and third days they were red and swollen. By the forth day, the spots dissipated and her symptoms have full resolved at the reporting date.  The patient also reported that she had an allergy to some drugs so she was not certain if her reaction was a possible allergic reaction to the shot. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Joint ache in hands and knees; Fever; Muscle ache in neck; Headache; Received the second dose one month and 10 days after getting the first dose; Nausea; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of arthralgia in a 66-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concomitant products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix).   On 22nd October 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). In October 2019, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced nausea. On 22nd October 2019, the patient experienced arthralgia, fever, myalgia, headache and drug dose administration interval too short. On an unknown date, the outcome of the arthralgia, fever, myalgia, nausea, headache and drug dose administration interval too short were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the arthralgia, fever, myalgia, nausea and headache to be related to Shingrix.  The patient received Shingrix about 10 hours experiencing joint ache in hands and knees, fever, muscle ache in neck and headache. The fever and headache are improving. Patient also stated that he received the second dose one month and 10 days after getting the first dose, which led to shortening of vaccination schedule. The reporter consented to follow up. No further details were provided.  The caller was reporting adverse event for himself and his wife.  This case is 1 of 2 cases, reported by same reporter.  From the case description it seems that US2019193745 is duplicate of US2019192798. As the case US2019192798 was reported earlier, it should be considered as case of record. Case US2019193745 would be deleted from system.

Diarrhea; Stomach does not feel rigth; Could not raise her arm up and down the rest of the day and the next day; Feeling weak; Headache; Arm was sore; Arm was red; Arm was swollen half way around and red; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 80-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm, erythema of extremities, swelling arm, mobility decreased, weakness, headache, diarrhea and stomach upset were unknown. She reports her arm was sore before she went to bed that night.When she was taking a shower the next morning she noted that her arm was swollen half way around and red.  She could not raise her arm up and down the rest of the day and the next day. At the time of reporting, she reports that her arm was not as sore and red and she can now move it around. The next morning after receiving the vaccine she noted that she was feeling weak.  She had headaches on October and she took Advil to help treat them. At the time of reporting she has not had any headaches so far and not as weak as she was.   She did not that she was having stomach issues. Her stomach does not feel right and she has had some diarrhea. The reporter did not consent to follow up. The reporter unable to obtain additional information.

Blood presure went to 175; headache; chills; off balance; Redness on arm/ huge mark from the shot, halfway around the arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of blood pressure high in a 78-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concomitant products included metoprolol.   On 13th October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 14th October 2019, 1 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced blood pressure high. In October 2019, the patient experienced headache, chills, balance difficulty and erythema of extremities. The patient was treated with Tylenol. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blood pressure high, headache, chills and balance difficulty were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the erythema of extremities was recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the blood pressure high, headache, chills, balance difficulty and erythema of extremities to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix in the right arm, eleven days ago of the reporting date. The patient claimed that, she had quite a reaction to the vaccine. She reported that she was fine the first day she got the vaccination till around noon, however, the next day everything went downhill. The patient took her blood pressure medication which worked well, however, her blood pressure went to 175 so her physician increased her Metoprolol dose and then she was fine. She also experienced a headache, chills and she was a bit off balance and had to hold onto the door frame. The patient stated, she had a huge mark from the shot which was halfway around her right arm and 11 days later, the red circle was of the size of a baseball. The patient's other symptoms resolved quickly but she had to go the doctor's office twice. The doctor told her to take anti-inflammatory drugs but because of her blood pressure medication, she could only take Tylenol which she did and her redness on her arm was currently paler in color. The patient consented to follow up.
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 20191014; Test Name: Blood pressure; Result Unstructured Data: Test Result: 175, Test Result Unit: unknown

PT CAME IN FOR SHINGRIX SHOT. SHE REMOVED HER SWEATER FROM HER RIGHT ARM AND SAT DOWN FOR THE INJECTION. I PROCEEDED TO TELL HER THE SIDE EFFECTS OF THE VACCINE, ETC. I ADMINISTERED THE VACCINE. PT TRIED TO GET UP FROM THE SITTING POSITION BUT HAD SOME DIFFICULTY. SHE TRIED TO GET SOME LEVERAGE WITH THE COUNTER. I TRIED HELPING HER UP BUT COULDN'T GET HER STANDING. PT IS ON CHRONIC OXYGEN AND HAD HER OXYGEN GOING. WHEN I COULDN'T GET HER STANDING, I SAT HER BACK DOWN IN THE CHAIR. SHE BECAME UNRESPONSIVE TO COMMENTS, COMMANDS, INTERACTION OF ANY KIND. SHE HAD HER EYES CLOSED, WAS BREATHING NORMALLY, HAD GOOD COLOR, AND HAD A REGULAR PULSE (PULSE WAS CHECKED BY A NURSE CUSTOMER WHO WAS HERE AT THE TIME. AT THAT TIME WE PAGED HUSBAND AND CALLED HIS CELL NUMBER WITH NO RESPONSE. PT'S HUSBAND CAME IN SHORTLY THEREAFTER. HE WAS WAITING IN THE CAR FOR HER. HE CHECKED HER OXYGEN AND TURNED IT UP. WE CALLED 911. IN THE INTERIM WE TRIED COMMUNICATING WITH PATIENT AND TRIED GETTING HER TO RESPOND. 911 ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER. PT'S HUSBAND LEFT WITH PATIENT. THE NEXT DAY PT'S HUSBAND CAME IN AND TOLD ME SHE HAD HAD A MASSIVE CEREBRAL BLEED AND WASN'T EXPECTED TO RECOVER. AT NO TIME DID HE INDICATE THAT HE THOUGHT IT WAS FROM THE SHOT. THE NEXT DAY I SPOKE TO THE PT'S DOCTOR AND HE TOO DIDN'T THINK IT WAS DUE TO THE VACCINE AND THAT THE TIMING WAS COINCIDENTAL. AT THIS TIME, I DO NOT KNOW IF THE PT IS CURRENTLY IN THE HOSPITAL OR HAS PASSED AWAY.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the flu shot 10/31/19 at about 2:30pm to my left shoulder. Initially I felt ok, but after about 4 hours I started feeling itchy and tingly to my whole body. My heart rate felt very fast and my chest felt a little tight so I took 2 puffs of my albuterol inhaler which I had previously been prescribed for exercise induced asthma. The rest of the night I still felt itchy and tingly but was able to go to sleep. The next morning I went to work still feeling a little itchy and tingly. Around 10:30am I started feeling an intense itching and burning to my left shoulder and when I looked down I noticed some hives to that shoulder. At this point I went to Employee Health to be evaluated. The nurse saw me and noticed the hives and asked if I had any shortness of breath. At that point I did not but I did tell her it felt as though my heart rate was fast. She told me the NP would not be in for a little while and that I could wait or go back to work and come back if my symptoms got worse. I decided to go back to work and to have her call me when the FNP was back in. I was called that the FNP would be back at 1:00pm so I went there around 1:30pm. At this time the hives had gone away, my heart rate felt to have decreased a little from before, the itching and tingling had decreased. At this point my heart rate was checked and it was about 109bpm calm and  sitting down which is still elevated from my normal of about 50-60bpm. The FNP was concerned that my heart rate was elevated from my normal and that I had had hives to that shoulder earlier so she gave me Zyrtec and Benadryl to have on hold in case the symptoms came back or got worse. The rest of the day I had some itching and tingling but by the morning of 11/2/19  my heart rate has normalized and the itching and tingling has just about completely subsided. I did not take the Zyrtec or Bendadryl.

On Sat had rash inside of both arms also and started taking benadryl..  P  The rash has been itchy especially ears and neck.  I have had many flu shots without any problems. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Between 5 to 10 minutes following the immunization, the patient and her mother returned to the pharmacy with complaints of not feeling well. She was pale, and complained of her ears popping, her eye hurting, and being very thirsty. She was instructed to sit and then to lie down while I assessed her. She had no immediate sings of an allergic reaction including no signs of labored/difficulty breathing, no signs of a rash or hives, no difficulty swallowing. Her pulse was normal and her blood pressure was normal. At her mothers request, 911 was called. Upon their arrival, they performed an initial assessment in the store and then transported her to the ambulance for further assessment. After a short time the patient was released and returned home.   After the patient was released, her mother returned to the pharmacy to let us know that she was okay and was feeling much better. Additionally, she recalled that patient had had a similar but less severe response to the flu shot last year. Sh had complained of her ears popping and generally not feeling well.

I did not receive any vaccination information prior or after my vaccinations.  Approximately five days after the vaccinations ( I am unsure of which pneumonia shot I received).   I started with a shingle on the tip to right side of my nose.  A few days later another on the top of my nasal area.   A day or so later I received what appears to be a chicken pox on my right cheek.  At almost the same time I received a massive cold sore on my left upper lip inside and outside of the lip.   It was very painful and large.   I treated myself with alcohol swabs which I have always found worked good on any shingle.   I still have a small bit of the cold sore on my lip it is almost gone. I have been feeling very unwell and overall lethargic.  I am undergoing treatment for a possible urine infection and am also on Cephalexin twice daily but the clinic has not confirmed the infection as yet.  But last evening on the first of November I started to get up and my left front thigh was so painful it felt like someone hit me with a bat repeatedly on that front part of my thigh.  I took Ibuprophen two 200mg tabs.  It helped somewhat.  I was able to sleep.  Today I took one potassium over the counter pill thinking it might help and maybe I was dehydrated or something from the possible urine infection.  I did ok all day until this evening and I began feeling lethargic again and I have had GERD now for about three days or so.  I am very tired, my eyes are also bothering me, dry and they seem like they are somewhat infected and get blurry off and on during the day.   MY 91 year old mother received the same vaccine on the same day and she has been in her pajamas since the 14th not feeling well.  Her eyes both got red and dry and she also received a STY.  I took her to the Clinic and nurse had her seen by the eye clinic.   He asked How I was doing and I showed him my cold sore and said, "not good".  I do not want the second vaccine.
CUR_ILL: I get one to three shingles above the crack on my butt, left side.  I had just had only one shingle less than two weeks prior to the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The first symptom of a reaction was an acute pain at the base of my skull; then a sense of dizziness and "brain squeeze". It passed, and I began to feel slightly feverish. When I rose to walk out at the end of a 2 hour-class (sitting with 1 break an hour earlier when I walked easily) I had difficulty getting easily to my feet. I had to shuffle my feet to walk. No pain, but great stiffness. On the 30 minute drive home I suddenly began shivering and my teeth chattering; felt very cold, even though it was a warm evening. As soon as I got home I took my temperature (no fever) had a hot bowl of chicken rice soup, with a lot of soda crackers and the shivering slowed and stopped. I slept very soundly. Even though I could walk without shuffling, overall stiffness continued for about 7 weeks. The injection site continued to be painful, then very tender when touched through June 12.  Although I don't know if these are at all related, I add them here; perhaps new issue with my neck is related. August 4 I was diagnosed with a kidney infection at ER. (Was referred to ER I was in abdominal pain and it was late in the day.) August 8 I checked myself into the ER because I had pain in my abdomen that I thought was due to a recurred kidney infection. Test results for the infection were negative, however I felt increasingly anxious; enough to check myself back in after release given all clear on kidney infection. (I started to see double while driving, so I went back to ER.) The ER doc suspected vagus nerve interactions. My GP subscribed a current XRay of my back and neck and a course of physical therapy which seems to be helping with pain, cramping and dizziness/anxiety.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 10/24 the day following the shot in my left arm and 12 days following the bee sting in my right arm, the area of my bee sting started to itch again and got very red.  Additionally, my thighs started to itch.  By the evening of 10/24, the red area on my arm by my bee sting grew to about the length of my pinky and about half as wide.  It was pulsing dark red/light red with my heartbeat and I had broken out in a rash of small bumps on my thighs.  I treated the arm area with steroid cream and took oral benadryl before bed. I went to see my dermatologist the next morning 10/25 and he believed that my arm was infected, and as I thought, having the flu shot prompted a immune response and major histamine response due to the underlying infection of which I was unaware at the time I had the shot, given that the bee sting redness and swelling had apparently resolved days before the shot. He prescribed a 14 day regimen of Cephalexin which I am still taking and we agreed that I would continue steroid cream twice a day and take Benadryl at night given that I do not tolerate well most other antihistamines. The arm redness and swelling as well as the rash, which had spread to include the area between my waist and knees, worsened for about two days before gradually improving. I had a follow up appointment with Dr. on Friday, Nov 1 by which time the arm was mostly better and the rash had resolved. By today, Nov 3, other than slight discoloration in the area of the bee sting, all has resolved.
LAB_DATA: Swabbed culture take on 10/25 on skin surface was negative. Could have been a false negative or infection just under the skin.
OTHER_MEDS: Vit D, magnesium, probiotic, turmeric, milk thistle

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Unknown if the above is the exact type of quadrivalent influenza vaccine, but it was one of them. About 24 hours after receiving it, I came down with a series of somewhat non-specific but all very unusual symptoms, starting with each arm independently becoming very cold and almost numb, followed by general malaise and feeling "off", heart palpitations/heart racing, excessive thirst and urination (requiring drinking 24oz water bottles every 2 hours or so, much much higher than baseline - no matter how much I drank, I remained extremely thirsty and with dry mouth), excessive sweating on palms and soles of feet, chills and difficulty maintaining a comfortable temperature, inability to sleep, pallor, minor/occasional dry cough, stomach discomfort/mild nausea, loose stools x 2, all lasting from 4PM that afternoon the day after the vaccine until about 9-10AM the next day.  Symptoms seemed to fluctuate a little bit but were at a persistent level of malaise throughout. I had never previously experienced anything like this before and felt about the worst I have ever felt physically in my life.  I am a physician and had my vitals checked when I arrived to work around 7:30AM near the end of it, with elevated blood pressure to the 146/86 range (baseline systolic is 110-120s), afebrile.  I had a difficult time making it through work, but was able to do so starting to feel a little better.  By the time I proceeded to my physician's office that afternoon, I was feeling much better. In the proceeding 1-2 days, I have had a few much more minor episodes since of 30-60 min of feeling off sporadically.  The family physician and I both agreed these symptoms were most likely a delayed reaction to the influenza vaccine given time course and diffuse nature of symptoms.  I was tested for other possibilities such as a thyroid condition, with bloodwork unremarkable.  I do plan to continue receiving the flu vaccine in the future though of course this raises some natural concern.
LAB_DATA: CBC, Comp, TSH on 11/1/19 - essentially WNL (CBC just notable for RBC 5.22, slightly outside of reference range)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 9 months after receiving these vaccines, my son started having chronic joint and muscle pain in right thigh/groin area.  The pain was so debilitating, he was often unable to walk,  he would limp or crawl due to pain.  Almost a year later and after extensive testing,  a muscle biopsy revealed Macrophages and Aluminum crystals striated throughout my son?s right thigh muscle, in the same area her received his vaccines.  The biopsy results showed that my son has Macrophagic Myofasciitis (MMF),  caused by the aluminum in his 2017 DTaP vaccine.  He has chronic, debilitating pain that has spread throughout his body and now he also has pain in both legs, arms, feet and hands.  He?s been living with this pain for almost two years.
LAB_DATA: Oct 2018 - inflammation blood panel Nov 2018 - x-ray of hip/groin/right leg April 2019 - inflammation blood panel and autoimmune work up May 2019 - MRI (showed inflammation in thigh muscles of both legs, with more inflammation in right leg) July 2019 - Muscle Biopsy (positive for Macrophagic Myofasciitis MMF) September 2019- specialized inflammation blood panel

Detoxing & flushing system with the oregano tumerica, I called CDC 10/31 they gave me to Vares & this form. Starting my new job Nov 3 & Im miserable I need to sleep & relax. I was instructed to fill out this form & return to clinic that gave me the Tdap & have them report it. The Director insisted on me being seen by their Dr. I was seen by Dr. He prescribed me a muscle relaxer & prednisone. I explained to him this pain in my legs was from my waist thighs knees & to my feet. Its tight & heavy & stiff & difficult to lift up my legs & walk I tried to stretch & do exercise to help stimulate my circulation to get this out of my system. Injection site redness; Injection site itching; Difficulty taking a deep breath; Arm swollen; Arm warm to the touch; not doing well; Dizziness; This case was reported by a physician and described the occurrence of dizziness in a 28-year-old female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Quebec (FluLaval Tetra 2019-2020 season) (batch number 72RS4, expiry date June 2020) for prophylaxis.   On 24th October 2019 13:00, the patient received FluLaval Tetra 2019-2020 season. On 24th October 2019, less than an hour after receiving FluLaval Tetra 2019-2020 season, the patient experienced dizziness, difficulty breathing, swelling arm, skin warm and unwell. On 24th October 2019 13:50, the patient experienced erythema of extremities and injection site itching. The patient was treated with benadryl (nos) (Benadryl) and non-drug therapy (Ice Pack (No Medication)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the dizziness, erythema of extremities, injection site itching, difficulty breathing, swelling arm, skin warm and unwell were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the dizziness, erythema of extremities, injection site itching, difficulty breathing, swelling arm, skin warm and unwell to be related to FluLaval Tetra 2019-2020 season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Flu vaccine in the right arm. The patient received 50mg Benadryl intramuscularly in her right arm. The patient experienced redness and itching at the site of injection. No other complaints were noted. The patient had no difficulty in breathing or swelling anywhere. The patient was given ice and was told to monitor because all other systems were intact. The patient was told to follow up if the events get wore. At 14:00, the staff person from the front office called and told that the patient was not doing well. The physician went to the office with all the emergency supplies. The patient was sitting down and reported that she experienced difficulty taking a deep breath and felt dizzy. The patient's right arm looked more red, slightly swollen and warm to touch. At 14:21, EMS was called and it came at 14:25. The vital signs were the blood pressure was 124/91 mm hg and the heart rate was 94. At the time of reporting, the patient was fully cognitive and was aware of the situation. The patient's husband was notified about the events. The patient was then transferred to the hospital for follow-up with the ambulance at 14:35. The patient remained calm during the process. The case has been linked with case US2019AMR196157 reported by the same reporter.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: epidemitis; rheumatoid arthritis; massive immune response/immune cells attacking his healthy tissue/ autoimmune reaction to vaccine; near death reaction; fever; chills; difficulty eating; sick mainly due to the reaction from the shot; Could not drive; Bad shape; bad back pain; couldnot bend back; difficulty walking/difficult for him to walk in his kitchen; stiffness/ stiff hands; Joint pain; Shoulder pain; falling; shakes; poor memor; Mind not good; testicle pain; Sjogren's syndrome; dry eyes; dry throat; Lucid; Sleeping a lot; tingling/ every toe was tingling on each feet; numbness/ toes, feet and ankles were numb; nerve damage; peripheral neuropathy; shooting pain/ pain all over the body; itching was consistent with a shingles reaction; unconscious/ passed out; coma; itching on various parts of his body/ was below the surface of skin; delirious; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of epididymitis in a 69-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included glaucoma and loss of vision. Concurrent medical conditions included blind left eye.   On 27th February 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). In February 2018, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced general body pain (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening), generalized pruritus (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening) and shingles (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening). In March 2018, the patient experienced peripheral neuropathy (serious criteria hospitalization, GSK medically significant and life threatening), tingling feet/hands (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening), numbness (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening), nerve damage (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening), lucid dreams (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening) and sleep excessive (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening). In April 2018, the patient experienced sjogren's syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization, GSK medically significant and life threatening), eye dryness (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening) and dry throat (serious criteria hospitalization and life threatening). Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix in the left arm. The patient had a history of glaucoma in left eye and total loss of vision before the vaccination. The patient had a really bad near death reaction 1 and 1/2 hours after the vaccination and was unconscious and in a coma for 5 days and was delirious for another two days after. Less than a week affter getting the vaccine, the patient woke up with shooting pain up the spine that went to his shoulders. Second time he came to consciousness he was awake and experienced fevers and chills.  Then he slept again and woke up with severe pain all over the body and he passed out because of the pain.  He stated that he had difficulty eating for 2 weeks after getting the Shingrix vaccine. Initially less than a month after receiving the shot, he had itching on various parts of his body that was below the surface of the skin. It was went away after a month or two which was consistent with a reaction to the shot and might be shingles. The patient had been really sick and partially from some outside things but mainly due to the reaction from the shot. The patient also reported that, every toe was tingling on each feet and the tingling was matching on both feet for months and then it stopped and his toes, feet and ankles were numb. The numbness was 5 to 6 inches above his ankles and was exactly in the same area on both feet. The patient described it as, when toes went numb he knew it was neurological which occurred 7 days after the vaccination. He had symptoms a half hour after the vaccine but his physician did not believe there was a correlation and denied that it could have happened. That physician had since retired, the patient saw another doctor who said it was impossible even though he was unconscious after getting the shot.  The patient's doctor had told him that, he had peripheral neuropathy in the fall of 2018. His left hand shakes all the time that began in the fall of 2018 and he could not rely on it.  There was nerve damage present on his left and right hand and both hands were shaking, but the left hand was much worse. The patient was lucid and sleeping a lot after 7 days from the reaction with matching tingling toes.  Less than 4 months after the vaccine, the patient could not drive and was in bad shape until early April 2018. The patient also reported bad back pain that was really serious. It was so bad that he could not plant his garlic in the greenhouse without laying on his side because he could not bend his back. This started in late April or early May 2018 but it eased up after physical therapy and he got dry needling which miraculously cured his back pain. He also had stiff hands in the fall of 2018.   In April 2018 less than 3 months after getting the Shingrix, the patient started to experience dry throat and dry eyes. He related these symptoms to an immune response called Sjogren's syndrome. The back pain was located in his lower back and he had another back reaction in late fall and in April, May and June of 2019 also he had another flare up. In May 2019 less than 4 months after the vaccination, in the course of 1 to 2 weeks he had symptoms of rheumatoid arthritis including joints in both feet and made it difficult for him to walk in his kitchen with numbing in his skin and the connective tissue of his feet. The numbness was below the skin in the connective tissue and when he pressed hard he felt the ligaments and bones in the deep parts of the foot. It started to hurt with the arthritis symptoms which had continued till the date of reporting. The patient had a period in 2019 where everything started to get worse including his back pain. The patient was experiencing a massive immune response which he believed was related to the shot. He had an ongoing immune issues like immune cells attacking his healthy tissue and his feet are numb with various health problems. If he had immune response symptoms flare ups, which he had on and off, his back would start hurting again. The symptoms had bilateral symmetry in both feet which still continued.   He also experienced joint pain that was episodic which began months after his autoimmune reaction and had been getting worse since April 2019. He has had difficulty walking and stumbled and fall when turning to do something. He falls at least once a month and has been getting worse since April of 2019. Less than a year of vaccination and a few months later after having an autoimmune reaction to the Shingrix, the patient's testicles hurt bad that he had to go to emergency room and they flared up again. The patient again went to emergency room in early September of 2019 and July of 2019.   This condition he described as Epididymitis as per his urologist. Urologist had suggested him to use ice packs and ibuprofen. On the day before the reporting date, the patient had an episode for 3 to 4 hours and took acetaminophen and ibuprofen which helped.   After couple of weeks of vaccination, the patient's mind had not been good since getting the vaccine. He had been experiencing poor memory weeks after getting the vaccine. The patient consented to follow up and also provided his physician's details.

don't spit up sputum maybe once in a while; pneumococcal pneumonia; pneumococcal pneumonia; COPD; shortness of breath; had a pain in my side; sweat a lot; no energy; diabetes; This is a spontaneous report from a Pfizer-sponsored program. A contactable consumer (patient) reported that the female patient of an unspecified age received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date at single dose for immunisation. The patient medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient had got pneumococcal pneumonia twice in a row within two months. Her last doctor in the hospital, the second hospital, put her into a breathing unit. And the doctor thought she had got chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). The patient had diabetes too and it came on suddenly. The patient didn't cough at all. The patient had a pain in her side and she sweated a lot. And shortness of breath and no energy. For the first time she was in the hospital for two weeks. Two months later she had the same thing happen to her all at once. And again she was sweating. She had pain in her side once in a while. Shortness of breath. No energy. And she was in the hospital for four days. That doctor sent her out oxygen unit home with her that she could not get rid of because the doctor thought she had COPD. The patient was at the moment undergoing lung tests to verify what she had because she didn't want it to happen again. As she said it was very sudden, she had no colds, she didn't wheeze. She didn't spit up sputum maybe once in a while. And she did spit up some for the hospital, the last hospital, but they never got it in the lab. The patient believed this was bacterial and not viral. The outcome of events was unknown.   No follow-up attempts are possible, information about batch number cannot be obtained.

The evening of the day the child received the vaccines, they started running a fever. The next day the child complained of their head and neck hurting. After two days of fever and complaints of a stiff neck and sore head, the child was taken to the local ER. Many tests were done and it was discovered that there was something in the neck. The child was transported to a hospital where they were admitted for 5 days. The diagnosis was a retropharyngeal abscess. The child received IV antibiotics and had interventional radiology done to drain the abscess. The child had no previous illness before receiving the vaccine. The child was also diagnosed with the RHino virus and Strep throat at the ER.
LAB_DATA: 10/13 -10/18/2019 Blood work and imaging and then interventional radiology to drain the abscess. Patient spent 5 days in the hospital on IV antibiotics.

On Friday started feeling bad, around 8am, patient noticed the redness on site; there was a red streak 3 inches long coming down from site, bicep completely red and had elevated temperature.  It was red enough that patient thought it looked like inflammation.    Patient called vaccine administrator and took Tylenol 650; patient felt better somewhat.   Patient went to doctor and specified it was not coming from vaccination site.  Doctor asked whether patient had low immune system and specified it was strep under the skin.  Doctor specified that it was not contagious and prescribed generic Augmentin. Patient felt better after taking antibiotic; it lasted for 5 days.   The redness slowly went away,   went to doctor on 10/30, because redness was still there and told that did not need more antibiotics. By yesterday patient felt better.   Today, only a little bit of redness remains.    Today patient not feeling great and not sure whether related vaccine or not.   Reaction to Flu vaccine in 2009 was similar but much worse; redness and warmth were similar but did not take any antibiotics.   Patient did not have carcinoma at the time but lung infection micro bacteria avian complex. Patient has received Flu vaccines after that year with no problems

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HISTORY: (1) November 27, 2018 called the eye Dr. - Horrible Headaches - Left eye was drooping - (also called Retina Dr) (2) November 28th : Went for eye check up - Dr suggested testing -  prescribed: Valtrex, Neurontyn, + topical Durezol drops. (3) November 29th : Pain increased - double vision starting - eye drooping further - went to Emergency Room at Medical Center. They suggested CT scans and MRI. (CT scan had already been done the day before) came back normal. (4) December 3rd : office visit with Dr - he tentatively diagnosed 3rd cranial nerve palsy - (5) December 5th 2 MRI's were done, they came back normal - (no growths or tumors.) (6) December 7th office visit with Dr - his diagnosis was : Pupil Sparing non compression partial third nerve palsy. (A) Continue with Neurontin - ( times per day). (B) Put patch on the eye glasses to aid with double vision. (7) December 17th Dr suggested neuro ophthalmologist visit. (8) January 3rd office visit with Dr, neuro othamologist he agreed with Dr's diagnosis-+ suggested a timeline of 3-6 months for spontaneous recovery. (9) Condition lasted for 3 1/2 months til March 11, 2019-> eye not 100% yet. Doctors mentioned in the previous page time line are: (1) Eye doctor (office visits were on :) 11/28.2018 11/30/2018 12/03/2018 12/07/2018 12/17/2018 Jan 3, 2019

SYMPTOM_TEXT: improperly stored vaccine administered; No adverse effect; This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant regarding unspecified patients of unknown demographics. The patient's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications and drug reactions or allergies were not reported. On an unknown date (also reported as on multiple unspecified dates), the patients were vaccinated with improperly stored rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent(ROTATEQ) (Strength, dose, frequency and anatomical location were not reported) intramuscularly of lot # R016791 with an expiry date of 16-APR-2020 for prophylaxis and hepatitis b vaccine (recombinant)(RECOMBIVAX HB) (Strength, dose, frequency and anatomical location were not reported) intramuscularly of lot # R007212 with an expiry date of 04-NOV-2020 for prophylaxis (Product storage error). No adverse effects were reported. It was reported that the vaccine was exposed to a temperature of 1.4 Celsius (C) for a time frame of 10 minutes. There was no previous temperature excursion reported. Data logger was involved. No product quality complaint (PQC) was associated with this report.  Follow-up information was received from a office manager on 01-NOV-2019. A call was placed to the medical assistant, but the pharmacist was no longer worked in the office. The phone was then transferred to the office manager who stated that there was no new information concerning the report and additionally there were no patient identifiers.  This is a non-valid case due to lack of patient identifiers.

By the time 8 hours had lapsed, my arm was paralized to the point that I could not lift it without using my other arm and hand to do so.  The pain was sharp in the shoulder joint the migrated down the length of my arm into my hand.   This severity level continued for four days. What sleep I got was sitting up. On October 24, I notified Dr. via message board. She called but offered no suggestions for pain relief or any ideas about regaining movement. Nor did she have any suggestions about how long the condition might persist.  By October 30, I was able to sleep in bed again and movement is pretty much back to normal although pain in the area below the injection site remains.

Within a few hours of receiving vaccine, child had a small area of localized redness & swelling. Over the next 2 days, he had increasing redness & swelling. 10/31 he had marked increase in redness & swelling - annular 10cm & was seen at a minor Er. Child had been on amoxicillin for an URI with cough. ER left him on amoxicillin. I saw patient the next day and opted to cover possible cellulitis with cephalexin. Area was quite red but was not particularly tender to touch & child was not limping. He did have some fever & flu like symptoms but I did not test him for flu. Child improved over the next days & a phone call to mom on 11/4/19 reported almost complete resolution of erythema. Mom denied that child ever had a noteable scratch in the area of the injection. She did not feel child fought the injection or had significant bruising at the time of the injection. Child has had 3 previous flu shots on 10/17, 1/18,10/18 without any significant reaction. Those vaccines were all fluzone quadirvalent but were the 0.25 dose. (This was the 0.5ml dose). I am not sure whether this was cellulitis or a severe local reaction but thought it should be reported since this was the first year to give children under 3 the higher dose.

Patient was given a flucelvax 0.25mg instead of the fluzone .5mg. We didn not have any state fluzone in stock at the time and that is why Dr. decided to have the child receive .25 of the flucelvax. I called the CDC and spoke to staff on 10/31/2019 he stated it was not harmful and often times can be ignored. Not a live vaccine. Patient does need to return for the fluzone .5mg because last year was her first dose but she only received one dose instead of two. Mom was notified baby was fine, no side effects and will bring her in for the fluzone.

The patient's arm swelled up and became very red.  It was warm to the touch and the spot was from the shoulder down to the forearm region of her right arm.  The patient went to her doctor's office on Saturday (11/02/19) and was give scripts of prednisone and keflex because to them it looked more like a case of cellulitis instead of an adverse reaction to the vaccine.  The patient wasn't convinced of their diagnosis and didn't take the antibiotic.  She did take the prednisone and when counseled asked for me to report the event.   Upon speaking with the patient today at 1pm, she stated that her arm was back to normal..

Immediately after receiving the shot, my son complained about a headache and "not feeling right." He went back to school, but as he came home the same afternoon he said he still did not feel well. We decided to go to hockey practice that evening and "sweat it out." Looking off and sluggish the entire practice, his head slumped forward in the car on the way home. This was his first seizure. It is now around 7,20 p.m. the same day he received Gardasil 9. He is still suffering from these seizures to this day.
LAB_DATA: MRI, EEGs are according to Neurologists "squeaky clean."

Transient global amnesia; short term memory loss; fever; nausea; fatigue; dizziness; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of transient global amnesia in a 74-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. Additional details were provided as follows: Seven days after vaccination, the patient experienced short term memory loss and was admitted to hospital for observation and was diagnosed with transient global amnesia (TGA). The patient was discharged on 26th October 2019. Less than 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient expereinced some dizziness. The reporter consented to follow up.

cellulitis; Elbow bursitis; swelling; pain; headache; couldn't sleep; could not extend his arm/ he could not lift weights for the past 5 weeks; two areas of numbness in his hand and up and down his thumb and across the lower half of a finger or two fingers and across the base of the finger; purple; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of cellulitis in a 21-year-old male patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season) (batch number 99CA4, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis.   On 25th September 2019 01:45, the patient received the 1st dose of Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season (intramuscular). On 26th September 2019, 1 days after receiving Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season, the patient experienced skin discoloration. On an unknown date, the patient experienced cellulitis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), elbow bursitis, swelling, pain, headache, sleeplessness, movements reduced and numbness of extremities. The patient was treated with ibuprofen and steroids nos (Steroid Injection). On an unknown date, the outcome of the cellulitis, movements reduced and numbness of extremities were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the elbow bursitis was recovering/resolving and the outcome of the swelling, pain, skin discoloration and sleeplessness were unknown and the outcome of the headache was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the cellulitis, elbow bursitis, swelling, pain, skin discoloration, headache, sleeplessness, movements reduced and numbness of extremities to be related to Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient's mother reported that her son received the Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 vaccine on an unknown arm and within 24 hours, he experienced a ball at the tip of his elbow which she claims was swollen. He received the vaccine at 1:45 PM and he had a headache that came on early that lasted a few days. She called the ball on his elbow elbow bursitis and it caused him so much pain that he said that he needed a pain killer but he did not typically take medications so he took a lot of Ibuprofen and he was up all night and could not sleep. The following day he started to experience swelling down through his lower hand and the hand was turning purple. The patient went to the urgent care and they diagnosed him with cellulitis. They administered a steroid injection on 28th September 2019, that reduced the swelling on Saturday night. The injection also helped with the pain but the swelling took longer to resolve on his elbow. The ball on his elbow has gotten smaller but it is still present and moving around.  The patient's elbow cellulitis was still not resolved and he could not lift weights for the past 5 weeks.  The patient claimed that this was due to the stress from his tricep tendon that he could not extend and workout. The patient could not extend his arm.  The patient was also experiencing two areas of numbness in his hand and up and down his thumb and across the lower half of a finger or two fingers and across the base of the finger. The mother could not confirm which arm her son received the vaccination on or what side of the body his side effects are affecting. The reporter consented to follow up.

The patient wrote out a letter describing what happened to her.  She brought it to us at the pharmacy on 11/2/19.  Here's what she wrote: "Saturday, October 26th.  Normal day out and about running errands.  That evening took 1.5 hour ride to visit with family.  It was on the way home that I started to feel achy and tired.  Went to bed around 10pm. Around 3am, Sunday morning, I woke up and needed to go to the bathroom.  My hips ached and were tight - hard to move.  Rolled to my side and put my feet on the floor.  Once I stood up the pain was very bad.  The pain went up my entire body.  Tried to sit on the steps beside the bed.  Still very painful.  My husband woke up to help me.  Tried to turn and get back into bed and slid down the bed and hit my face on the bedside table.  It didn't bruise, but it hurt.  My husband got me up and I was in so much pain I started getting sweaty and clammy.  I couldn't explain what was going on.  He wanted to call an ambulance, but I didn't.  I told him I would get through this.  He helped me back in the bed.  I tried to stretch out the pain.  Finally able with his assistance was able to go to the bathroom.  Hard to sit down and then stand back up.  Finally able to go back to sleep. 9am Sunday morning (Oct 27th).  Tired, but able to move on my own.  Did stretches throughout the day to work it out.  Monday through Wednesday - ached some in the morning but throughout each day it would get better the more i moved.  Thursday and Friday I had little to no weird feelings.   Saturday November 2nd, 2019.  Woke up felt great.  Can't explain what caused this but scary."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in to get a flu shot. She is 24 years old, so she should have gotten the Fluzone Quad. I mistakenly gave her the Fluzone HD. I personally spoke to her provider, PA and her supervisor, Dr. They indicated that she may experience increased side effects, but that was it. I called the patient personally and let her know what happened as well as repeated my conversation with PA and Dr. I reassured her that she would be fine, but may exhibit increased side effects (headache, pain at injection site, fever, redness at injection site.

Patient felt fine but stressed prior to vaccination of shot. Family going through medical trouble and talking about house burning down during vaccine (anxiety trigger in her past). Other than stress, patient was ok. Gave patient Boostrix. Administration went according to protocol. Asked patient to sit for 15 minutes and she started reporting dizziness and hand tremor. Asked patient to lay down and she refused. Asked if mouth felt tingling or swelling and it did not at first. I suggested she take one of her anxiety alprazolam to relax. Patient started getting more stressed as we talked and then reported her lips started to feel tingly. She reported half of her tongue does go numb when she smells certain smells. I stated that we do have many different scents in our store as we are a gift store. I asked if she would like me to call 911 as her mouth was starting to tingle and I stated I would prefer her have a reaction in the ER (1 block away) than in our store so she could get proper medical treatment. She refused. I asked if I could get her husband here and went out to their truck and informed husband of the situation. He came in and drove her to the ER. Prior to them leaving, I contacted the local ER and gave them a rundown of the events leading up to their admission. Followed up with clinic every hour times 2 when patient was sent home. She received benadryl IV and relaxed. Dr did not report anaphylaxis.
LAB_DATA: ER did not report any tests were completed to me.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Body aches; When he got home he was complaining of site pain / any pressure was very painful; he received both vaccines in the same arm since he needed to be held down to receive the injections; The mother reports the reaction looked like cellulitis because it was red, indurated, hot and growing; Injection site celullitis; the injection site was bruised; lethargic; This spontaneous report was received from a nurse who was the mother of the patient, referring to a 9-year-old male patient. The patient's concurrent conditions included a drain due to recurrent perirectal abscesses. He had a history of recurrent infections where he complained of joint pain, leg pain and body aches when the infection was bacterial. He also had a history of some "titers" that showed he was not immune to pneumonia or tetanus (+) diphtheria (+) pertussis (reported as "TDap"). Concomitant medications were not provided.   On 21-OCT-2019 at 16:30, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) in the deltoid (dose, frequency, route, lot/batch # and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis, at the same time, he was vaccinated with tetanus (+) diphtheria (+) pertussis (reported as "TDap") in the deltoid (dose, frequency, route, lot/batch # and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis, this vaccine was administered just 1 inch apart from the previous one, in the same arm (unspecified) since he needed to be held down to receive the injections (product administered at inappropriate site). The patient did not have any active infection at the time of vaccination.   On the same date in the evening, the injection site was bruised (vaccination site bruising). On 22-OCT-2019, the injection site was a little red and puffy which the mother considered normal injection site reactions; at 15:00, the mother was called to pick him up from school program due to headache, body aches (pain), chills and fever. The injection site at this that was also very red and swollen but maybe only "3 by 3". The site was getting hot and red. When he got home, he was complaining of site pain (vaccination site pain) so ibuprofen and acetaminophen (TYLENOL) were given to treat the pain. He was also given an ice pack to reduce swelling, redness, warmth and pain. Any pressure was very painful. At about 23:00, he had the maximum dose of ibuprofen and acetaminophen (TYLENOL) and spike a 102.9 (units not provided) fever. He was given a tepid bath and the fever reduced to 102.1 (units not provided). He was given acetaminophen (TYLENOL) 15 minutes early which reduced the fever until 23-OCT-2019 at about 03:00, when his fever was 102.8 (units not provided) and climbing so he was given ibuprofen and acetaminophen (TYLENOL) an hour early. Around 05:30, his fever broke, and he developed sweats. The acetaminophen (TYLENOL) and ibuprofen were continued to prevent fever, but the injection site was growing from the size of a plum to the size of a baseball. On the same date, he was given 25mg of diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) to see if this would work and help, and hydrocortisone cream was putted on the injection site but the diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) and hydrocortisone did nothing. On 24-OCT-2019, he was seen by his primary care provider (PCP) who stated the reaction was local and was now about "6 by 7". The mother thought he was having a systemic reaction due to he was having malaise, body aches, headache, and being lethargic (lethargy). The mother reported the reaction looked like cellulitis (cellulitis - injection site cellulitis) because it was red, indurated, hot and growing. No treatment was given at that time. On the evening of that day, he started spiking fevers again over 102 (units not provided) so he was being treated with acetaminophen (TYLENOL) and ibuprofen (MOTRIN). The injection site reaction was also still growing. Therefore, on the same date, the reaction was "10 by 12". The doctor still did not think it was cellulitis but started him on cefalexin (KEFLEX) twice daily. The mother marked the injection with the largest point being "14.5 by 12". On 25-OCT-2019, the patient's fever broke again, and the injection site started to shrink within 12 hours of starting cefalexin (KEFLEX). At the time of the report (26-OCT-2019), the injection site reaction was shrinking, and he woke up for the first morning since vaccination without a fever. He was scheduled to received titers again in 3 weeks. It was unknown if he would continue pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) as he continued to experience symptoms though the symptoms were improving.   The outcome of cellulitis, vaccination site pain, pain, vaccination site bruising, injection site cellulitis and lethargy was reported as recovering.  The causality assessment between the events and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) or tetanus (+) diphtheria (+) pertussis (reported as "TDap") was not reported.   Upon internal review, the event of cellulitis was considered to be medically significant.
CUR_ILL: Perianal abscess drainage; Perirectal abscess; Prophylaxis
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Antibody test negative; Recurrent infection (where he complained of symptoms of joint pain, leg pain and body aches when the infection was bacterial.)
