Patient had never had a flu shot before, was not allergic to eggs, was feeling well today and had never had Gillian-Barre Syndrome.  He received his shot and sat with my for 15 min.  Reported feeling fine and left.  Following the above incident, he returned to the room stating ?I think I?m having a reaction, I feel like I?m tripping on acid, I feel off, my vision is blurry and I feel dizzy?.  I cleared the room, one employee choose not to leave, patient said it was fine.  Employee who did not leave reported that he was a first responder and wanted to stay in case I needed anything.  BP was 132/82, pulse was regular.  Pupils were equal, round and reactive.  Lung and heart sounds WNL. No other symptoms. Patient sat with me for a bit, then said he was going back to his office.  I requested that he let someone nearby know how he is feeling and let them check in on him, he said he would.  He returned to the room during the clinic and said he was a bit better.  Following the completion of the clinic, I checked in with him. Reported still having difficulty with his vision and felt off, but was OK, ?I do have an issue with vertigo, cutting caffeine out has helped. I still feel like I?m looking through things and not at them?  Reported being in treatment for 2 years for this issue, unable to find a cause.   I requested that he notify his PCP today and report the reaction, as well as not driving himself if he continued to have difficulty seeing.  Also recommended future vaccinations be administered at his medical home for observation following.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt presented two days after vaccine administration  to clinic concerned about tenderness, weakness, pain on back of neck, swelling, and redness on site of injections.

Within a few weeks of receiving my innoculation, I began to exhibit loss of muscle strength and control in my extremities.  I was having difficulties with basic functions such as walking, climbing stairs, holding a glass in one hand, picking up heavy items, etc.  I initially saw my internist, who ran a complete blood panel for 11 items.  All ranges were normal. Dr. referred me to a neurologist, who did a complete evaluation in January, 2019.  He was unable to identify the cause of the condition and discussed the possible need for nerve conduction tests if the condition did not resolve itself.  I had additional blood work done in March, 2019  by Dr. with no change in the results.  In May, 2019, Dr. performed a nerve conduction test and found no systemic issues.  However, my condition persisted without improvement.  It wasn't until I mentioned to Dr. that I had received a flu shot in October, 2018, about two weeks prior to the onset of my symptoms, that he suggested that my condition was the result of the innoculation - that my body was reacting as if it had the flu without all of the side effects. He suggested that my symptoms could take up to 9 months to resolve after the shot.  It wasn't until July, 2019, that I was nearly fully recovered.
LAB_DATA: Blood panel, December 6, 2018. Neurologist Visit:  January, 2019 Follow up blood work, March, 2019 Neurologist visit with nerve conduction test, May, 2019

Fibrous mass on lens.   Immediate treatment with Durezol to stop inflammation.  Also Alphagan, Phenylephrine, Cyclopentolate, Cosopt.  Also valtrex since herpes infection suspected. 10/27 Hypopyon clearly visible As of 11/05, synechnae have disappeared and IOP in low 20's.  Inflammation reduced, cloudiness reduced.  11/06 fibrous mass gone from lens.  Keratic precipitates gone.

Third dose of hepatitis B was given too early.  1st dose given on 1/17/19 2nd dose given on 3/5/19 3rd dose given on 5/1/19  There had to be 16 weeks between dose one and dose three, but the third dose was given at 14 weeks and 6 days.   Reviewed the Agency information that was printed back on 4/30/19. The Agency information said that the the accelerated date for hepatitis B is 4/30/19, which is incorrect. The right accelerated date was 5/9/19. Confirmed that the Agency was having a bug in their system around Spring/Summer of 2019 and was forecasting wrong accelerated and recommended dates for third dose of hepatitis B vaccine.  RN called the mother and explained what happened. Mother verbalized understanding and agreed to have the patient redo the third dose of hepatitis B on 11/7/19 to ensure immunity.    No adverse reaction has happened from this incident.

Patient received her MMR vaccine during her 1 year well visit on 3/24/2016 Manufacturer MERCK L033589 Until this time, she was on track with her milestones. Started crawling at 5 months, walking at the age of 10 months, had good appetite, overall was in good health with no concerns. She was saying simple 1 syllable words ?mama , dada?). Per pediatrician notes on the 12 months visit MD said ?well baby, no concerns, on track with her development?.  After receiving MMR vaccine on 3/24/2016 she became lethargic later that night and had a low grade fever of 101 (which was explained to us was ?normal?). She was still very tired and irritable the following day and had very poor appetite. These symptoms continued until the following week. And even though her fever resolved, her energy level was not the same.   My husband and I noticed that patient was not the same child anymore.  Her appetite became very poor, she didn?t make any progress in her vocabulary (at 15 months she was still saying 1 syllable words).  At out 18 months visit, pediatrician was concerned with poor appetite and sleep, along with bad temper tantrums. She also didn?t make much progress with her speech, her vocabulary only consisted of 4-10 words per her chart records. Per MD note ?patients has some behavioral issues?.   At 2 year follow up, she really was behind on her speech, still only used simple words and no sentences, and only gained 1 pound since 18 months follow up visit. She also developed GI symptoms, constipation, hard stools and her appetite didn?t improve since previous visit. Per pediatrician notes ?developmental and behavioral issues? were noted at that time. We had another follow up visit with Dr. on August 3rd, 2017 regarding patient?s very poor appetite and developmental delay issues. Per MD after visit summary ?growth and eating concerns, as well as speech concerns were noted?. At 2 years 6 months patient?s speech really didn?t progress, she only used simple words and rarely combined them into sentences, her articulation was quiet poor as well. So Dr. referred us to speech therapist for an evaluation. Per initial speech therapist evaluation, on 09/26/2017, patient had expressive language disorder and articulation disorder. Her expressive language skills were consistent with that of an 18 months old and receptive language skills of an 21 months old. Her vocabulary was reduced and she did not consistently combined words into phrases. She also demonstrated decreased oral motor range of motion when producing words. Per speech therapist summary, difficulties in these areas have negatively impacted patient?s ability to functionally communicate her needs and wants in her daily life. And speech therapy was initiated at twice a week sessions.  At the age of 3, patient was only able to use 3-4 words sentences with very poor articulation. We are still seeing therapist for speech therapy weekly. Patient is still behind in her development, she is 4.5 now, and even though her vocabulary and speech improved since our initial evaluation, she is still behind in articulation with speech equivalent of a 3 year old. Her appetite is still very poor and she still has a lot of behavioral concerns, as well  GI issues (constipation, recurring enemas and Miralax use daily). At this point, we saw GI specialist Dr. as well as nutritionist with very little improvement.
LAB_DATA: Diagnostics solutions/ GI map Stool sample- 10/04/2019 CBC- 10/22/2019 Methalation/Neuropsych profile test-10/11/2019  Vibrant Wellness- wheat zoomer/intestinal permeability -10/22/2019

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received 3 shots of the HPV ( Gardasil ) Vaccine. Previously completely healthy girl with zero health issues, few days after receiving first dose her health rapidly deteriorated. Patient developed excruciating bladder pain, difficulty urinating, urgency to urinate, feeling of not being able to empty bladder, burning pain in bladder during urination and during regular daily activities as well. Suffered through 7 months of horrible pain. Finally diagnosed with Interstitial Cystitis. No cure, no medicine for this disease. Patient has been in constant pain for 3 years. Pain in both arms at the location where shots were given. This pain still exists today after 3 years. Electric-like shocks that start at the location where shots were given and theses shocks radiate down the arms.  Gravely disrupted menstrual cycle. Excruciating headaches. Highest level of anxiety (Diagnosed). Depression (Diagnosed). Excruciating stomach aches. Heart palpitations. Ear popping. Numbness and tingling in left side of face. Feeling of not being able to breathe. Feeling of something stuck in throat. Pain that randomly jumps from one site to others throughout the body. Patient had an adverse reaction 2-3 weeks after each shot; she developed a very painful, hard, red-purple, big bulge at the injection sites that lasted for weeks.
LAB_DATA: Bladder Scoping - Interstitial Cystitis Diagnosed Gastroscopy -For stomach pain Therapy - Highest level of anxiety and depression diagnosed Ultrasounds for uterus pain

acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM); headache worsened; nausea; photosensitivity; vomiting; lethargic; speaking in tongues as if she was possessed; extremely disoriented; could not follow commands or respond appropriately; diffuse hyperreflexia; ankle clonus bilaterally; short-term memory and balance; some problems with balance; Initial information received on 30-Oct-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from a Literature article.  Abstract:  Case Presentation: A 62 year old woman with a history of hypertension suddenly developed a headache starting 3 days after receiving the influenza vaccine. The headache worsened and was associated with nausea, photosensitivity and vomiting. The next day she was lethargic, and that night, her husband states she sat up in bed and started "speaking in tongues" as if she was "possessed". He brought her to the emergency room where she was extremely disoriented, could not follow commands or respond appropriately. Temperature was 101.2F on presentation, and remained afebrile afterward. She had diffuse hyperreflexia with ankle clonus bilaterally; otherwise exam was unremarkable. Serum white blood count was 12.2, ESR 51, CRP 3.40; anticardiolipin IgM and beta-2-glycoprotein were elevated. The remainder of serological studies were unremarkable, including anti-NMDA antibodies, tick borne infections, autoimmune and viral studies. CT head and CTA of the head and neck were unremarkable. Lumbar puncture showed protein of 57, 87 white blood cells and 36 red blood cells; glucose was normal. Other cerebrospinal fluid tests including herpes virus and oligoclonal bands were negative. MRI brain demonstrated multifocal ovoid and serpiginous areas of diffusion restriction and T2/FLAIR hyperintensities in the bilateral mesial temporal lobes, frontoparietal white matter, thalamus, putamen, and globus pallidus; this was thought most consistent with acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM). She was briefly treated with IV acyclovir (until HSV PCR was found to be negative), and IV steroids for 5 days followed by prednisone taper over about 1 month. Her mental status improved dramatically each day; score on montreal cognitive assessment (MOCA) test was 19/30 on discharge. At follow up 1 month after presentation, she complained of some problems with short-term memory and balance, but was otherwise back to normal. Examination demonstrated MOCA of 26/30, difficulty with tandem gait, and mild hyperreflexia without clonus; neurologic exam was otherwise normal. Cardiolipin IgM was borderline-positive, ESR 13, CRP 2.2, and beta-2-glycoprotein was negative. Repeat MRI demonstrated resolution of diffusion restriction and improvement in the size and number of T2/FLAIR hyperintensities without any new lesions. Discussion: ADEM is an inflammatory demyelinating disease of the central nervous system. The assumed mechanism is immunemediated demyelination triggered by infection, or, rarely, vaccination. For most vaccines, incidence rates of ADEM are as low as 0.1 to 0.2 per 100,000 vaccinated individuals. A search from 1979 to 2013 showed only 3 cases of seasonal influenza vaccine associated with ADEM. As such, there have been no large population studies with estimated incidence rates yet. Lesion patterns often seen in ADEM include widespread, multifocal lesions in the white and deep grey matter, as seen in our patient. Conclusions: Significant spontaneous recovery is the expected outcome in most cases of vaccine-induced ADEM, usually occurring within 1-6 months. Based on the current literature, it is difficult to predict who may be at risk. The risk must be balanced by the fact that influenza infection itself is a risk factor for ADEM, which is likely more common than that triggered by the vaccine. We do not advocate avoiding any vaccinations, but wish to promote awareness of this potential complication, as early identification and treatment may improve outcomes, and avoid unnecessary testing and treatment  This case involves a 62 years old female patient who experienced acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (adem) (Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis), short-term memory (Amnesia) and balance (Balance disorder), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA VACCINE. Employee declined going to ED and when hives persisted and increased in intensity the following day and she started to complain of a scratchy throat- she finally agreed to be seen in Urgent Care/ED for further treatment. Received the following in ED-  Famotidine 20mg IM x 1, Methylprednisolone 125mg x 1, and Diphenhydramine 25mg x1 Sent home with following meds: Famotidine 20mg BID x 7 days, Prednisone 20mg BID x 7 days and Benadryl 25mg Q6hrs/prn (all po) The employee took Benadryl 10/25 with no relief and then was seen in ED on 10/26 and treated as above. Symptoms then took about 5 days to finally resolve- completed treatment with no residual symptoms noted.  Advised of Flu vaccine allergy and not to receive flu vaccine going forward.

The subject's obstetrical history included one previous full-term live birth. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's relevant medical history included anemia. The concomitant medications of the subject included folic acid as vitamin and OB Complete (as reported) for vitamin obstetrics (OB) care and anemia.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 24-Jun-2019, the estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 30-Mar-2020 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was not reported. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 12-Sep-2019, approximately at 11 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Flucelvax QIV) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 261200, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] for an influenza immunization (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy').  On the same day, after vaccination, the subject experienced nausea and started therapy with Bonjesta (doxylamine succinate and pyridoxine hydrochloride) one tablet administered two times per day via oral route.   On an unknown date, after vaccination, the subject's pregnancy status was collected, and unspecified pregnancy complication was noted. No further details were provided.  At the time of initial reporting, the patient had not recovered from nausea, while the outcome of unspecified pregnancy complication was not reported.   The case was assessed as serious.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  Company comment: The subject experienced nausea and complication of pregnancy after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of anaemia and pregnant state may provide alternative aetiology for the events. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Associate gave me your information to contact you regarding several issues I have been experiencing since my flu shot was administered on October 3rd. On Friday, October 4th I began to feel fatigued and experienced some discomfort in my throat. On Saturday the throat discomfort, not exactly a sore throat but generally feeling like something was going on. This continued on Sunday the 6th and worsened on Monday the 7th. I continued feeling fatigued and having some discomfort in my throat through the remainder of the week including a fever and went home early on Tuesday, was off sick on Wednesday and then worked through Thursday and Friday. By Monday the 14th whatever was causing the issues in my throat moved to my chest turning into an upper respiratory infection and fever. I was off work two days that week and on vacation Thursday and Friday but remained very ill with fever, chills, coughing, but with no congestion I have had some issues catching my breath during coughing fits to the point where my husband was ready to call 911 in the middle of the night. About a week ago I noticed tenderness in the upper quadrant of my right arm. I thought that maybe I had strained a muscle. It got to the point where it hurt to press down to write something. A couple of days ago my husband noticed a bruise in the area where the tenderness is and it was then I realized that it was right below the area where the flu shot was given. It appears that what I am dealing with is indeed muscle pain and deep tissue bruising. Today I still have a terrible cough and have all but lost my voice. While I am susceptible to upper respiratory infections, bronchitis, and pneumonia none of the symptoms I've experienced in the last month are similar to those that I have experienced with any of the conditions I've had with those illness. In addition the fatigue is unbearable at times. I just haven't felt well since before getting the flu shot. I hope I provided what you might need so that the lot can be reported. I know several other people who are having same issues as I am however they're not here where I work so I'm not sure what's causing the similarities. Let me know if you have any questions.  Handwritten notes 11/7/19, RPh, Severe coughing spells, Arm bruise, tender to touch. Mild vertigo after flu. Under Tx. 5 days of work missed. Has had Rxn in the past, ill for an different.
PRIOR_VAX: 20 yrs ago Ill for an extended period. This event is unlike previous

My son received his flu shot (no other vaccinations done at this time) around 10:40 in our Pediatricians office during flu shot clinic.  About 10 minutes after receiving his shot we were in the elevator and heard a thump behind us.  I turned around and my son was having a grand mal seizure on the floor of the elevator.  He was stiff, shaking and eyes were open and rolled back in his head.  I am a nurse (BSN) and I have training in recognizing a seizure.  It lasted about 30-45 seconds before he started to come to.  He doesn't remember what happened and was confused for a short time afterwards.  My husband picked him up and ran back upstairs to the Peds office where he was diaphoretic but didn't feel overly warm tp the touch.  I asked them to check a Blood Sugar which was reported to be 100.  His Blood Pressure remained low for a while afterwards and was dizzy when sitting up.  They monitored his BP for about 30 minutes afterwards until it returned to his norm and was able to sit without feeling that he needed to lay back down.  He was sleepy the reminder of the afternoon and by evening he felt himself again.  He was 100% healthy prior to getting flu shot, has received flu shots in prior seasons without reaction.  He has never had a reaction to any vaccine he has received and is up to date on all vaccines.  He has never had a seizure prior to receiving this flu shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He started to run a fever on 10/24/19 of 100.9 at 4pm. He did not eat and went to bed a few hours later with a temp of 101.5. He woke up at 4am not able to sleep still running a fever of 102.2. He complained his feet hurt. I took him to abovementioned Dr's Office on 10/25/19. They did an exam and stated it was just a virus. Took him home, alternating Tylenol and Motrin every 4 hours and his temp was not responding to the fever reducer. He continued to have a 102.9 temperature. He woke up at 4am on 10/26/19 screaming and crying saying his head hurt and his feet hurt. We noticed his lip was swollen 3x's the normal size. His lips where bright red and chapped. Both feet were swollen and with red blotches and even bruising on both ankles and toes. I took him to the abovementioned Dr's office Urgent care on 10/26/19 the practicing Dr examed him and diagnosed with Kawasaki's Disease. He called Dr. who was at Medical Center and he agreed his sypmtoms were consistent with Kawasaki's Disease. He also had a strawberry tongue, his hands and wrist were swollen and bruised looking, as well as swollen lymph nodes. He sent us immediately to Hospital to be admitted to PEdiatric ICU for Kawasaki's Disease. He had a treamtment of IVIG for 14hrs and his temperature broke that evening at 1am.  They kept us for 48hrs and on Monday 10/28/19 at 5pm he spiked another temperature of 102.2. They gave another dose of the IVIG treatment. He did not have another fever after the treatment on 10/29/19. He was discharged on 10/31/19. We spent 5 nights/ 6 days in the Hospital.  He continues to be fatigue quickly and not normal, as well as complaines his feet can still hurt at times. He will follow up with a cardiologist on 11/14 for hit 3 echocardigram and then will continue to have follow up appointments with a cardiologist.
LAB_DATA: He had a full lab work up daily in the Hospital.
OTHER_MEDS: Smarty Pants Kids Complete Multi and Omega 3's Daily Vitamins Sambucus Kids Elderberry Culturelle Probiotics for Kids

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 11/07/2019 This morning, at 9:30, I had a flu shot at store.  3 to 4 minutes after, I had a strange reaction. Face flushed,  a quickening pulse or anxiety feeling,  slight lightheadedness, light pain but with serious weakness in both legs spreading across my lower back. Lucky I had a shopping cart to assist me. Great difficulty in walking. Struggled to my car nearby and drove to my doctors office, Dr. I was immediately seen by a nurse who checked me for chest pain. None. But there was no doctor to see me, so I was directed to a walk-in clinic. I was now feeling somewhat improved. I approached the clinic small waiting room. There sat about a dozen people, half of them wearing masks. I declined and came home. Flushed face was improving and I was a little steadier on my feet. Took my blood pressure. 140/64 pulse 61 Now 4 hours later I am approaching normal but guarded. I am 80 and reasonably fit.
LAB_DATA: Lasted approx. 30 minutes. A little light headed and stepping cautious for a further 2 hours.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My flu vaccine was admin in my right shoulder, too high. The needle went in very easy without any pain until the medication was admin and there was a burning sensation. I experienced extreme pain and limited mobility within minutes of the administration. but pain began to increase to a point where I was unable to move my arm without being in severe pain. I was off work for several days for a planned period of time off. I sent a message to my Manager regarding the the extreme pain. I sought treatment from our employee health doctor who sent me for an MRI which showed:1 Supraspinatus tendinosis with mild to moderate partial-thickness undersurface tearing; 2 Mild infraspinatus tendinosis; 3 probably tear of the superior labrum 4 Moderate subcapularis tendinosis with intrasubstance tearing, 5 Mild proximal biceps tendinosis.  I have never had shoulder pain or an injury to my shoulder before. A referral was made to an orthopedic specialist, Dr who ordered physical therapy, Celebrex and oral steroid. The oral steroid relieved some pain and allowed me to sleep through the night. Physical therapy started with minimal relief. Celebrex allowed some relief but did cause stomach issues. When stopped severe pain returned and mobility again was very limited. A steroid injection was admin Nov 6. To this date, I still have pain in my right arm, throbbing continues; pain runs down my arm to my thumb. Physical therapy continues to this date.
Admitted, treated, and discharged at Hospital on 11-5-19 for intussusception.

Mom and dad tried behavior therapy, play therapy and had many visits to the pediatrician extremely concerned.  He was no longer carefree, and was no longer social. patient passed out; patient was shaking uncontrollably; patient had "painful muscle spasms, especially in his hand"/patient "could not move his fingers"; Information has been received from a medical assistant referring to a 16 years old male patient. The patient had no concomitant medication, pertinent medical history or allergies.  On 25-OCT-2019, the patient was administered a dose of hepatitis a vaccine, inactivated (VAQTA) (lot number S002460 and expiration date 15-MAY-2020; dose number was unknonw) intramuscularly in the left upper arm for health maintenance.         After administration of the vaccine on 25-OCT-2019, the patient did not wait 15 minutes for observation but got up and left shortly. On his way to the car, the patient passed out and was shaking uncontrollably. The reporter stated that the patient did not had a seizure but had painful muscle spasms, especially in his hand. Entire event lasted 20-30 minutes and during the event patient could not move his fingers. The patient was assessed at office and upon recovery was sent home on the same date.  No product quality complaint (PQC) was involved. No treatment was given for the events and no labs was performed. The patient sought medical attention. The causality assessment between the events and hepatitis a vaccine, inactivated (VAQTA) was not provided.  Upon internal review, the event passed out was determined to be medically significant.

cardiomegaly; Left Atrial enlargement; dizzy lightheaded, like she was going to faint; ransient viral illness, some arthralgia and myalgia; ransient viral illness, some arthralgia and myalgia; ransient viral illness, some arthralgia and myalgia; This spontaneous report was received from a physician and refers to a 68-year-old female patient. The patient's medical history included splenectomy performed 30 years ago and a pacemaker insertion. The patient's concurrent conditions included heart rhythm problem with pacemaker in place, high blood pressure, reflux, asthma and allergy to acetaminophen (+) hydrocodone bitartrate (NORCO) and peanuts. The patient's concomitant medications included procaterol hydrochloride (PROAIR), coenzyme q, fluticasone propionate (FLONASE), loratadine (CLARITIN), omega-3 fish oil, pravastatin sodium (PRAVACHOL), rivaroxaban (XARELTO), sacubitril (+) valsartan(ENTRESTO) and cimetidine (TAGAMET).  On 25-JUL-2019, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) injection (dose, route of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis as she was working in health care facility.  On an unknown date in 2019, the patient started to experience transient viral illness, arthralgia and myalgia. Due to aforementioned events, she missed some time from work. On 27-AUG-2019, the patient received the second dose of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) injection (dose, route of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported). On an unknown date in 2019, after the second dose of the vaccine, the patient experienced arthralgia, myalgia and dyspnea. She again missed some time from work due to these symptoms. Computed tomography (CT) completed on 29-AUG-2019, showed cardiomegaly and left atrial enlargement. The physician reported that the patient was given sacubitril (+) valsartan (ENTRESTO) as treatment for cardiomegaly and left atrial enlargement. On 04-SEP-2019, the patient went to an emergency room (ER) due to a two-week history of chest pain which worsened with deep breathing and exertion. She also complained of feeling dizzy, lightheaded, like she was going to faint. On the same day, the patient was admitted to a hospital. The reporter stated that the patient was discharged within 48 hours. An echocardiography (ECHO) performed on 17-OCT-2019, showed that the patient had an ejection fraction (EF) of 20 percent. The physician highlighted that an ECHO performed on 17-JUN-2019 showed 60 percent EF. On 30-OCT-2019, the patient was admitted to the same hospital due to shortness of breath. The physician stated that the patient received an unspecified treatment during her stays in the hospital. At the reporting time, the patient had not recovered from the events and it was unknown if she had been discharged from the hospital.   The causality assessment was not provided. The physician stated that the events caused significant disability or incapacity, and he considered the events of cardiomegaly and left atrial enlargement as life-threatening.  Upon internal review, the events of cardiomegaly and left atrial enlargement were determined to be medically significant.

SHINGLES; The area started to itch; Red patch on her right shoulder that was itchy and red; Right shoulder began to hurt; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of shingles in a 75-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (first time was below her elbow on her right side, second time was on the left side of her stomach, 3rd time was on her left arm and fourth time was on her left hand). Concurrent medical conditions included arthritis.   On 16th October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season. Muscle pain around middle and back that felt like back labor; Muscle pain around middle and back that felt like back labor / hurt my back; Muscle pain around middle and back that felt like back labor; Muscle pain around middle and back that felt like back labor; Muscle pain around middle and back that felt like back labor; Migraine; Vomiting; Could not get out of bed; Headache; Could not eat / had to leave work / missed 1 1/2 days work; Couldn't sleep; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of muscle pain in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Shingrix (1st dose received on an unknown date and had no problems).   On 28th October 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. In October 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced sleeplessness. On 29th October 2019, the patient experienced muscle pain, back pain, skin peeling, feeling abnormal, difficulty in standing, migraine, vomiting, bedridden, headache and activities of daily living impaired. Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. On monday afternoon, the patient received second Shingrix vaccination. The patient had been warned with the standard warning. The patient had never a problem with any vaccinations before nor or had problems with the first.  1 day after receiving Shingrix, it took her out.  The patient had to leave work and stay out a second day.  It was the most bizarre thing the patient had ever felt. The first thing the patient felt was muscle pain around her middle and back that felt like back labor.  The patient told that she was not kidding. The patient could not stand up.  Then the patient got the migraine. Less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient could not sleep and nothing alleviated it aal the night. When the patient got up, she tried to go to work figuring and had just hurt her back and that my being out of it was the result of no sleep. The patient started vomiting half way through my work day. The patient  left and could not get out of bed or eat for that day and overnight. The headache began to be alleviated by motrin the morning after vaccination but the patient was afraid to take it because it might upset me stomach more. This was not a mild side effect.  When the patient actually looked it up with the cdc, 1 in 6 will had this kind of reaction. No one told me about this. Then the patient read that they were afraid to warn people because they would not come in for the second shot.  The patient missed 1 1/2 days work. The patient did not expect that or she would had gotten it on a Friday night.  The reporter told they need to list these possible side effects as more than just a maybe. 1 in 6 the patient was just coming out from under. The patient know this was only considered anecdotal, but those are the real statistics. The patient was going to send a copy of this to the CDC. Just inform them.

Cholestasis; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational pregnancy study case initially received from other health professional on 31-Oct-2019, concerning a 26-year-old, adult, female pregnant subject of body weight: 146 lbs, height: 67 inches and body mass index (BMI): 22.9, enrolled in a prospective observational study.   The subject's current condition included bacterial infection due to streptococcus, group B. The subject's concomitant medication included Prenatal (minerals nos, vitamins nos) as a vitamin.  The subject's obstetrical history included 2 previous pregnancies with 1 full term live birth and 1 spontaneous abortion. The subject did not have a history of offspring with major congenital malformation. The paternal risk factor included father of baby maternal cousin � mental retardation, while the subject had no maternal history of offspring with major congenital malformations.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 31-Mar-2019, estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 05-Jan-2020.  The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. On an unknown date, the pregnancy status was collected, and no pregnancy complications were noted. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 26-Jun-2019, the subject underwent first trimester screen and nuchal translucency and no major congenital malformation (MCM) was noted.   On 26-Jul-2019, the subject underwent second trimester screen-alpha fetoprotein test (AFP) and no MCM was noted.   On 15-Aug-2019, the subject underwent anatomy ultrasound and no MCM was noted.   On 19-Sep-2019, at 24 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flucelvax QIVc (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261200, dose, route of administration, expiry date and anatomical location: not reported] for influenza immunisation (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy').  On 21-Oct-2018, 1 month and 2 days after vaccination, the subject developed cholestasis and was treated with ursodiol, one tablet, three times a day, administered orally.    At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event cholestasis was not reported.  The case was assessed as serious and the reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax (QIV).  Company comment: The subject experienced cholestasis after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIVc. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy. Chronology is plausible. Pregnant state may provide more plausible alternative aetiology for the event. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For the event cholestasis, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced cholestasis after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIVc. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient stood up approximately 5 minutes after receiving her last vaccine (flu shot) and stated she was "feeling hot and ready to go".Her mother observed a shift in her mood which she described as child gets mean prior to having a seizure. I asked patient to have a seat in the chair and she fainted. Her skin was clammy and sweaty. I called her name 3 times and she responded partially and closed her eyes. a Whiff of ammonia inhalant was given approx. at 10:04 A.M., Applied cool cloth to forehead was given 4oz. water. FS-123 and repeat BP 88/61 P-80. Parent declined 911 ambulance and agreed to take child to ER at Hospital. Repeated BP at 10:15 A.M. 86/60 P-83. Patient continued to be responsive. I explained Importance of child being evaluated today and parent agreed to give RN an update. Last vitals were done at 10:40 A.M. BP 89/60 P-65. Patient reported feeling better. Patient left clinic with her mom and was being transported to Hospital Emergency Room by her parent. 11/8/2019 Telephone call to parent today. Mother states child was evaluated at Hospital ER on 11/7/19. Was told by ER physician that child had a syncope episode after receiving vaccinations. Child was discharged on 11/7/19. Went home and rested. Mother stated "child is fine" and went to school today. - RN
HISTORY: History of seizure disorder for approximately 3 years

SYMPTOM_TEXT: about 4 days after receiving the vaccine on 8/23/19 I began having sharp ear pain in L ear  accompanied by very sensitive skin/ear on L side.  I had also had a slight headache that did not go away and felt very tired. Upon going to urgent care for my ear, the PA asked questions that led her to believe that I was pre-shingles and put me on  valacyclovire. Upon taking it the pain was gone the next day.  Then, about  October 24, 2019 I started having sharp pain in my lower jaw and a tooth on my lower jaw and one on my upper jaw became very sensitive to cold and then heat.  I also developed a cold sore (first in 10+ years) about the same time. This continued for about a week (I was out of town at a conference) and upon going to my dentist on 10/31 he took x-rays and examined me and could find no sign of infection or problems.  I was using cold sore medication and as the sore diminished so did the pain.  At the time of both these episodes, my life had become very chaotic and stressful, and as the stress lessened so did the symptoms - particularly the second time since I did not go to urgent care, but was working on the stressors and feeling less stressed as the symptoms were going away.  I never had shingles symptoms before these episodes.
LAB_DATA: No tests were run. X-rays showed no infection or problem with teeth or jaw.
OTHER_MEDS: one-a-day vitamin, fish oil 1000mg, zinc 50mg, 1000mcg, zyrtec 10mg, lisinopril-HCTZ 10/12.5mg, escitalopram 10mg6

Went to Gynogcogistt to see if putting on pill would make her feel better. That help either. After even more test. We found heavy metals in her hair and she is now allergic to milk and other things. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the flu shot on OCT. 23, 2019, about 5pm. About 2 hours after receiving the shoT, I began experiencing a side effecT, which felt 1/2 like a tootheache, and 1/2 like an infection. There was swelling in my face and upper lip. When pressure was applied to my right upper lip, in the area immediately below my right Nostril opening, there was a lot of pain. The pain was throbbing. The pain got worse as time went on, even thought I was taking Advil. On Oct. 25, after continuous pain, I called my Doctors, FNP office, to report the side effecT. The pain was abouT an 8 on a scaled of 1 to 10. The person I spoke with at FNP clinic Advised me to go to an Urgent Care. I did so the same day, Oct. 25. I was evaluated, and prescribed Amox-clav 875 MG tablets for anti-biotic treatment, and Tramadol 50MG tablets for pain. My face was visibly swollen at that time, and especially in my upper right lip area. I Advised the health care person, FNP, that I had no dental problems. I also told him that this was a side effecT. I also reported the side effecT to the FDA.
OTHER_MEDS: ACTOS; MEFTORMIN; HYDROCHLOROTHIAZIDE; POTASSIUM CHOLORIDE; LEVOTHYROXINE; ADVIL

Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy; Information was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient (pt) of unknown age. No information was provided regarding the pt's medical history, concurrent conditions, previous drug reactions, allergies and concomitant medications.  On or about 09-JAN-2013, the pt was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date were not reported), as recommended for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles.   On an unspecified date (reported as "shortly after"), the pt was diagnosed with chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the pt suffered serious, severe, progressive, permanent and incurable personal injuries that caused physical limitations (physical impairment) not presented prior vaccination; the pt also suffered significant conscious pain and mental anguish, loss of enjoyment of life and emotional distress due to his physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a further proximate result, the pt has suffered significant medical expenses, the loss of accumulations and other economic and non-economic damages.  The causality was reported as related and the event was considered to be disabling.   Upon internal review, the pt's chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy was determined to be a medically significant event.  Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received a flu shot on 10/10/19 at 09:00 in my left arm.  About a week later I started having symptoms with my right arm and hand.  Upon waking, my arm is numb and I couldn't make a fist with my right hand.  I couldn't (this still occurs) squeeze toothpaste onto my toothbrush with my right hand because my hand was weak and it caused a low level of pain.  I took ibuprofen off and on and this has helped with the discomfort. As the day went on I could close my hand into a fist, but I didn't have strength in my hand.  Every day I would check to see if I could close my right hand when I woke up. I thought my symptoms were going away, but on Sunday 11/3/19 in the evening my right hand was so cold and numb, I put a heating pad on my hand.  I noticed the end of my pinky finger was blue from the joint below my nail to the fingertip.  It appeared to be bruised from an injury and my finger was swollen, but I didn't remember injuring the finger.  Today (5 days later) the discoloration and swelling in my pinky is much improved (it is still cold to the touch). I have noticed numbness and tingling in my middle, ring and pinky fingers in the morning while putting on my makeup. I am concerned about the numbness, cold to the touch and tingling in my fingers/right hand.  A co-worker mentioned similar symptoms, so I wanted to document my symptoms.
Family reported death from unknown cause. Coroners report did not identify cause of death. Patient died driving on the way to work 8 hours after receiving vaccination.

Of note, he received Hep A, MMR, varicella, and influenza vaccinations on 10/31 with the Hep A and varicella vaccines administered in the right thigh.  In the ED, inflammatory markers were elevated and MRI was notable for myositis, osteomyelitis and a soft tissue abscess in the right thigh.  He was admitted for IV antibiotics and remains admitted at the time of this submission.
LAB_DATA: MRI of R thigh:  T2 hyperintense and diffusion restriction is seen in the muscles and soft tissues of the right mid thigh extending down into the knee -the vastus intermedialis and medialis, as well as short head of the biceps femoris. This area enhances, and is consistent with myositis. T2 hyperintense and diffusion restriction is also seen in the medullary space of the femur in this region (series 12 image 79-81), concerning for osteomyelitis. A rim-enhancing fluid collection is identified in the medial soft tissues and measures 1.5 x 0.8 cm, representing an abscess (series 6 image 10). � No hip or knee effusion. � No cortical break is identified, favoring hematogenous spread of infection. � IMPRESSION � � 1. Osteomyelitis of the distal femur. � 2. Abscess in the medial soft tissues of the lower thigh. � 3. No septic arthritis.  Blood culture:  Growth of Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A) at 11 hrs, 46 minutes.
CUR_ILL: Mild URI symptoms at time of vaccination; mild diarrhea 1-2 weeks prior (resolved at time of vaccination).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received vaccine Thursday afternoon at 12:30PM. By 5:00PM, patient stated he felt very tired and started having flu-like symptoms including headache, body aches, and overall malaise. Patient went to bed at 8:00PM because he was so tired.  Friday morning, the patient woke up at 7:30AM and had lost about 50% of his hearing in his RIGHT ear (vaccine in left arm). He said he felt like he was talking into a barrel, and he couldn't really hear high-pitched noises - low-pitched noises were more audible, but still muffled. He said he did not feel congested or stuffy at all, and it was only his right ear that was bothering him. He regularly cleans his ears, but did not clean them Thursday or Friday. He does not think he has wax build-up in the ear. Patient also stated that a close friend of his also reported hearing loss after receiving the shot, and that patient was currently seeking medical care for the hearing loss (that event did not occur here, but patient states the incident was reported by his physician). After discussion with the patient, we agreed that it could be the body's response to the vaccine and he might have some congestion/stuffiness/fluid that may be affecting the ear.  Patient is going to try a couple days of Claritin 10mg, one tablet daily, to see if it clears up until he can discuss with his doctor on Monday. Outcome is still pending. Patient was advised to notify us or his physician if symptoms worsen/

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient arrived at the pharmacy at approximately 1:50 P.M. with complaints of difficulty breathing. The patient was in noticeable distress, displaying shortness of breath and difficulty breathing. The patient was very possibly experiencing an allergic reaction. I retrieved the epinephrine injection to deliver to the patient and asked my associates to call 911. I advised the patient I would be delivering the epinephrine injection and the patient verified understanding. I delivered the epinephrine injection in the patient's right thigh, and the patient displayed noticeable improvement in breathing. I advised the patient that one of my associates called 911, an ambulance was on the way, and would wait with the patient until emergency services arrived. Two EMTs arrived at approximately 2:00 P.M. and they asked me about the situation. I reported to one EMT I had delivered 1 epinephrine injection to the patient after she approached the pharmacy with symptoms, likely caused by a recent Shingrix vaccine I had delivered in the patient's right arm. The EMT examined the epinephrine injection I delivered and then he returned it to me. The EMTs cared for the patient and left the pharmacy area by 2:10 P.M.  I contacted the emergency room via telephone at approximately 2:48 P.M. to check on the patient's status. I spoke to a gentleman; he reported the patient was stable, the patient had not received another epinephrine injection since the injection I had delivered at approximately 1:50 P.M., and the patient's airway was not compromised. I thanked him for updating me on the situation and ended the telephone call.

Received vaccine Thursday at 8:10 am and by approximately 8 pm was feeling body aches.  The body aches intensified during the night and when I got up at 6:00 am Friday had a temperature of 102.2 orally and felt lightheaded, weak headache, significant joint and muscle pain .  Took 400 mg Ibuprofen by 11:00 am temperature dropped to 101.4.  Took additional 400 mg Ibuprofen and temperature dropped to 100.6 by 3 pm.  8 pm temperature rose to 101 with worsening body aches, took 400 mg ibuprofen at that time and awoke at 1:30 am Saturday and was diaphoretic with temperature  of 99.  Body aches significantly improved, but not resolved.  As of 4 pm on Sat improved.  I did not call the doctor about the above, but I think it is  very important that you know that there are people who have significant adverse reactions to  vaccines and that your data should reflect rather than minimizing the side effects of vaccines.

Immediately following patient's two-month immunizations, and especially by that evening she was acting very uncomfortable and was not herself. Thankfully her fever broke by the next morning. However, her personality and alertness changed significantly as she started having severe fatigue and she slept almost constantly. When she was awake, her eyes were not focusing on me as usual, and she was not being responsive and cheerful. Even though at two months old she normally slept a lot, she kept falling asleep for prolonged periods of time without her general awake, happy, alert periods throughout the day. It was very difficult to see the dramatic change to her personality, and not get to interact with her as I normally did for a couple days. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Woke up with severe overall mouth pain and swollen lips and cheeks. Was wearing a night guard as I have for over 3 months with no issues. It was very painful to remove the guard, my gums and cheeks were bleeding.  The skin on my gums and cheeks were bright red, hot, swollen, painful to touch and the skin was sloughing; like peeling from sunburn. I rinsed with Dry Mouth Smart Mouth, warm water, couldn't brush my teeth, too painful to open mouth. Saw my dentist and they gave me a pain mouth wash. Only explanation was an acute allergic reaction.

Vaccine was a GSK influenza vaccine, distributed by ID BioMedical. If it was a quadrivalent or trivalent, and lot number unknown by me. A 4 inch long swelling occurred on the arm below the injection site, as well as throat tightening. Swelling was red and hot to the touch.  Called the Doctor's office on 11/6/19 and was advised by doctor's office staff to  use ice, Motrin, and Benadryl until symptoms subsided. As of 11/11/19, the site is still slightly red, but swelling has decreased.
PRIOR_VAX: Same symptoms when he was 3 years old in 2013.

a diminished response to the 23-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine;   This literature marketed report has been received from the author of a published article titled as stated above referring to a 65-year-old female patient.  The patient was referred from otolaryngology for evaluation of several years of long-standing chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRS w NP). Her symptoms included mucopurulent drainage, congestion, and facial pain without anosmia. Computed tomography (CT) sinus was notable for septal deviation with opacification of the left frontal, paranasal, maxillary, and ethmoid sinuses. She underwent endoscopic sinus surgery several months prior without significant improvement. Operative cultures grew penicillium and beta-hemolytic streptococcus, and pathology showed benign inflammatory changes. Consequently, allergic fungal rhinosinusitis (AFRS) was the leading diagnosis. Symptoms persisted for several years despite multiple courses of oral and intranasal steroids, antihistamines, and leukotriene modifiers. She had no history of pneumonia or recurrent infections. An allergic and immunologic workup was initiated upon consultation in our clinic. Labs revealed normal immunoglobulins, protective tetanus/diphtheria titers but a diminished response to the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) (dose, route, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis (3 protective titers post-vaccination) (Therapeutic response decreased). Total Immunoglobulin E (IgE) was 1161 international unit per litre (IU/L). Specific IgE testing for molds was negative. The patient was diagnosed with specific antibody deficiency.   The outcome of the event was unknown. The reporter considered the event to be related to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown).  A copy of the published article has been requested.
LAB_DATA: Test Name: Immunoglobulin E (IgE); Test Result: Negative
CUR_ILL: Allergic rhinosinusitis; Nasal polyps; Rhinosinusitis; Selective polysaccharide antibody deficiency
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Functional endoscopic sinus surgery

Epiretinal Membrane; Vitreomacular Traction; hearing loss; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a lawyer refers to a female patient(pt) of unknown age.The pt's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications were not provided. On or around 25-AUG-2017, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot#, expiration date were unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). In approximately August 2017 (reported as "Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX)"), the pt suffered an abrupt visual acuity and separated retina as well as hearing loss. Pt was diagnosed with Epiretinal Membrane and Vitreomacular Traction. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX), pt's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX). Pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX), pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX), pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live(ZOSTAVAX), pt had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.   Macular fibrosis, deafness and vitreoretinal traction syndrome were considered to be disability. Upon internal review, macular fibrosis, deafness and vitreoretinal traction syndrome were determined to be medically significant.

Hepatitis B surface antigen positive; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of hepatitis b surface antigen positive in a 65-year-old male patient who received Hepatitis B vaccine for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included end stage renal disease, diabetes and diabetic foot ulcer.   On an unknown date, the patient received Hepatitis B vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, 14 days after receiving Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient experienced hepatitis b surface antigen positive (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the hepatitis b surface antigen positive was unknown.   The reporter considered the hepatitis b surface antigen positive to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of hepatitis B surface antigen positive in a 65-year-old male patient who was vaccinated with unspecified hepatitis B vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. The case corresponds to patient 2 reported in this literature article. The patient had underlying condition of end-stage kidney disease (EKSD), diabetes and diabetic foot ulcer. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, 2 weeks prior to admission, the patient received booster dose of unspecified hepatitis B vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosages unknown; batch number not reported). It was reported that, detailed information on administration vaccination revealed by patient's dialysis unit. [The current advisory committee on immunization practices guidelines recommend hepatitis B vaccination series for All ESKD patient's preceded by serologic testing and followed by post vaccination confirmation of immunity]. The age at vaccination was not provided, but it could be 64 or 65 years. On an unspecified date, 2 weeks after receiving the booster dose of vaccination, the patient with ESKD was admitted to the hospital for a diabetic foot ulcer. Patient's routine hospital testing for hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) was positive, and the patient was dialyzed with isolation practice while awaiting results of an acute hepatitis B panel. The patient was irate about faulty vaccination, stating that he was told his recent vaccination would help to prevent hepatitis B infection, not cause it. Treatment was unknown. The outcome was not reported. The authors did not comment on relationship between the event hepatitis B surface antigen positive and unspecified hepatitis B vaccine. The authors stated "The current advisory committee on immunization practices guidelines recommend hepatitis B vaccination series for all ESKD patient's preceded by serologic testing and followed by post vaccination confirmation of immunity'' This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in the same literature article. This article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction.      Lab Comments: Lab test done on an unknown date.
LAB_DATA: Test Name: Hepatitis B surface antigen; Result Unstructured Data: Test Result: Positive, Test Result Unit: unknown
CUR_ILL: Diabetes; Diabetic foot ulcer; End stage renal disease

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe shoulder pain that has persisted 11 days after vaccine with little improvement. Limited range of motion of left arm. Lifting my left arm up or across my body causes severe pain.

Prior to receiving the shot on 11/5 and the days leading up to I was healthy and feeling perfectly fine. Around 1:00 I began to notice a funny painful feeling in my left arm, so I walked over to one of my pharmacist to be informed my arm was swollen. That same day as I laid down for bed my body felt off.  However, on 11/6 I woke up for work but I could not make my body get up because it felt really week. Once I was able to get up I began to walk towards the bathroom and I became really dizzy so I immediately laid down and called into to work. During that same day I began experience muscle pains, and body sweats. On 11/7 as I woke up for work I woke up with a really bad headache, so I decided to just call into work again. I went back to sleep and I began to experience chills and fever, but not once did I feel sick it was more like I was just having weird symptoms. On 11/8 I woke up and I was still dealing with my same symptoms, but I was managing to move around okay. It was about 5:30pm that night and my voice just left. I could barely get a word out clear enough or loud enough to be understood. Thats when I googled and read up on my symptoms and they were all listed under a severe reaction to the shot. On 11/9 I went to the ER and they told me I had the flu as well as pneumonia which I never had before. And last year after receiving the shot it caused me to be sick as well
PRIOR_VAX: 26, I experienced aches and chills. March 2019, Not sure of the type of vaccine because it was administered by the hospital duri

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Child received Infanrix and Havrix IM on 10/30/19 IM in Right Vastus Lateralis around 9AM. He started with a low-grade fever around 4pm of 99 degrees. It did elevate to 101.6 per ear thermometer later Wednesday night. Mom gave him Tylenol throughout the night. On 10/31 the fever remained around 99 degrees. He was not himself. No real appetite. By 2pm, the child started having a seizure. EMS was called and he was taken by ambulance to the ER. His seizure lasted a total of 90 minutes from start to finish. The ER doctor felt this was a Grand Mal type seizure. He had an MRI, chest x-ray and spinal tap to rule out infectious nature for seizure. All were negative and no meningitis was noted. Genetic testing has been done and results are pending. Child is on anti-seizure medication and being followed by a Pediatric Neurologist- Dr. No further seizure activity for the child when mom called on 11/5/2019. Child's activity was back to normal.
LAB_DATA: Head MRI, Chest x-ray, spinal tap and genetic lab testing all done on 10/31/19.

She was complaining of feeling generally bad, feverish and had pain, warmth and redness to left arm that started about 24 hours after injection.     Employee immediately released from work and sent to ED.  Followed up with employee in ED who was seen by ED physician at approx 2000.  Released from ED on Bactrim.  Followed up with Lupus MD next day.  Was treated with steroids and told to return to work Sunday.  Followed up with employee Sunday 11/10/19 and was told she had fever of 102 but arm had improved greatly.  She notified her MD of this and was told by MD not to return to work until fever is below 99.  Employee excused from work, told to stay home until fevers under control per MD orders.  She stated that she has appt to follow up with Lupus MD on 11/11/19 and that this event was being treated as a Lupus flair that she has experienced prior, but never as the result of an immunization.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received vaccinations at approx 10:50 am.  PHN instructed her to remain sitting in her chair after receiving her vaccines.  She sat in the chair for approx 5-7 min, then patient and her mom left the nurse's office and walked out to the HD main lobby to schedule the next clinic appt.  They were in the lobby for approx 1-2 min. when PHN heard a "thud" and the admin asst shouted for PHN to come to the lobby.  PHN grabbed an ammonia inhalant and ran to the lobby.  PHN arrived in the lobby within 30 seconds of admin asst shouting for PHN.  Patient was laying face up on the floor in the HD lobby doorway.  Patient was responsive when PHN knelt beside her.  PHN Instructed her to remain laying down.  She was crying and upset and sat up.  PHN knelt behind her and supported her in the sitting position.  PHN waved the ammonia inhalant under her nose and told her to remain sitting.  Patient stated her head hurt, and wasn't sure what happened.  Patient's mom stated that patient was standing at the admn asst desk in the HD lobby and passed out and fell into the health dept entry way and hit her head on the floor of the building lobby.  PHN applied an icepack to the back of patient's head.  Another HD staff member called 911. HD police chief and HD fire capt. arrived on scene.  HD fire capt took over care of patient until FD EMS arrived.  FD asked mom if they wanted them to transport patient to the hospital.  Mom stated she would like her to be transported to hospital.  Transport to hospital by FD occurred at approx 1130-1145 am.  PHN followed up with mom on 11/6/19 at approx 2:30 pm.  Mom stated patient was home and resting. Mom stated that patient did not have a concussion, no CT scan was done.

My left arm immediately became very very sore and inflamed. I was unable to lift my arm, sleep on it. I had to sleep on my back and not move my left arm. My arm was hot to the touch and red to the elbow. This condition remained for several weeks. The muscle is still sore to the touch. I had high fever and chills for four days following the shot. Then I had diarrhea for at least 3 days. Then the fever and chills came again perhaps they did not leave me. I also had bad headaches. I was sick in my bed for a week, I could not get up. My friends brought me food, soup mostly and toast. It took about 3 weeks before I felt well enough to leave my house. It has been a while so I might not have included everything that happened to me. I was very ill. I filed a complaint with Pharmacy against the Manager wig gave me the shot as she was very rude and in my opinion no medical trained to administer shots. She just stabbed my arm then told me not to cry. She has since called me and apologized. I will never go there again. I saw my doctor she hasn't decided if I should have the booster shot however we are waiting for 6 months. I will she her prior to that time.

itching down to her elbow, toward the collar bone and into her chest; had a really big knot; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable pharmacist via a Pfizer Sponsored Program IBCC (Inbound Call Center for HCPs). A 69-year-old female patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13, NDC#: 00005197102), via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date at single dose in right arm for vaccination, influenza vaccine (FLU), via an unspecified route of administration on the same date at unknown dose in left arm for vaccination. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.  The caller said she did not get the immunization from her pharmacy and said she did not come to them much and she just cams to them for acute care. The patient had received the pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) at another pharmacy. When the patient had the reaction she did not break out into hives but had itching down to her elbow, toward the collar bone and into her chest and she had a really big knot that felt like an egg but was quite a bit bigger and it was bruised but slightly sore but not overly painful. This was the patient's first year getting pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) and she was concerned about getting the pneumovax next year because of the reaction to the pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein). The itching, swelling and knot size had gone down and some of the bruising was gone and it was still a little sore but not as sore. The outcome of itching was recovered, the other event was recovering. Reporter seriousness for the events was medically significant.; Sender's Comments: The association between the events itching and swelling with pneumococcal 13-valent conjugate vaccine can not be fully excluded.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

The patient came into the pharmacy on 11/11/19 3:40 pm and stated that she thinks that she had a reaction to her flu shot. The flu shot was administered on 10/19/19. The patient's son was with her today, and the son stated that he does not think that the symptoms/ reaction is due to the flu shot. I referred the patient to be seen by her provider, to assess the reaction that the pt. reports.  The patient reports a lump in her left arm near her elbow. She asked me to palpate the lump, which I could feel near the elbow. The area was not swollen, but there was a hard lump under the skin. The lump was not located near the area where immunizations are administered - the lump is much lower very near her elbow. The patient reported that she noticed this lump a few days ago. The patient reports no fever, no redness, no itching, no swelling. The patient said that the lump does not hurt, reports no pain from the lump.  The patient said her regular doctor, I encouraged her to make an appointment to have this lump evaluated, and I let the pt. know that I will call Dr. as well, and let them know what she is reporting. Called Dr.'s office and left message in nurse voice mail about this 11/11/19 4:02 pm. Asked the nurse to call us back.  Note: I am submitting this VAERS for documentation, since the patient thinks that this was caused by her flu shot.

All of the joints in my entire body ached down to the very small joints in toes and fingers.  That state remained for 2 entire days. The inflammation in my upper arm remained for about 10 days. At least with the 2nd shot I did not get the blisters around the injection site that I did with the 1st shot in the series. I did take diphenhydramine and Tylenol  and had lots of rest time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had vaccination and remained in pharmacy area.  He came up to the pharmacy window as his wife is a pharmacy technician about to clock out and patient collapsed and went down to the ground after fainting.  Patient was clammy, sweating, and had visual disturbances.  I laid patient down and put feet up in the air.  Gave two ice packs and a ginger ale.  Gave a dose of benadryl as a precautionary measure.  Patient remained supine position for 15 minutes or so at which time we helped to a sitting position and eventually standing position.  Patient felt much better at this time, was no longer clammy and sweating, and had regained some color in his face.  Patient was instructed not to drive home - his wife drove.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprazole 20mg capsules, members mark 10X probiotic, cyclobenzaprine 5mg tablets

Unwitnessed seizure-like activity. Father reports that after vaccines were administered and pt was sitting in the car about to leave she c/o "feeling nauseous". Father reports that immediately her eyes opened widely and she seemed as if she was not there. Father says that one leg was extended and stiff and her arms were pulled into her chest with stiffness and jerking. Father was touching pts face and asking if she was okay but was "unresponsive". Child's lips were pale and white. Father estimates this episode lasted 5-7 seconds. Afterwards pt did not seem to know what had happened. Patient reports that she remembers saying she was feeling nauseous and then "blacked out". Pt was brought back into the clinic withing 5 minutes of episode and was very pale appearing. Pt was laid down on exam table. VS re-taken and pt was offered juice. All VS stable and pt reported that she felt okay. Father asked if an ambulance needed to be called and I told him that this was most likely a vasovagal syncopal episode but that a EEG would be ordered to evaluate for seizures. Father would like to take child to ER to have more testing done.

A literature article has been received from the authors of a marketed literature article, titled as above, referring to a currently 50 year old male patient. varicella vaccine-associated primary varicella infection; A 4-year-old female with ataxia-telangiectasia was vaccinated;    This literature marketed report was received from  the authors of the published article as stated above, concerning a 4-year old female child. The patient's concurrent conditions included ataxia-telangiectasia. The pertinent drug reactions/allergies and concomitant medications were not provided.    On an unspecified date, the female child with ataxia-telangiectasia presented for question of vaccination. Family was  concerned to travel with patient's immunocompromised state in the setting of the measles outbreak. The immune system evaluation showed adequate T cell function testing, and it was thought that she should be able to tolerate live vaccines (Product use issue).    She proceeded with the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) and varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown) or Zoster Vaccine Live (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis (doses, route, lot #, expiration date, and anatomical location were not provided).   Subsequently, 12 days later, the patient developed a runny nose and 104 F fever. She broke out in papules that returned positive on varicella zoster PCR. She only required supportive care, with no use of antivirals or hospitalizations. Testing showed the strain she had was the same as the varicella vaccine, confirming a varicella vaccine-associated primary varicella infection.    The authors considered that patient's lymphocyte function testing was adequate, and it was thought her T cells should appropriately be able to respond to the vaccine, but unfortunately this was not the case. It may not be enough to determine if a patient can appropriately respond to vaccines as the patient was self-limited and may have prevented a future more significant varicella infection.    The authors considered the event varicella zoster virus infection to be related to varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown) or Zoster Vaccine Live (manufacturer unknown).   A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.

Mom states child vomited three times around 9:00 pm that night, then mom noticed child was stumbling when he walked. Mom put child to bed. The next morning mom states child would not walk and every time he tried to stand up he would fall to the ground; mom also noticed his legs were shaking. Mom brought child to our clinic that day, on 11/8/19 at 3:00 pm to be evaluated. In the exam room, the child starting walking but was very unsteady on his feet and stumbled several times throughout the course of the exam . Mom states this was the first time he has walked the entire day, at 3:00 pm.  I performed an examination and advised mom to take child to hospital if symptoms continued and/or worsened. Spoke to mom Monday, 11/11/19 to check on child. Mom states child seemed ok over the weekend , still somewhat off balance/unsteady but child has not worsened and does seem to be improving. Informed mom that this incident would be reported to VAERS.
CUR_ILL: Recent otitis media infection but was clear on the day of vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: some soreness at the right deltoid injection sight; 15 year patient was given Flublok vaccine in error; Initial information received on 07-Oct-2019 and follow-up information received on 08-Oct-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse.  This case involves a 15 years old patient who experienced some soreness at the right deltoid injection sight (Vaccination site pain) while she received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV].  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  On 07-Oct-2019, the patient received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE Prefilled syringe (lot number: QSAA1921 and Exp date: 30-Jun-2020) via intramuscular route in the right deltoid.  On an unknown date, patient developed a non-serious soreness at the right deltoid injection sight (vaccination site pain) (Unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE. The nurse states that, the soreness is not abnormal.  It was a case of actual medication error due to Inappropriate age at vaccine administration.  (Other relevant tests included No lab data.)  Final diagnosis was vaccination site pain.   It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  The patient outcome is reported as Unknown for vaccination site pain.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. Pancratitis; Blood sugar spiked very high; Pain in hands and knees; Pain in hands and knees; This is a spontaneous case, initially received from consumer via Med Communication (reference number: SEQ19-06147) on 04-Nov-2019, concerning a 68-year-old, male patient.   The patient's relevant medical history included flu shot in 2018 after which the patient developed pancreatitis. The patient's concomitant medications included Keprom (ketoprofen) and levetiracetam, both for an unknown indication.  On 31-Aug-2019, the patient was administered Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid, batch number: P100110154 and expiration date: not reported] for influenza prophylaxis.    On 03-Sep-2019, the patient's blood sugar spiked very high and he developed pancreatitis. The patient was hospitalised.  On an unspecified date, the patient experienced pain in hands and knees.   On an unspecified date, the patient was still having trouble with pain in his hands and knees.  The patient was recovering from the events of pancreatitis and increased blood sugar, while the outcome for the events of pain in hands and knees was not recovered, at the time of this report.  The reporter assessed the case as serious bit did not provide causality assessment to Afluria Quadrivalent.  The case was linked with 201905880 (due to same patient).  Company comment: The patient experienced pancreatitis, blood glucose increased, arthralgia and pain in extremity after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of previous pancreatitis may have contributed to development of the events. Causality was also confounded by therapy with concomitant medications, Keprom (ketoprofen) and levetiracetam. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as possibly related.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced pancreatitis, blood glucose increased, arthralgia and pain in extremity after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent.
