SYMPTOM_TEXT: Spontaneous uterine abruption; Depression; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 04-Nov-2019, concerning a 35-year-old female pregnant subject of body weight: 312 Ibs, height: 68 in and body mass index (BMI) 47.4 enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The subject's past medical history included gastric bypass, while the subject's risk factors included advanced maternal age and high BMI.  The subject's concomitant medication included buspirone, ondansetron, Protonix (omeprazole), cyclobenzaprine, clonazepam and Zoloft (sertraline); all for an unknown indication.   The subject had three previous pregnancies, two with full term live births and one spontaneous abortion. The subject had a history of caesarean section. The subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs) and had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 04-Feb-2019. Estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 11-Nov-2019 and corrected estimated delivery date (CEDD) was reported as 25-Nov-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 01-May-2019, the subject underwent Maternit21 and there were no MCMs noted.  On 17-May-2019, the subject underwent gastric bypass panel and there were no MCMs noted.  On 21-Jun-2019, the subject underwent maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein /serum markers and there were no MCMs noted.  On 11-Jul-2019, the subject underwent targeted ultrasound and there were no MCMs noted.  On 10-Oct-2019, at approximately 35 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Afluria QIV [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, cell cultured derived, batch number: P100112488, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  On 04-Nov-2019, the pregnancy status was collected and polyhydramnios, spontaneous uterine abruption and depression were noted.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome for spontaneous uterine abruption and depression was not reported.  This case is linked to case number 201905906 (corresponding child case).  The case was assessed as serious and the reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  Company comment: The subject experienced premature separation of placenta and depression after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at gestational age of 35 weeks. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of obesity (body mass index 47.4) and advanced maternal age (35 years) may provide alternative aetiology for the events. Causality was also confounded by therapy with multiple concomitant medications. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Causality between suspect product and the events premature separation of placenta and depression is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced premature separation of placenta and depression after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at gestational age of 35 weeks. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of obesity (body mass index 47.4) and advanced maternal age (35 years) may provide alternative aetiology for the events. Causality was also confounded by therapy with multiple concomitant medications. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Causality between suspect product and the events premature separation of placenta and depression is assessed as unlikely related.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: received INJECTION ON 10/08/2019. On 10/14/2019 I woke up early, very dizzy and a little nauseated, headache in back of my head. I felt not well all week, foggy head and occipital headache. On 10/18/2019 I had my blood pressure checked and it was 220/140. My blood pressures has always been very well controlled  with Lorsartan. I contacted my PCP, who suggested that I has a systemic reaction to the flu shot and that I should double up on my medication. However, the next day my pressure was still very elevated, I went to my local emergency room. I was given IV Labatelol and sent home. On 10/21/2019 my pressure had not gotten any lower, so I called my PCP, he advised me to go back to the emergency room. I was again given IV Labatelol and IV Hydralazine and kept overnight. I was start on Norvasc, in addition to Lorsartan 50mg. Cardiac work-up was negative. CT head was negative. I am now on HCTZ 25mg in addition to those meds to keep me under control. After thinking about this, I recalled that last year approximately 1 week after receiving my flu shot, I was hospitalized with left upper and lower extremity numbness and slightly elevated blood pressure. Stroke and cardiac workup were negative and told I had a TIA, because they couldn't figure out what what was wrong with me.  So weird symptoms, 2 years in a row after a flu shot, I do not think is a coincidence.
LAB_DATA: MRI and CT brain  negative cardiac enzymes negative EKG normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right after giving HPV pt became light headed, pale, diaphoretic, nearly fainted.  Laid pt down and monitored x 1 hour, until she was symptom free.
Pt was inoculated with smallpox on 06NOV2019.  On 10NOV2019 at 1200 pt got a tattoo directly below the inoculation sight.  Tattoo shows no signs of possible infection due to the inoculation.

On 10/11/19 I went for a physical and also got the flu shot and shingles shot. That night I awoke with excruciating pain in my hand. It felt like it would burst, my heart was beating in it, it was on fire and very painful. If I tried to move it I had to use my other hand because of the pain. The next day it still hurt but it was a Saturday so I didn?t contact my doctor. On Monday I called the doctor?s office and told my symptoms and then someone called me back and said it could be normal or could be a reaction but shouldn?t last long. Today it is 1 month since I have received those shots and I am not better. My right hand is in constant pain along with the soles of my feet. I cannot grasp with my hand. I can?t open a door, I can?t cut with a knife. Also my hips and ankles are sore. I am fatigued. Before this happened I was very healthy- where I worked I usually got about 10,000 steps. This has totally changed my life.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D, Centrum Silver, Gingko Biloba

Eyes color changed to red; Pain in my legs muscles, chest and jaw; Pain in my legs muscles, chest and jaw; Acute allergic reaction to flu vaccine; Pain in my legs muscles, chest and jaw; Blood pressure was around 160; This is a spontaneous case, reported by other non-health professional to agency [reference number: SEQ19-06089] and initially received on 04-Nov-2019, concerning a 53-year-old, male patient.   The patient's relevant medical history included flu vaccination with other brands for more than 10 years with no adverse events. The patient was not taking any concomitant medication.  On 04-Oct-2019 at 4:30 pm, the patient was administered Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, NDC: 33332-419-11; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid, batch number: P10011060 and expiration date: 15-May-2020] for prevention of seasonal influenza.  On the same day, an hour after vaccination, the patient experienced pain in leg muscles, chest and jaw, and the patient's eyes colour changed to red.  On the same day, the patient went to hospital emergency room and underwent electrocardiogram (EKG), chest X-ray and had blood tests done, however, results were not provided. The patient's blood pressure was around 160, units were not specified. It was reported that the patient was diagnosed with acute allergic reaction to flu vaccine. The patient received treatment medicine prednisone at a dose of 20 mg, administered once per day, for 5 days (5 tablets).  On 05-Oct-2019, the patient's blood pressure went to normal, and the patient was discharged home.  At the time of the initial reporting, the outcome for the events of pain in legs, chest pain, pain in jaw, red eyes and acute allergic reaction was not reported.  The case was assessed as serious.   The reporter assessed the events to be related to Afluria Quadrivalent.  This case is linked to cases 201905876, 201905877 and 201905878 (same reporter).  Company comment: The patient experienced pain in jaw, blood pressure increased, ocular hyperaemia, chest pain, pain in extremity and hypersensitivity an hour after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. No diagnostic findings and concomitant medications were provided. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as possibly related.; Reporter's Comments: They recognized this is acute allergic reaction to flu vaccine.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced pain in jaw, blood pressure increased, ocular hyperaemia, chest pain, pain in extremity and hypersensitivity an hour after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. No diagnostic findings and concomitant medications were provided. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as possibly related.
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 20191004; Test Name: Blood pressure; Result Unstructured Data: Around 160; Test Date: 20191005; Test Name: Blood pressure; Result Unstructured Data: Normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Bilateral choroid plexus cysts; Vaccine fetal exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 04-Nov-2019, concerning a foetal subject, whose mother was 31-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 136 lbs, height: 63 inches and body mass index (BMI): 24.1 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.  The subject's mother obstetrical history was collected, and it was noted that the mother did not have any previous pregnancies, nor maternal and paternal history with major congenital malformation (MCM). The mother did not consume tobacco, alcohol and illicit-drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's mother current condition included chlamydia. Concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamin (unspecified vitamins) for an unknown indication.   The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 23-May-2019, and estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 27-Feb-2020. The corrected estimated date of delivery was not reported. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 15-Aug-2019, the subject's mother underwent Sequential 1 and Nuchal translucency prenatal tests and no MCM was noted.  On 12-Sep-2019, the subject's mother underwent Sequential 2 test and no MCM was noted.  On 10-Oct-2019, at gestational age of 20 weeks, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Afluria QIV) [Influenza Vaccine, batch number: P100112488, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiry date: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy, second trimester') for influenza immunisation.  On the same day, the subject's mother underwent targeted ultrasound scan and bilateral choroid plexus cysts were noted.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event was not reported.   This case was assessed as serious.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  This case is linked to 201905903, the corresponding mother case.  Company comment: In foetal subject of an unspecified gender, congenital choroid plexus cyst was noted after foetal exposure during pregnancy, at gestation age of 20 weeks with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Temporal relationship is implausible because congenital choroid plexus cyst was found on the day of vaccination and cyst need more time to form. Mother's current condition of chlamydia infection may provide alternative aetiology for the event. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For the event congenital choroid plexus cyst, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as not related.; Sender's Comments: In foetal subject of an unspecified gender, congenital choroid plexus cyst was noted after foetal exposure during pregnancy, at gestation age of 20 weeks with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Temporal relationship is implausible because congenital choroid plexus cyst was found on the day of vaccination and cyst need more time to form. Mother's current condition of chlamydia infection may provide alternative aetiology for the event. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For the event congenital choroid plexus cyst, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as not related.

Doctors note from clinic visit on 11/12/19: Patient is a 70 year old female here following an allergic reaction to recent pneumovax immunization.  She got her immunization at the clinic at about 9 am last Friday.  By 3 pm she had swelling and was not able to lift her arm.  By the next morning, she had redness, swelling and rash at the borders of the reaction which was from elbow to shoulder on the left.  She presented to the ER and had an echo done which showed no emboli.  She was covered for infection with Keflex and allergic reaction is covered with benadryl and prednisone.  She has some side effects from the prednisone, and dry mouth from the benadryl.  Arm swelling is much improved, but not completely resolved.  Constitutional: No fevers or chills. No weight change.Continue prednisone and benadryl until completed and no longer reacting to immunization.  She will RTC if symptoms return with dc of meds. After 5 hours she developed a high fever 103, then she had diarrhea and vomiting. Which caused her to become dehydrated. I called her dr and he said take her to the ER because that is not a normal reaction. This exact same thing happened at the 4 month vaccines which were the exact same. She had diarrhea for 1 week after the fever broke. The fever started 5/6 hours after receiving the 2nd doses.  She did not receive 6 or 12 month vaccinations. I got a new pediatrician who said we can start back with vaccines but to do them separate to see if a specific one was causing the symptoms. She did not get the 3rd and final dose of ROTATEQ but she received DTaP and had no fever but did have a small amount of diarrhea which she had with all the vaccines once we split them up. No fever. She received MMR at 17 months she had fever of 101 and diarrhea. She received varicella 2-3 months later and had no reaction at all. She is completed on the varicella.

Medical Assistant Administered 1st vaccine, pt took a deep breath while crying; simultaneously, 2nd Vaccine Administered, at that point pt became limp & breathless, had episode of synchopy. Nurse came in & placed him prone, felt mucus plug in chest, & slapped his back a few times. Pt took breath & started crying almost immediately. Please see office visit Note for further clarification. DX: Syncope VS clearing mucus plus vs hyperventilation Patient is a 19 month old male. He presents with acute cough, congestion/drainage, and fainting. The history is obtained from the patient's mother and maternal great grandmother. The history appears to be reliable. 19 m m brought by his mother for vaccination for hepatitis A and influenza vaccination. MA administered his vaccines. Per MA, he began to cry after first vaccine. While crying hard, he inhaled deeply, 2nd vaccine was given and he became breathless. MA sat him up. Mom picked him up. Nurse in doorway stepped over to pick him up from mom, felt mucus move in chest, placed him prone, and slapped his back. He began to cry almost immediately. He was crying, breathing without distress, pink and well-perfused, in nurse's arms as I walked in. Patient's vitals were RR 36 bpm with HR 148. Patient was observed and reassessed every 10 minutes. Repeat vitals 20 minutes later were HR 135 bpm, RR 28 bpm, oxygen saturations 98% on room air also while crying and fighting to climb down from mom's lap. Mom reports that yesterday he developed cough, nasal congestion. Per mom, cough has progressively worsened today becoming gradually more wet and congested as the day has passed. No fever. No loss of appetite. Drinking well. No vomiting. No change in stools. No rash. Wetting diapers normally. On Sunday, 3 days ago, he was moving from mom to dad walking down steps when he fell on step, hitting right cheek and eyelid. No loss of consciousness. He cried immediately. No vomiting. No clumsiness. No unusual irritability. He has abrasions to right upper eyelid, cheek and chin that are healing well. He fell at great-grandmother's house recently and hit chin, on Friday of last week. Fall was witnessed by great-grandmother. He cried immediately, no loss of consciousness. Abrasion on chin is healing well.
LAB_DATA: Vital signs & physical exam every 10 minutes

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt received vaccine at approximately 5:35 pm. A few minutes after patient received vaccine, pt stood up to leave and describes feeling a strong head pain and pressure, and nausea. pt then sat down again in a bench seat next to his brother looking pale out of it. He became very pale and was instructed to elevate his feet. His father felt his head and he was sweaty. While pt was pale in the face and lips, his hands become red and flushed. 911 was called and pt remained pale for several minutes until paramedics arrived at 5:50pm. Vitals per paramedics were: pulse 57 and sitting blood pressure of 120/80; standing blood pressure of 118/72. Patient's father declined transporting to the hospital and patient did regain color. Patient seemed to feel better and was able to get up and walk out of the store. At 7:00pm the patient's parents were called to check on how he was doing. They reported that he seemed to be feeling much better. He had regained his color and was doing his homework and was able to eat dinner.
LAB_DATA: Pulse 57 and blood pressure of 120/80 sitting, 118/72 standing

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started to feel sick almost immediately, felt dizzy and lightheaded. Left arm painful and stinging at times. Began to have very sharp pains in joints running all the way down to feet. Had to take constant breaks at work. At home couldn't concentrate, read or write very well due to extreme headache. Started to feel sick to my stomach and like I was going to vomit. As I am typing this now I feel lightheaded, have a horrible headache, and feel like I am going to throw up constantly. Before I got the flu shot I was fine, healthy, energetic, could walk for hours. A female consumer reported that she experienced nerve pain on injection side (PT: Neuralgia), headache (PT: Headache), low grade fever (PT: Pyrexia), and injection site pain (PT: Injection site pain), following immunization with BioThrax. On 17SEP2019 at 01:30 PM, she received a dose of BioThrax by intramuscular route in the left arm. On the same day, at 2:15 PM, she experienced low grade fever (101 degree Fahrenheit), which lasted for 18 hours, along with a headache which was also lasted for 18 hours. In addition, she also had nerve pain on injection side. She recovered from the reported events headache, low grade fever, and site pain on 18SEP2019 at 08:00 AM, while she did not recover from the event nerve pain on injection side.  Treatment medication included oral Naproxen (400 mg).  Medical history included fever/ pain post vaccination with diphtheria tetanus and pertussis (Dtap), at age 29 years and fever/ arthritis post vaccination with measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine, at age 31 years.  Company comment: The described events "headache, low grade fever and injection site pain" are known effects of Biothrax, and therefore are considered to be causally related to the administration of Biothrax. Generalized dermatitis with an onset day 17. The dermatitis is very pruritic, nontender, and presents to chest, back, trunk and extremities x4 including fingers but not palms. Lesions are discrete and he has developed new lesions over several days. He denied vesicles or pustules. He feels well and denies fever, chills, malaise, headache, myalgias or arthralgias. He denies vision changes, eye pruritis, pain, blurring, erythema or edema. He denies oral lesions. PE: dermatitis with discrete erythematous round raised  lesions with central shallow depressions in varying sizes and fewer small papules.  Affected areas are chest, back, trunk, upper and lower extremities including hands. No vesicles or pustules seen. No scale or eschars. Left upper arm SPV inoculation site with intact dark dry scab. The  dermatitis was somewhat but not fully consistent with either EM, BAPE and generalized vaccinia (GV). Followup  2 days later P/E documented. Skin:       dermatitis with discrete scattered erythematous annular papules & plaques, some with central shallow depressions; in varying sizes and fewer small papules. Some are confluent and lesions are in varying stages.  Affected areas are chest, back, trunk, upper and lower extremities including hands, fingers, but only periphery of palms. No vesicles or pustules seen. No scale or eschars. He then complained of notable arthralgias to PIP joints of hands.
LAB_DATA: Skin, right posterior shoulder, punch biopsy: - Spongiotic dermatitis with eosinophils (see comment). Comments The histologic differential diagnosis of spongiotic dermatitis with eosinophils includes, but is not limited to, allergic/contact dermatitis, Id reaction, nummular dermatitis, or a drug eruption.  The presence of subcorneal pustules noted on the PAS stained slide could indicate an evolving acute generalized exanthematous pustulosis.  Clinical correlation is advised.  Objective features of erythema multiforme or granuloma annulare are not observed. This case received intradepartmental dermatopathology consultation. ***Electronically Signed *** 10/1/2019     , CPT, MC, Addendum Date Ordered: 10/17/2019 Date Reported: 10/17/2019 Addendum Diagnosis   This case was reviewed at Clinic with the following diagnosis:    Skin, right posterior shoulder: - Spongiotic vesicular dermatitis. Received for consultation on WS19-6665 are 3 slides and 1 block. Additional slides prepared from the block were also reviewed. Immunostains were prepared in the lab here with adequate tissue controls. Sections show acanthosis, spongiosis with small intraepidermal vesicle formation, papillary dermal edema and a perivascular lymphocytic infiltrate with scattered eosinophils. There is focal vacuolar interface change. No viral inclusions are identified. Review of the PAS stained section fails to reveal any fungal elements.The lymphoid cells show immunoreactivity for CD2, CD3, CD5, CD4, CD7, and CD8 (less than CD4) with no significant decrease in pan-T antigens.  CD20 marks a few cells.  CD30 marks rare cells. The findings are not regarded as etiologically specific. Given the clinical history this could represent post- vaccination reactive changes / hypersensitivity reaction or possibly a drug eruption. The differential includes a chronic eczematous process. Considerations include contact dermatitis, nummular dermatitis, and atopic dermatitis.  Further clinical correlation is advised. This case was reviewed in consultation with Hematopathology and with Infectious Disease Pathology. This case was reviewed in consultation with a staff dermatologist-dermatopathologist at Medical Center.  M.D. Dermatopathology Microscopic Description Histologic sections of skin demonstrate slight acanthosis with spongiosis. The overlying cornified layer maintains a basket-weave configuration. Lymphohistiocytic inflammation is found predominantly surrounding superficial dermal vessels. Scattered eosinophils are also present.  A PAS stained slide does not reveal any definitive evidence of fungal elements. A rare subcorneal pustule is identified on the PAS stained slide. Clinical Diagnosis and History 34 yo male who developed an erythematous papular rash 20 days after SPV receipt.  Rash consists of multiple rounded (irregular) lesions on entire body from the neck down.  Concern for generalized  vaccinia was ruled out via negative PCR swabs and blood/serum testing by Lab. SYMPTOM_TEXT: My son was given the FluMist even though he was not the recommended minimum age (2yo). Prior to the administration of the FluMist the provider deferred to my judgement about the route of administration. A conversation was had about the benefits/costs of both mist and injection. The provider repeatedly said it was the same and continued to defer to my judgment. After she administered the FluMist she "remembered" that the minimum age for FluMist was 2yo and informed me that they would follow up with us about best course of action. Needless to say, I was furious.   My son started to experience significant symptoms 48 hours later, including coughing, congestion, mucous, and sneezing. My son is fairly healthy and has never experienced symptoms as significant as he did after receiving the FluMist. His symptoms lasted approximately 7 days. Because my son is only 1.5yo we only used babyVicks, humidifier, and childrens strength Sambucas (elderberry extract) as forms of treatment. My son is now fully recovered and does not appear to having any residual symptoms.
LAB_DATA: I did not take my son to the doctor to receive medical treatment. We provided in-home care.

The patient's medical history was not provided. The patient did not take any concomitant medications.  On 30-Sep-2019, the patient was administered Flucelvax QIV [Influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid, batch number: 261211 and expiration date: Jun-2020] for prevention of seasonal influenza. The patient stated that his left hand went numb and he had no strength. The patient also reported pain and loss of motor skills in his left arm. It was stated that doctors were calling this Parsonage-Turner syndrome. The patient consulted with Sports Medicine Doctor as the pain in his left arm was preventing him from sleeping. The reporter assessed the case as serious and did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIV.  Company comment: The patient experienced neuralgic amyotrophy week and a half after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIV. Chronology is plausible. No medical history and diagnostic findings were provided. Reportedly, the patient did not take any concomitant medications. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt called this morning at 10:46am to notify us of his adverse reaction to the vaccine.  Received vaccine 11/8/19 and on 11/9/19-11/10/19 he woke up with an odd headache, extremely blurry vision, and nausea.  Stated he was walking to his mailbox and his knees buckled as he got dizzy and fell into the snow (no reported injuries).  He said he continued falling after he got up and had to crawl into his house.  He has notified his MD and waiting to hear back.  I asked if he had checked his BP, he stated it was around 115/48 when he had checked that day.  I asked if he could have taken his BP medications twice on accident.  He said he is unsure and it was a possibility but he feels it was unlikely due to the BP meds and more of a reaction to the vaccination.  He has been advised to reach out to his MD and continue to monitor his BP.  Asked pt if he has had flu vaccinations in the past and he said "yearly with no issues."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: It started with a headache on Sat. at 11:00. I took Tylenol twice that day. That evening I felt worse and was running a temp. I continued to run a temp until Monday noon w/the highest recorded at 102.8. My arm became more sore and had a large red patch of skin It was very warm to the touch and burned. The patch became much larger and began traveling down my arm. I tried warm compresses and ice packs with no relief. I returned to work on Tues. as a teacher (10-8-19 and had my temp. taken in the morning. It was still at 99.5; I still did not feel 100%. The redness and swelling in my arm was spreading down my arm. By, Wednesday evening (10-8-19) the redness was subsiding and the pain is less. On Sunday (10-6-19), I became worried and phoned call-a-doc to seek medical help. He advised me to take a pic of my arm and send it to them. He then asked me to take a marker and draw a line around the redness and let him know if it continued to spread. He also advised me to take 600mg of Motrin every 6 hrs. I took pictures of my arm again on Monday (10-7-19) after the redness and swelling had spread more than an inch beyond the marked outline. They called me back today (10-9-19) to see how I was doing. I told them that I felt like it was finally getting some better and the pain was getting better. I have never had a reaction to a shot in the past.
OTHER_MEDS: methotrexate, folic acid, meloxicam, Mirapex, plaquenil

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A little over 24 hours after receiving her vaccine, patient broke out in hives on her forehead, right eyelid, left cheek, nose, and chin. The hives lasted for almost two weeks.  She was constipated for a week and a half after the vaccine, a problem she has never had before as she usually goes once a day. When she finally had a bowel movement it was runny and frequent, up to 5 or 6 times a day for a few days.  One week after the vaccine, as some of the hives were beginning to go away, she had an eczema breakout. Her skin was red and hot where patches of eczema were popping up. It was on her arms, legs, small spots on her back, and on her cheeks. In the creases of the backs of her knees and her ankles the skin would crack and bleed.  Almost a month has passed and the eczema has not gone away. Her skin stays rough in patches on her arms and legs and has flared up 2-3 times, lasting 3-4 days each time when it gets very red and hot and seems to itch. She still doesn?t have bowel movements regularly and gets very fussy. I called the pediatrician?s office after the reactions began and have sent them pictures of the hives but they did not need to see me in the office and no treatment was given. I have used moisturizer for the eczema daily.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Type II mixed cryoglobulinemia; cyanosis of the toes and fingers; nonpalpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers/worsening purpura; acral pain; digital ischemia/increasing acral ischemic symptoms; livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces; anorexia; night sweats; myalgias; fatigue; arthralgias; flu-like symptoms; leukocytoclastic vasculitis; Initial information received on 07-Nov-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case issued from a literature article.    Abstract: Influenza virus vaccineeinduced cryoglobulinemia has been reported in only 1 patient,1 whereas pneumococcal-induced cryoglobulinemia has never been described. Mixed cryoglobulinemia is a systemic inflammatory syndrome that is caused by the development of immunoglobulins that deposit at low temperatures affecting small and medium blood vessels and may manifest as either an inflammatory or noninflammatory vasculopathy.2 Multiple organs including the skin are most commonly affected.2 Mixed cryoglobulinemia has been regularly associated with Hepatitis C viral infection2 and may persist even when the infection has been eradicated. Vasculitides have been associated with vaccination. We report on a patient without prior immunologic disease whose disease occurred shortly after vaccination with influenza and pneumococcal vaccines, and persisted.  This case involves a 76 years old male patient who experienced type ii mixed cryoglobulinemia (cryoglobulinaemia) while he received vaccines PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE (PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE) and INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT).  The patient's past medical history included Vascular graft and Gastrooesophageal reflux disease. The patient's past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing Coronary artery disease and Hypercholesterolaemia.   On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT) produced by unknown manufacturer lot number not reported via unknown route in unknown administration site.  On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE not produced by Sanofi Pasteur lot number not reported via unknown route in unknown administration site.  On an unknown date, The patient developed a serious type ii mixed cryoglobulinemia (cryoglobulinaemia), flu-like symptoms (influenza like illness) and cyanosis of the toes and fingers (cyanosis) 5 days following the administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE. These events were assessed as medically significant.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious leukocytoclastic vasculitis (hypersensitivity vasculitis), purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers/worsening purpura (purpura), acral pain (pain), digital ischemia/increasing acral ischemic symptoms (ischaemia), livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces (livedo reticularis) Unknown latency following the administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE. These events were assessed as medically significant.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious anorexia (decreased appetite), night sweats (night sweats), myalgias (myalgia), fatigue (fatigue), arthralgias (arthralgia)  4 weeks following the administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE. These events were assessed as medically significant.  Relevant laboratory test results included: Blood immunoglobulin G - On an unknown date: 19 [19] Blood immunoglobulin M - On an unknown date: 64 [64]; on an unknown date: elevated [elevated] C-reactive protein - On an unknown date: 5.24 mg/dL [5.24] Complement factor C3 - On an unknown date: 75.50 mg/dL [75.50] Complement factor C4 - On an unknown date: <1.67 mg/dL [<1.67]; on an unknown date: low level mg/dL [low level] Red blood cell sedimentation rate - On an unknown date: 48 mm/h [48] Rheumatoid factor - On an unknown date: 24 iU/mL [24]; on an unknown date: 54 iU/mL [54] Total complement activity test (60 - 185) - On an unknown date: 28 [28]. A bone marrow biopsy finding was normal.  Final diagnosis was flu-like symptoms, leukocytoclastic vasculitis and type ii mixed cryoglobulinemia.   Corrective treamtnet: was initially treated with oral prednisone, 20 mg daily, which was increased 2 weeks later to 40 mg daily. Intravenous rituximab, 375 mg/mm2, was administered weekly for a total of 4 infusions (additional 2 infusions of rituximab were given monthly.). His acral lesions healed roughly 3 months after his last rituximab infusion. Prednisone, 40 mg daily, was continued throughout the first 3 months of his course and then slowly tapered and stopped 4 months after his last infusion of rituximab. Twenty months after his initial presentation, he began therapy with oral cyclophosphamide, 100 mg daily, and oral prednisone, 10 mg daily. 3 years after his presentation, his doses have been decreased to cyclophosphamide, 50 mg every other day, and prednisone, 5 mg daily.  The patient recovered from nonpalpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers/worsening purpura and outcome is reported as Recovering / Resolving from all other events.  Reporter's causality: based on the timing of the vaccination, constellation of symptoms, and positive laboratory results, influenza virus induced cryoglobulinemia is the most probable cause of our patient's symptoms.  There will be no information available on the batch number for this case.; Sender's Comments: A 76 years old male patient experienced cryoglobulinaemia along with associated  and non-associated events after vaccination with INFLUENZA VACCINE (TRIVALENT) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE. Time to onset is compatible with the role of the vaccines. Past medical history included Vascular graft and Gastrooesophageal reflux disease. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing Coronary artery disease and Hypercholesterolaemia. However, further information including concomitant medications, previous vaccination and tolerance would be needed to fully assess this case. Based on available information the role of an individual vaccine not be assessed.

atrial fibrillation; tachycardia/ fast heart rate; sore arm; knot/ large knot on arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of atrial fibrillation in a male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On 22nd June 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 25th June 2019, 3 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced atrial fibrillation (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and tachycardia (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the patient experienced pain in arm and skin mass. On an unknown date, the outcome of the atrial fibrillation and tachycardia were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the pain in arm was recovering/resolving and the outcome of the skin mass was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the atrial fibrillation, tachycardia, pain in arm and skin mass to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient provided only his first name and would not provide his last name or any contact information. The patient stated that, in the evening of Saturday, he received the Shingrix vaccine in left deltoid.  On Tuesday morning, he started experiencing a very fast heart rate, over 200. The patient went to the emergency room and was admitted to the hospital for atrial fibrillation. The patient never had atrial fibrillation.  He was shocked 3 times while at the hospital but he did not go back into normal rhythm. He finally went back into normal rhythm on his own. The patient had a few periods of tachycardia since this experience, but they did not last long enough to need treatment. The patient's heart tests were performed and it showed he was clear of blockages. He also noted that, less than a month after Shingrix vaccination, he had a large knot on his arm after the injection and his arm was very sore for 3.5 to 4 months and was a little sore till the reporting date. The patient mentioned his arm often hurts for 2 weeks after getting the flu shot (refer case ) and sometimes he would get that after the tetanus vaccine. The patient did not consent to follow-up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 11am the morning after (10/22) the pneumonia vaccine I had a complete lack of appetite and an increasing fever. Shortly after that I started to have deep full body muscle aches, chills and my right arm pain/redness/swelling was intensifying. By 6pm that day my fever was 102.6 and I started to vomit uncontrollably. I knew something was very wrong and went to Urgent Care. Between my fever, high pulse rate and elevated WBC count they sent me to the ER with what they perceived to be an infection. The ER got me in right away and were hesitant to diagnose an infection so quickly and indicated my immune system might just be having a strong reaction to the vaccine. They wanted me to keep an eye on the injection site and if it got worse I could start taking antibiotics but they warned me not to panic and often times it could look worse the next day. The next morning all my symptoms escalated/returned even worse than before and I had to be rushed back to the ER. This time I was diagnosed with Cellulitis and given IV antibiotics and a full work up of tests. After 7-10 days on 2 different antibiotics all my symptoms cleared up.
LAB_DATA: Over the course of these events I received countless blood tests (on 10/22, 10/23, 10/24 & 10/28), a blood culture test (on 10/23) and an ultrasound of my right arm (on 10/23).
OTHER_MEDS: Microgestin FE 1/20 Olmesartan Medoxomil 10mg Qvar 40mcg inhaler ProAir Albuterol inhaler Folic Acid B-12 D3 Krill Oil Red Yeast Rice Multivitamin Metamucil

On 28Oct2019 a surgery in her right arm was done and she had a cast on it and she did not feel good.  She needed her left arm really bad. She was not hospitalized and it was done in a surgery center. She had a Fiberclast cast on it and 22 stiches were pulled out. She was still recovering from that and she believed this cast will be on for two weeks. She said her arms were really skinny normally, she never had heavy arms. On 05Nov2019 patient stated it hurt where vaccine was put in, her left arm got all blown up; since an unspecified date she had  rash and lump. On 07Nov2019 patient saw her doctor who told her to take diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL). She did not take it and she went to his office. She said "there was one on one side of the elbow and one on the other side of the elbow and one where biceps are.  She doesn't have any biceps." Additional details were received as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. In a separate clinic on another day, it was noted that an HCP had given a patient Menveo with menA reconstituted with sterile water, not the menCWY diluent provided. These patients were then re-vaccinated with Menveo. This case 1 of 22 cases reported by the same reporter.

Type II mixed cryoglobulinemia/IgM kappa (k) monoclonal cryoglobulinemia with polyclonal IgG cryoglobulinemia; Leukocytoclastic vasculitis; Cyanosis of the Toes and Fingers; Flu-like symptoms; nonpalpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers/acral purpuric lesions; Necrosis of the distal finger; Acral pain; Digital ischemia/acral ischemic symptoms; livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces; anorexia; Night sweats; Myalgias; Fatigue; Arthralgia; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of acrocyanosis in a 76-year-old male patient who received Flu Seasonal TIV Dresden (Flu trivalent vaccine) for prophylaxis.    Co-suspect products included PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included coronary artery disease (bypass surgery), hypercholesterolemia and gastroesophageal reflux disease.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu trivalent vaccine at an unknown dose and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, 5 days after receiving Flu trivalent vaccine, the patient experienced acrocyanosis, cryoglobulinemia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), leukocytoclastic vasculitis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza-like symptoms, purpura, digital necrosis, pain localized, peripheral ischemia, livedo reticularis, anorexia, night sweat, myalgia, fatigue and arthralgia. The patient was treated with prednisone, rituximab and cyclophosphamide. On an unknown date, the outcome of the acrocyanosis, cryoglobulinemia, leukocytoclastic vasculitis, influenza-like symptoms, purpura, digital necrosis, pain localized, peripheral ischemia, livedo reticularis, anorexia, night sweat, myalgia, fatigue and arthralgia were unknown.   The reporter considered the acrocyanosis, cryoglobulinemia, leukocytoclastic vasculitis, influenza-like symptoms, purpura, digital necrosis, pain localized, peripheral ischemia, livedo reticularis, anorexia, night sweat, myalgia, fatigue and arthralgia to be probably related to Flu trivalent vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of type II mixed cryoglobulinemia, leukocytoclastic vasculitis and flu-like symptoms in a 76-year- old male patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified trivalent influenza vaccine and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (manufacturer unknown for both) for prophylaxis. The patient's medical history included coronary artery disease, bypass surgery, hypercholesterolemia, and gastroesophageal reflux disease. The patient had no prior immunologic disease. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified trivalent influenza vaccine and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided for both). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 75 or 76 years. On an unspecified date, at the age of 76 years, 5 days after the vaccinations, the patient presented with flu-like symptoms and cyanosis of the toes and fingers. The patient had nonpalpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers (necrosis of the distal finger) along with acral pain. The patient progressively had worsening purpura and digital ischemia along with livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces. Within 4 weeks, the patient had anorexia, night sweats, myalgias, fatigue, and arthralgias. A biopsy was offered and discussed with the patient, but the patient refused initially.  Laboratory evaluation found a normal complete blood count, normal urinalysis, comprehensive metabolic panel, negative antinuclear antibodies, antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, anticardiolipin antibodies, immunofixation electrophoresis, hepatitis A antibody, hepatitis B surface antigen, and hepatitis C antibody. The following test results were abnormal: rheumatoid factor: 24 (normal range: less than 20 IU/mL); total hemolytic complement level [CH50]: 28 (normal range: 60-185); complement component 3 (C3) level: 75.50 (normal range: more than 78 mg/dL); C4 level: less than 1.67 (normal range: more than 16 mg/dL); Westergren erythrocyte sedimentation rate: 48 (normal range: less than 20 mm/h), high sensitive C-reactive protein: 5.24 (normal range: less than 4.0 mg/dL); antiphosphatidylserine Immunoglobulin G (IgG): 19 (normal range, less than 11) and antiphosphatidylserine(IgM: 64 (normal range: less than 25). A chest radiograph and Doppler studies of blood flow of the extremities were also normal. Initial testing for cryoglobulins was negative. Two weeks later, the patient's rheumatoid factor was 54 IU/mL. The patient was initially treated with oral prednisone, 20 mg daily, which was increased 2 weeks later to 40 mg daily. However, the patient continued to develop new acral purpuric lesions and had increasing acral pain. Therefore, 6 weeks into this course, intravenous rituximab, 375 mg/mm2, was administered weekly for a total of 4 infusions. Because of limited clinical change, an additional 2 infusions of rituximab were given monthly. Cryoglobulins were detected for the first time at the end of his fourth infusion of rituximab. The patient's acral lesions healed (healing of toes and fingers) roughly 3 months after the patient's last rituximab infusion. Prednisone, 40 mg daily, was continued throughout the first 3 months of his course and then slowly tapered and stopped 4 months after his last infusion of rituximab. The patient's cryoglobulin level continued to be detectable, and 18 months after his initial presentation, he had increasing acral ischemic symptoms, and an elevated IgM level and low C4 level led to plans for another 4 rituximab infusions. However, before the second set of infusions, palpable purpura developed on his legs. Biopsy at that time found leukocytoclastic vasculitis, and direct immunofluorescence microscopy found IgG in the vessel walls. At that time, the patient was treated by service with oral prednisone, 40 mg daily, which was tapered and stopped over 3 weeks and the patient's hematologist administered another 4 weekly infusions of intravenous rituximab. The patient was seen at clinic (hematology), and a type II cryoglobulin was identified and characterized as IgM kappa (k) monoclonal cryoglobulinemia with polyclonal IgG cryoglobulinemia. A bone marrow biopsy finding was normal. Twenty months after the patient's initial presentation, he began therapy with oral cyclophosphamide, 100 mg daily, and oral prednisone, 10 mg daily. The patient's symptoms and clinical findings had been controlled with this regimen, and 3 years after his presentation, his doses had been decreased to cyclophosphamide, 50 mg every other day, and prednisone, 5 mg daily. Although the patient's symptoms and physical findings had remained controlled, his low level of C4 had persisted. The authors commented, "The mechanisms of vasculitis and cryoglobulinemia induced by the influenza or pneumococcal vaccination remain unknown. It was not possible to ascertain which vaccine responsible for this patient's disease, but it we propose that it was more likely caused by the viral vaccination. Mixed cryoglobulinemia was commonly associated with viral infections including hepatitis C virus (HCV), hepatitis B virus, or Epstein-Barr virus. The mechanism of viral-induced cryoglobulinemia is not completely understood but was postulated to be caused by cryoglobulin formation induced by cytokine or chemokine-mediated immune response to the HCV infection. It was not clear why cryoglobulins were produced as a response to a viral antigen was triggered in response to a vaccination. Studies have shown that mixed cryoglobulinemia can persist or recur after successful treatment of hepatitis C virus (HCV) without detectable hepatitis C virus ribonucleic acid (HCV RNA) in the serum yet detectable in the cryoprecipitate. Although a causal link with the influenza vaccination cannot be proved by our observation, we can speculate that based on the timing of the vaccination, constellation of symptoms, and positive laboratory results, influenza viruses induced cryoglobulinemia was the most probable cause of our patient's symptoms. Induction of cryoglobulin after viral stimulation may result in a prolonged disease. Early recognition and treatment can improve patients' long-term outcome. Further research was necessary to explore the possible immunopathogenic link due to the sequential nature of the disease following vaccinations."      Lab Comments: Lab tests done on an unknown date. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Missed abortion; Twin B non-viable; Twin A was blighted ovum; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case initially received on 06-Nov-2019, concerning a 28-year-old, pregnant female subject of body weight 126 lbs, height 60 inches and body mass index (BMI) 24.6 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had one previous pregnancy with elective abortion. No birth defects were noted. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-Aug-2019. The subject's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 12-Jun-2020 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 13-Jun-2020. The type of pregnancy was multiple.   The subject's current conditions included anxiety and attention deficit-hyperactivity disorder. The subject's concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (minerals NOS, vitamins NOS) for pregnancy and clonazepam for anxiety and attention deficit-hyperactivity disorder.  On 18-Oct-2019, at 6 weeks of gestation, the subject underwent dating ultrasound. As reported, intrauterine pregnancy was noted with uncertain cardiac activity. No MCMs were noted.  On 23-Oct-2019, at approximately 7 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Afluria QIV) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, cell cultured derived, batch number: P100123038, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.   On 02-Nov-2019, at approximately 8.1 weeks of gestation, the subject underwent ultrasound and non-viable twin pregnancy was noted,  twin A was blighted ovum, and no cardiac activity for twin B. No MCMs were noted.  On the same day, the subject received misoprostol at a dose of 200 mcg and had missed abortion due to non-viable pregnancy with both twins.   On 04-Nov-2019, the subject underwent complete blood count with differential, type and screen. The complete blood count was reported as normal. Positive Rh factor was noted.   The case was assessed as serious.   The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria Quadrivalent.  Company comment: The subject experienced foetal death, anembryonic gestation and abortion missed 10 days after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at gestational age of 7 weeks. Chronology is unsuggestive but plausible. Clonazepam as concomitant medication may provide alternative aetiology due to its known harmful pharmacological effects on pregnancy and the foetus/newborn child. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For events foetal death, anembryonic gestation and abortion missed, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced foetal death, anembryonic gestation and abortion missed 10 days after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria QIV. On 14th August 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, 21 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced itchy rash. The patient was treated with methylprednisolone (Medrol). On an unknown date, the outcome of the itchy rash was unknown. The patient started to have a rash that extended from back of his neck to his back and the rash was itchy. The patient consented to follow up. This case has been linked with case US2019AMR206374, reported by the same reporter.

blockage in intestine; condition aggrevated; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of intestinal obstruction in a 76-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included colostomy (experienced 5 months before the date of reporting). Concurrent medical conditions included intestinal obstruction and scar.   On 2nd October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than a month after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced intestinal obstruction (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and condition aggravated (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the intestinal obstruction was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the condition aggravated was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the intestinal obstruction and condition aggravated to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix on an unknown arm. The patient could not remember which arm she received either dose of Shingrix. It was reported that, sometimes in between dose 1 and dose 2 of Shingrix, the patient was hospitalized for 4 days due to a blockage in her intestine. It was reported that, the patient gets these blockages from time to time in her intestine due to scar tissue that was there prior to receiving Shingrix.  The reporter did not consent to follow-up. This was 1 of the 2 cases reported by same reporter.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Colostomy (experienced 5 months before the date of reporting)

Patient came in for their Pneumovax23 immunization. Filled out Questionaire and sat down for their immunization. Immunization was given, pt had no initial reaction. Patient got up and felt fine. Had no issues. Walked away without assistance about 20 steps, Then started feeling dizzy, lightheaded, and warm. Came back to the pharmacy and patient sat down. Upon return, patient was flushed, stated back was hurting. After sitting down, I told the patient to take a deep breathe as I noticed she wasn't taking any conscious breathes. Once she took a deep breathe, the flushing went away and pt stated they started feeling better. Asked patient if she was feeling anything. Stated her back was hurting and was experiencing muscle spasms. She took a few more deep breathes and was feeling better and better with each breathe she took she stated. Pt drank some water and felt better. Talked to the patient and she said she had an intense zumba class this morning and that she hasn't done it in a long time and that it was exhausting. Stated she didn't drink much water today so may have been dehydrated. She asked, what could it be. Told her it didn't seem to be immunization related. I told her, she has been "running around" all day and had a strenuous workout this morning. With her, "resting and sitting down" for the immunization, her body was resting and her getting up, her body possibly just tightened up out of no where. After about 10 minutes, she said she felt fine. Asked her if she wanted us to call 911 to be sure, even though the patient was feeling better. She said, "No, that wouldn't be necessary, she was feeling better." No complications the patient was feeling she stated.. No dizziness or flushing. No warm feelings. Pt stated her back went from a 7 on a pain scale down to a 2, but had no issues or complications after. Talked with the patient some more, she said she felt fine. She stated she felt well enough to leave. Told me if she started to feel anything, she will pull over to the side of the road and call her daughter. She said, "I'm feeling fine". Asked her if she wanted us to call anyone. She said, "No, she was feeling fine." Had no issues she could feel at the moment. Had Pharmacy Technician walk her out to her car to be sure in case anything happened again or if she had any reaction or feeling again. Patient made it out to her car and pharmacy Technician stated pt was doing well. Called patient once she got home safely at 5:56pm and pt stated she felt fine. Stated didn't have a proper lunch today, a big cup of coffee, and a small breakfast. Patient said she was going to take her blood pressure and blood glucose. Those numbers were BS:154, BP: 152/86 Pulse: 65. Says she is feeling anxious. Called back at 6:51pm. Patient stated was feeling a lot better, looked back at her daily food log. Didn't eat lunch. Felt she threw her own body a curveball and didn't adequately hydrate and eat well today. Doing well she said. About to eat her dinner and had no questions.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D3, Metformin ER 500mg, Levothyroxine 75mcg, Lisinopril, Janumet 50mg-500mg.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: she could breathe, however "felt like was being strangled as if something were around neck; feel pain under her right arm; felt her lymph nodes were swollen under her arms and neck; she was administered a dose ofMMR II when she was a child/she had another dose of MMR II administerd on 10/11/2019; she developed rash on her chest, arms, trunk and legs; she developed rash on her chest, arms, trunk and legs; she developed rash on her chest, arms, trunk and legs; she developed rash on her chest, arms, trunk and legs; her eyes became sensitive; she felt very lethargic; her joints were very painful especially in her hands and fingers and lower back; her joints were very painful especially in her hands and fingers and lower back; her joints were very painful especially in her hands and fingers and lower back; her joints were very painful especially in her hands and fingers and lower back; she had swelling in her hands and feet; pain in her feet; numbness in her hands and feet; she had titers for Measles and Mumps; she had titers for Measles and Mumps; the titer for Rubella was low; This spontaneous report was received from a 67 year-old-female consumer referring to herself. Her pertinent medical history included Crohn's disease, hypothyroidism, low estrogen and chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL). There was no information about drug reactions or allergies. Concomitant therapies included mercaptopurine (6-MP), levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID) and estradiol (VAGIFEM).     The patient was vaccinated with a dose of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) (unknown lot/expiration date) on an unspecified date when she was a child. The patient had titers drawn on an unknown date in September 2019 and results showed that she had titers for measles and mumps, but the titer for rubella was low. On 11-OCT-2019, the patient was vaccinated with another dose of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) (rHA) (lot # N032751, expiration date: 20-NOV-2019; dose and route were not reported) administrated in the right arm for prophylaxis (reported as revaccination).      On 21-OCT-2019 (reported as 10 days later), the patient began to feel pain under her right arm and felt her lymph nodes were swollen under her arms and neck. On an unknown date a few days after that she developed rash on her chest, arms, trunk and legs, her eyes became sensitive, she felt very lethargic, her joints were very painful especially in her hands and fingers and lower back, she had swelling in her hands and feet, pain in her feet, numbness in her hands and feet, her hands felt as if they were asleep and she was sometimes unable to feel them and she was unable to make a fist. The patient sought medical attention by seeing her primary doctor and her hematologist on 22-OCT-2019. The patient was not given treatment. On 25-OCT-2019 (at the end of the week), she could breathe, however she felt like was being strangled as if something were around neck. The patient reported that the pain in her lower back has since subsided. She was still experiencing the swelling in her hands and feet, the pain in her feet, the numbness in her hands and feet, she still had some of the rash on her legs and her joints in her fingers were very painful. The patient would be rechecked the lymph nodes on 07-NOV-2019. The outcome of rash on her chest, arms, trunk and back pain was resolved. The outcome of the other events was not resolved. The causality between the events and measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) was not reported.

This triggered the diagnosis of severe combined immunodeficiency, and the patient was subsequently treated with stem cell transplants. Post-transplant, the patient continued to have rotavirus (detected by routine lab, presumed to be persistent vaccine strain) and received additional experimental treatment in attempt to clear rotavirus. The outcome of the events was unknown. The causality between severe combined immunodeficiency and rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) was not reported. The reporter considered that rotavirus infection to be related to rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ).  Upon internal review, severe combined immunodeficiency syndrome was determined to be medically significant.  As of 12-NOV-2019, all telephone attempts to obtain follow-up information have been unsuccessful. SYMPTOM_TEXT: SUBJECTIVE: The patient is a 36 yo female who is here today for a flu vaccine.  The Pt. denied any allergies except Latex and Ibuprofen.   She received Fluarix  Quadrivalent, ZZ772  Exp. 6/30/20 given in right deltoid at 8:42 AM.  Five min. after the vaccine the Pt. started C/O itching on her back.   She denied any lip tingling/swelling or trouble breathing.   She didn't disclose any other allergies until after the vaccine had been given.  Once she started feeling itchy she admitted that she had been allergy tested and was very sensitive to Balsam of Peru and slightly sensitive to polysorbate 80.  OBJECTIVE. Red flat 20 plus blotches appeared on the back of her neck and mid scapular area 5 min after injection. One, three cm sized hive on her right arm 3 inches from the injection site after injection.   No redness or swelling or itching around the injection site at 10 min after injection. Palpable fine rash and redness noted on left shoulder 10 min. after the injection. Palpable fine ash on right side of face 10 min after injection.  VITALS: Pulse 80 Respirations 14 Airway patent and lungs clear BP not taken (We do not have a BP cuff large enough)  Denies being pregnant - on OCPS LMP: 10/19   ASSESSMENT:  Possible allergic reaction to Fluviarx (contains polysorbate - 80)  PLAN. 1.  Diphenhydramine  25 mg given PO STAT.  Epi pen was on hand. 2.  Manager notified by the Pt. that she was having an allergic reaction to the flu vaccine. 3.  Pt. was observed for one hour after given 25 milligrams of diphenhydramine po. 4.  Pt. advised she could RTW after an hour of observation but if the itching started again that she should go      straight to the ED. 5.  Pt. advised should let her PCP and allergist know about today's allergic reaction. 6.  Pt. was given a list of all the flu vaccines and what each one contains and advised to share with her       physicians.   7.  Pt.  was advised to clarify with her allergist if she can have the Fluzone Quadrivalent vaccine in the future as it       is polysorbate - 80 free.  The Fluvarix Quadravalent that the patient received did contain polysorbate - 80. 8.  Redness and itching started to resolve 15 min after administration of Diphenhydramine but still pink rash at 1 hour after meds. 9.  Pt.  states she understands and agrees with the plan of care.  FOLLOW - UP DONE: The Pt. was called an two hours after the allergic reaction and 6 hours after the reaction for f/u.  She stated she no longer felt itchy and the hive and rashes were still improving.
CUR_ILL: Anxiety disorder, GERD, Insomnia, PCOS, Obesity
ALLERGIES: Latex, Ibuprofen, Polysorbate - 80, Balsam of Peru

The red area had little dots so has been checking whether shingles would develop.  One night, patient reports waking up and blood pressure was very high (~180/80); during the day would rise on and off.  Patient went to pharmacist around the week of 10/28, told to follow-up with doctor if symptoms continue. On 11/6 a rash under both breast started; site was painful, itching, and burning. Also had times when blood  pressure was very low (~100/50).   Patient felt terrible, used Claritin, Tylenol, put baking soda on affected sites, was tired, and had a headache. Nausea had resolved by then.  On 11/10, patient went to pharmacist to show breasts; patient told to follow-up with doctor.   On 11/14 patient went to see the doctor; there was no testing and doctor recommended continuing with same care--provided no treatment.  Doctor specified symptoms are related to vaccine reaction. This is the 3rd day that the rash on breasts is drying out.  Today, patient obtained lot number from pharmacist.   Today,  red area still on arm still there and a bit pin painful, under breast rash is drying off,  no nausea, not as fatigued and no headache.  Recovery at 75%.

On an unknown date, shortly after receiving the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered right ear pain that radiated down the right side of her neck and was diagnosed with otitis media. On an unknown date, shortly after, she was diagnosed with irreversible pulpitis with symptomatic apical periodontitis which required a root canal. She continued to experience severe pain after the root canal and was diagnosed with trigeminal neuralgia. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, the patient's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. She also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of vaccination, she sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result, she suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered. The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The events were considered to be disabling.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Midly confused, had trouble comprehending conversation and tracking the newspaper articles; Unusually tired.; Lethargic could scarcely function; Fell; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of lethargy in a 91-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (had 10 years before sever shingles) and shingles (had mild shingles last year). Concurrent medical conditions included blood pressure abnormal, vascular insufficiency and nerve pain (Taking Lyrica ). Concomitant products included pregabalin (Lyrica).   On 30th October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 31st October 2019, 1 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced lethargy and fall. On 1st November 2019, the patient experienced confusion and fatigue. On an unknown date, the outcome of the lethargy, fall, confusion and fatigue were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the lethargy, fall, confusion and fatigue to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received dose of Shingrix in the late afternoon and experienced no ill effect tiil the reminder day. The next day after vaccination , the patient found herself so lethargic, could scarcely function. The patient took slept in until noon, took a four hour nap during the day. The patient was getting ready for bed felt and in less than twelve hours laterthe next morningshe felt again. The next day, the patient was mildly confused, had trouble comprehending conversation and tracking the newspaper articles, and continued to be unusually tired. The patient was alert and oriented, until was administered vaccine. It took until the third day after the immunization for her return to normal. Due to these side effects, the patient did not took 2nd dose of Shingrix. Till the time of reporting, the patient still recovering from fall and  could not risk another.
CUR_ILL: Blood pressure abnormal; Nerve pain (Taking Lyrica); Vascular insufficiency
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Shingles (had mild shingles last year); Shingles (had 10 years before sever shingles)

Pt slumped & became limp as dad was lifting her. Pt never lost consciousness, but became limp, pale, & unresponsive to verbal commands for aprox 30-40 seconds. No sz activity was noted & pt had her eyes open the entire time. Pt was placed on exam table & help was called. Pt immediately became responsive verbally & physically and color returned to her face. Pt was A&Ox3. Vitals @ 2:37pm were: B/P 82/64, temp 98.5F, HR 82, O2 98% & blood sugar 108. Pt's dad stated that "the same thing happened to me after getting my blood drawn in college & they found that I had a heart murmur. But it hasn't happened since then." Pt was evaluated by FNP & no heart murmur was noted. Dad stated that pt "had a late lunch & candy" when asked when had pt last eaten. Both writer & FNP stated & stressed importance of pt eating a meal with protein & less sugar after leaving clinic & pt being evaluated by her primary physician & or urgent care center asap. Dad verbalized understanding. At aprox 2:50pm, writer assisted pt & dad to check out & pt was noted to be walking independently & playing down the hallway by jumping from tile to tile to "avoid stepping on the tile cracks". 11/18/19 FU PC to dad. Dad stated pt was "sick all weekend with her temp going up to 102 degrees", however, she was given Tylenol & fever went down. Dad states that her mother "is currently taking care of her." Writer strongly urged either him or pt's (M) to take pt to her primary pediatrician or urgent care today to be evaluated. Dad verbalized understanding & stated that pt's "mother is supposed to be taking care of that." Dad states that pt has been "jumping around" & playing despite being sick & denies any further problems or needs @ this time.

Chlamydia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 04-Nov-2019, concerning a 31-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 136 lbs, height: 63 inches and body mass index (BMI): 24.1 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's obstetrical history was collected and it was noted that the subject did not have any previous pregnancies, nor maternal and paternal history with major congenital malformation (MCM). The subject did not consume tobacco, alcohol and illicit-drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's medical history was not provided. The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamin (unspecified vitamins) for unknown indication.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 23-May-2019, and estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 27-Feb-2020. The corrected estimated date of delivery was not reported. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 15-Aug-2019, the subject performed Sequential 1 and Nuchal translucency prenatal tests and no MCM was noted.  On 12-Sep-2019, the subject performed Sequential 2 and no MCM was noted.  On 10-Oct-2019, the subject underwent targeted ultrasound and bilateral choroid plexus cysts were noted.  On the same date, at gestational age of 20 weeks, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Afluria QIV) [Influenza Vaccine, batch number: P100112488, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiry date: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On 05-Nov-2019, pregnancy status was collected, and it was noted that the subject was positive to chlamydia. No further details were reported.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event was not reported.   This case was assessed as serious (medically significant).   The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  This case is linked to 201905904, the corresponding child case.  Company comment: The subject experienced chlamydial infection after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at gestational age of 20 weeks. Chronology is plausible. Pregnant state may have contributed to development of the event. They advised us to bring her to the emergency room, since she was at risk for becoming dehydrated and we didn?t know what was causing the vomit. Since she had received the flu vaccine that morning, I imagined there could be a correlation.
LAB_DATA: The emergency room doctor and nurses observed her, decided that Zofran would help stop the vomiting, so gave her a dose, observed her, and sent us home with more doses for the following day. The next day, she developed diarrhea (but did stop vomiting).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: How could I possibly know which arm took which shot, the dose number of the vaccines and/or the manufacturers of the vacs?  Adverse Events: Within two hours of receiving the final vaccination on Oct. 9th, 2019, my face became red and somewhat rough to the touch. A particularly affected area was the skin around (both under and above) my eyes and between my eyebrows. This redness was noticeable enough for a friend I was visiting with that day who had no idea I received the vaccinations asked if I had been in a tanning bed. As the days progressed, the skin surrounding my eyes began flaking off from extreme dry skin. The redness and rough, dry skin continued down my entire face, beneath my chin and on the front of my neck. About a week later this red/dry skin condition was mostly gone. This said, since the vaccinations I have been experiencing unexplained patches itching on different places on my body. This itching shows up as small hive-like bumps surrounded by redness. As this skin condition comes and goes without warning, it is beyond difficult to schedule any examination to take place while symptomatic. Last night, Nov. 18, 2019 was my most recent experience with this itching.
CUR_ILL: Yes. I had a severe cold in September.
HISTORY: Breast cancer survivor (4 years post-op). Currently cancer free and no other med conditions
ALLERGIES: No allergies to meds. Seasonal, dust and some fresh vegetable allergies.

Fever and myalgia that started 24 hours later.  As a physician, I assumed these to be normal and expected side effects. However, I had progressive worsening of muscle pain and stiffness that limited my ability to function.  Ten days after the vaccination,  I developed tetany of my elbows and could not straighten them at all for about 10 minutes and it took about 6 hours for that to completely resolve.  I was severely affected for 6-8 weeks with horrible muscle pain and stiffness.  The latter was so bad that I had trouble standing from a seated position and exercise performance deteriorated.  My energy level declined.  My hair started falling out.  It took a full 3 months for me to return to my level of functioning and relative pain free state that I was enjoying in the 2 weeks prior to my Shingrix shot.   I had difficulties with muscle pain and stiffness for about 7 years prior to the vaccination, however, my symptoms had improved tremendously over the last several years and I was nearly asymptomatic at the time of the injection.  I do not know if this was a true adverse reaction to the Shingrix shot or if the Shingrix vaccination really exacerbated my underlying condition.
