seronegative autoimmune hepatitis; right upper quadrant (RUQ) abdominal pain; jaundice; intermittent low grade fever; Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 18-Oct-2019.  Literature citation-  The following is the abstract from the article-  Acute seronegative autoimmune hepatitis is a rare entity but has been reported in the literature. Few cases have been reported where hepatitis occured after yellow fever vaccine. We present a case of acute seronegative autoimmune hepatitis (SAIH) that has probable association with yellow fever vaccine as indicated by the patient's strong history.  This case involves a 35 years old female patient who experienced seronegative autoimmune hepatitis (autoimmune hepatitis), while she received vaccine YELLOW FEVER VACCINE.  The patient's past vaccination(s) included yellow fever vaccine. The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s) and family history were not provided.  On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect YELLOW FEVER VACCINE produced by unknown manufacturer lot number not reported via unknown route in unknown administration site.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious right upper quadrant (RUQ) abdominal pain (abdominal pain upper), seronegative autoimmune hepatitis (autoimmune hepatitis), (Unknown latency) following the administration of YELLOW FEVER VACCINE. This event was assessed as medically significant. The patient was hospitalized for this event.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious jaundice and intermittent low grade fever (pyrexia) (Unknown latency) following the administration of YELLOW FEVER VACCINE. The patient was hospitalized for this event.  On an unknown date, the patient was discharge from the hospital.  Relevant laboratory test results included: Alanine aminotransferase - On an unknown date: 2189 [2189]; on an unknown date: 1146 [1146]; on an unknown date: 603 [603]; on an unknown date: 78 [78] Aspartate aminotransferase - On an unknown date: 2135 [2135]; on an unknown date: 1087 [1087]; on an unknown date: 374 [374]; on an unknown date: 67 [67] Bilirubin conjugated abnormal - On an unknown date: 1.8 [1.8]; on an unknown date: 12.5 [12.5]; on an unknown date: 10.2 Blood albumin - On an unknown date: 3.6 [3.6]; on an unknown date: 2.7 [2.7] Blood alkaline phosphatase - On an unknown date: 213 [213]; on an unknown date: 132 [132]; on an unknown date: 83 [83] Blood bilirubin - On an unknown date: 2.5 [2.5]; on an unknown date: 20.7 [20.7]; on an unknown date: 19.1; on an unknown date: 3.6 [3.6] International normalised ratio - On an unknown date: 1.3 [1.3] Platelet count - On an unknown date: 13.2 [13.2] Protein total - On an unknown date: 7.9 [7.9]; on an unknown date: 7 [7]  (Other relevant tests included CT abdomen was unremarkable for biliary system abnormalities Her viral panel (HSV, EBV, HIV, Hepatitis A-D serology) and autoimmune work-up (ANA, anti DNA, anti smooth muscle, anti mitochondrial, SSA, SSB antibodies turned) were negative. PCR for Yellow fever virus was negative as well. Liver biopsy showed severe chronic active hepatitis (grade III) without fibrosis (grade 0) but with extensive periportal necroinflammatory changes, hence, a working diagnosis of SAIH was made.)  Final diagnosis was Mild seronegative autoimmune hepatitis  The patient was treated with 1 gm METHYLPREDNISOLONE SODIUM SUCCINATE (SOLUMEDROL) and PREDNISONE (PREDNISONE) 40 mg daily. They were able to taper her steroids in the next 4 months with maintenance treatment of 5mg Prednisone.  The outcome of the event was Unknown for all the events.  Conclusion: It is concluded that given the history of this patient, the possibility of association of yellow fever vaccine inducing acute flare of autoimmune hepatitis cannot be ruled out. Further studies to unearth this rare association in detail are warranted. Type 2 mixed cryoglobulinemia; Leukocytoclastic vasculitis; This is a literature case, initially received from physician on 11-Nov-2019, concerning a 76-year-old, male patient.  The patient's historical conditions included bypass surgery. The patient's current conditions included hypercholesterolemia, coronary artery disease and gastroesophageal reflux disease. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.  On an unspecified date, the patient was administered unspecified Flu Vaccine [Influenza virus vaccine trivalent; anatomical location, route of administration, dose, batch number and expiration date: not reported] for an unknown indication.   On an unspecified date, the patient was administered co-suspect unspecified pneumococcal vaccine [pneumococcal vaccine; anatomical location, route of administration, dose, batch number and expiration date: not reported] for an unknown indication.  On an unspecified date, reported as 5 days after vaccination, the patient experienced flu-like symptoms and cyanosis. The patient developed non-palpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers along with acral pain. He progressively had worsening purpura and digital ischemia along with livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces.  On an unspecified date, within 4 weeks, the patient developed anorexia, night sweats, myalgias, fatigue and arthralgias. The patient refused biopsy. Laboratory evaluation found a normal complete blood count, normal urinalysis, normal comprehensive metabolic panel, negative antinuclear antibodies, negative antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, negative anticardiolipin antibodies, negative immunofixation electrophoresis, negative hepatitis A antibody, negative hepatitis B surface antigen, and negative hepatitis C antibody. The following test results were abnormal: rheumatoid factor was 24 IU/mL (reference range less than 20); total hemolytic complement level [CH50] was 28, units unspecified (reference range 60-185); C3 level was 75.50 mg/dL (reference range more than 78); C4 level was less than 1.67 mg/dL (reference range more than 16); Westergren erythrocyte sedimentation rate was 48 mm/h (reference range less than 20), high sensitive C-reactive protein was 5.24 mg/dL (reference range less than 4); anti-phosphatidylserine IgG was 19, units unspecified (reference range less than 11); and anti-phosphatidylserine IgM was 64, units unspecified (reference range less than 25). A chest radiograph and Doppler studies of blood flow of the extremities were also normal. Initial testing for cryoglobulins was negative. The patient was treated with oral prednisone at the dose of 20 mg, daily.  On an unspecified date, two weeks later, the patient's rheumatoid factor was 54 IU/mL. The dose for the prednisone was increased at the dose of 40 mg, administered once per day. The patient continued to develop new acral purpuric lesions and had increasing acral pain.   On an unspecified date, 6 weeks into his course, the patient was administered treatment medication rituximab intravenously, at a dose of 375 mg/mm2, weekly for a total of 4 infusions. Because of the limited clinical change, an additional 2 infusions of rituximab were given monthly.  On an unspecified date, at the end of fourth infusion of rituximab, cryoglobulins were detected for the first time.  On an unspecified date, roughly 3 months after last rituximab infusion, the patient's acral lesions healed. Prednisone at the dose of 40 mg, daily was continued throughout the first 3 months of the course and then slowly tapered and stopped 4 months after his last infusion of rituximab. His cryoglobulin level continued to be detectable.  On an unspecified date, 18 months after initial presentation, the patient had increasing acral ischemic symptoms. Elevated IgM level and low C4 level led to plans for another 4 rituximab infusions. However, before the second set of infusions, palpable purpura developed on his legs. Biopsy at this time found leukocytoclastic vasculitis, while direct immunofluorescence microscopy found IgG in the vessel walls. The patient was treated with oral prednisone at the dose of 40 mg daily, which was tapered and stopped over 3 weeks and his hematologist administered another 4 weekly infusions of intravenous rituximab. The patient was seen at Clinic (hematology), and a type II cryoglobulin was identified and characterized as IgM k monoclonal cryoglobulinemia with polyclonal IgG cryoglobulinemia. A bone marrow biopsy finding was normal.   On an unspecified date, twenty months after initial presentation, the patient began therapy with oral cyclophosphamide at the dose of 100 mg daily, and oral prednisone at the dose of 10 mg daily. His symptoms and clinical findings have been controlled with this regimen.  On an unspecified date, 3 years after the presentation, doses for the treatment medications were decreased to cyclophosphamide at the dose of 50 mg every other day, and prednisone at the dose of 5 mg daily. Although his symptoms and physical findings have remained controlled, his low level of C4 has persisted, and the patient was recovering from the events.  The case was assessed as serious.   The reporter assessed the event of type 2 mixed cryoglobulinemia as related to unspecified Flu vaccine while the causality assessment for the event of leukocytoclastic vasculitis was not reported. It was reported that it was not possible to ascertain which vaccine was responsible for the patient's disease, but it was more likely caused by viral vaccination. Although a causal link with the influenza vaccination cannot be proved by reporter's observation, they could speculate that based on the timing of the vaccination, constellation of symptoms, and positive laboratory results, influenza virus-induced cryoglobulinemia was the most probable cause of patient's symptoms.  Company comment: The patient has experienced cryoglobulinaemia and hypersensitivity vasculitis associated with the suspect product - INN Flu Vaccine. Chronology seems plausible. It was reported that it was not possible to ascertain which vaccine was responsible for the patient's disease, but it was more likely caused by viral vaccination. Although a causal link with the influenza vaccination cannot be proved by reporter's observation, they could speculate that based on the timing of the vaccination, constellation of symptoms, and positive laboratory results, influenza virus-induced cryoglobulinemia was the most probable cause of patient's symptoms. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. Leucocytoclastic vasculitis is seen in cryoglobulinaemia and infection is a very important cause of this disease and parasites (toxoplasmosis, malaria), bacteria (streptococcus, syphilis, Lyme disease) and fungi (coccidiomyocosis) have all been associated with this disease. Viruses such as cytomegalovirus (CMV), HIV, Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) and in particular; hepatitis A, B, and C (or chronic liver disease) are also important causes. 61-year-old gentleman with a history significant for HTN & HLD who presented with proximal bilateral lower extremity paresis of 1 day duration.  While he was still able to walk, he noted that his thighs felt weak and his knees kept buckling.  He has had multiple falls since the onset without serious injury.  His weakness had been worsening, prompting him to go to the ED for management.  He is noted tingling in the bilateral toes without sensory changes in the upper extremity.  MRI of thoracic and lumbar spine demonstrated enhancement of the cauda equina nerve roots.  Lumbar puncture demonstrated cytoalbuminologic dissociation.  He had received the influenza and shingles vaccine 10 days prior to onset of symptoms.  He was admitted to the General Neurology Service.
LAB_DATA: It was felt that the most likely diagnosis was AIDP given his areflexia, proximal greater than distal weakness and sensory changes which was also supported by his peripheral nerve enhancement and CSF findings.  He was started on a course 2 g/kg IV immunoglobulin.  Over time, his exam worsened to include proximal upper extremity weakness and mild progression of sensory changes.  However, by the time of discharge, he had improving strength. Throughout his stay, he had no bulbar symptoms, autonomic dysfunction, or respiratory weakness.  He was discharged to acute rehab.  He will follow up in Neurology after completion of an EMG to continue his clinical monitoring.  Given that his AIDP was in the setting of recent vaccination, it was recommended that he not receive further influenza vaccination and consider not completing his shingles vaccination. Certainly, if he were to develop worsening weakness, respiratory changes or dysphagia, he should return to the hospital. As the stay progressed, he developed significant back of the leg pain at night, possibly consistent with a radiculopathy. On the night prior to discharge, he did not respond to 300 mg of gabapentin and we would recommend increasing to 600 mg of gabapentin at bedtime with PRN gabapentin, tylenol and limited NSAIDs available.  � Operative Procedures Performed  Basic labs, LP with labs  PT/OT c/s, Respiratory therapy,  � Diagnostics:  CSF:WBC 1, RBC 109, protein 83, glucose 62, NGTD, no oligoclonal bands, normal IgG index � Imaging: � MRI T/L-spine 10/06/2019: 1. Postcontrast enhancement of the cauda equina with enhancing nerve roots exiting laterally at S1 and S2 most suggestive of arachnoiditis. �This could be infectious or inflammatory in its origin.  2. Mild multifocal degenerative disk disease in the thoracic and lumbar spine without associated foraminal or canal narrowing.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1. Night of the vaccine, 11/12/19, chills, extreme shivers, slight fever of one degree, malaise, inability to sleep, muscle soreness all over body. 2. Next day 11/13/19, shivers and fever subsided, continued malaise and muscle soreness. Appearance of very dark bruise at injection site. 3. Next day, 11/14/19, felt better in terms of malaise but  a  raised, pink, hot rash appeared 2 inches BELOW the injection site. The rash was approx 4 inches horizontally across upper outer left arm and approx 3 inched lengthwise. So a rectangle of 4"x3," appearing as if someone had slapped me hard laterally across the arm. It felt warm to the touch. It did NOT itch. It was very marked and surprising to anyone who saw it. I called the pharmacist who said that as long as it faded and I felt ok that it was possibly a reaction from the vaccination but that would go away on its own. Since I did FEEL better and was not in pain, I decided to wait and see rather than go to my doctor.  Over the next several days, it gradually faded away without issue. Today 11/20/19 it is only barely visible as a slight pink blush. The blue bruise is fading but is still quite visible at the injection site.

Flu vaccine - not sure what kind.  Paper simply says Influenza Vaccine Inactivated or Recombinant.  Patient was given shot and became increasingly combative and ripped out his IV twice.  He was on a Milrinone drip at the time.  He was first given benadryl in an attempt to allow him to sleep.  His agitation got worse over several more hours.  He was then given 0.5mg of ativan IV push.  He immediately fell asleep.  The next morning it was discovered that he failed to regain full consciousness and was extremely lethargic and difficult to arouse.  It was assumed at the time that this was the result of the ativan not clearing his system.  However, over the course of the day, he remained unconscious for the most part without any signs of improvement.  Suspecting the vaccine was causing encephalitis, he was given 200mg of Ibuprofen at 4:30pm that day.  His condition slowly started improving and he became increasingly easier to arouse.  By the next morning, he was able to open his eyes spontaneously and walk with assistance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was given Afluria Vaccine at 3 months old at Flu Line. (no adverse symptoms)

Pt relates that the area that the shot was given got red, irritated and scabbed starting the day after(10/1/2019). He says he used Neosporin on it. He came in late afternoon yesterday(11/20/2019) to report it and there was a small red mark on his arm. I related due to his concerns that he could see his provider and that I would report it.

The evening of the vaccination I began to experience some achiness in my neck and shoulders.  Overnight I developed a crushing headache, fever, the achiness spread to my entire body and I felt nauseous.  I also had the sore arm which was totally expected given the intramuscular injection.  I went to work the following morning but had to leave early as the symptoms continued to increase to an unmanageable level.  The headache intensified and the fever rose.  I couldn't lift my head to do anything.  I am now on the second day post-vaccination and most of the symptoms still remain but at a much more manageable level.  I did not seek any medical treatment for the symptoms, living alone and being as sick as I was I couldn't have even if I needed to.

On 08-Nov-2019, seventeen days after vaccination, the patient came back to the Emergency Room with gross motor function deterioration. A spinal tap was performed. Allergic Reaction; Throat tightness; Chest Tightness; Low Blood Pressure; Diffused Hives; Ears Tightness; 3 Injections Given; Initial Report Received on 08-Nov-2019  A 26-year-old female nurse (race not reported) reportedly received 3 injections of HEPLISAV-B (hepatitis B vaccine) for hepatitis B immunization and developed an unknown allergic reaction.   Relevant medical history and concomitant medications were not provided.   On 30-Aug-2019, the patient received the first injection of Heplisav-B (lot #, expiration date, and NDC # not reported). The vaccine was administered via a prefilled syringe.   On 30-Sep-2019, the patient received the second injection of Heplisav-B (lot #933841, expiration date, and NDC # not reported). The vaccine was administered via a prefilled syringe.   On 31-Oct-2019, the patient received the third injection of Heplisav-B (lot #399838, expiration date, and NDC # not reported). The vaccine was administered via a prefilled syringe.   On 08-Nov-2019, Dynavax received a voicemail from a nurse. The nurse reported that they had a female nurse in her 20-30s that received her first dose of HEPLISAV-B on 30-Aug-2019, that they forgot to chart. On 30-Sep-2019 and 31-Oct-2019, the patient received a second and third injection of HEPLISAV-B, respectively. The injections were administered at the left deltoid. After the third injection, while driving home, the patient started to have an allergic reaction.  She drove herself to the emergency department. The patient developed diffused hives, her throat, chest, and ears started to tighten, and she had a low blood pressure of 89/68 upon arrival to urgent care. Treatment with Epipen (epinephrine) 0.03 mg x 2, methylprednisolone shot, and Benadryl (diphenhydramine) were administered. The patient fully recovered and was released. At the time of this report, her status was stable and within normal limits.   At the time of the report, the events were considered recovered.   The reporter did not provide a serious assessment for the event.   Company comment: The company assessed the events of hypersensitivity, throat tightness, chest discomfort and hypotension as serious, and the events of urticaria, ear discomfort and extra dose administered as non-serious. Based on the temporal relationship, the events of hypersensitivity, throat tightness, chest discomfort and hypotension occurred after the third dose of Heplisav-B, a causal association between the events and Heplisav-B is possible. The events of hypersensitivity, throat tightness, chest discomfort, ear discomfort, urticaria, hypotension and extra dose administered are unlisted per Heplisav-B USPI.; Sender's Comments: The company assessed the events of hypersensitivity, throat tightness, chest discomfort and hypotension as serious, and the events of urticaria, ear discomfort and extra dose administered as non-serious. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient did not have an adverse reaction to the immunization.  Patient was due to Hib vaccine and polio vaccine was administered. Called Health department and mother notified.

Beginning at 5 p.m. the day of the vaccine, patient noticed itching and red rash under neck, and  on upper chest. In the middle of the night, patient awoke with itching and noted that rash had spread over more of upper chest and into left axillary area. She took Benadryl which helped the itch. Rash disappeared after 2-3 days.

Patient's mother reports that approximately 2 to 3 hours after vaccine administration, child began to break out in hives. Hives started on child's abdomen but spread systemically. Mother administered over the counter Benadryl and reports that the reaction resolved by morning. After administration of Benadryl, child was laid down for bed near mother for further monitoring. Child has recovered and there does not appear to be any lasting adverse side effects.
ALLERGIES: none reported (denies allergy to eggs and states child received preservative free formulation). patients mother reports that child has always been more sensitive to medications and immunizations but has never had a reaction that was out of normal limits or rare.

Seizure; Information was received from an investigator concerning a 6-month-old male subject enrolled in a study.  The subject's concurrent conditions and concomitant therapies were not reported. The subject's medical history included shoulder dystocia. ^^The subject had family history of seizures (2 maternal cousins had seizures when they were toddlers). the infant was born at 38 4/7 weeks gestational age, length 52 cm, weight 3470 grams, head circumference 35 cm. No neonatal problems except shoulder dystocia^^  On 11-JUL-2019, the subject was randomized into the study protocol. On that date, at 15:06, the subject was vaccinated with the first dose of Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent (ROTATEQ) (dose: 2 mL) orally (PO), and on the same day, at 15:07, he was vaccinated with the first dose of V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13) 0.5 mL intramuscularly (IM), 4 doses in visits 1, 2, 3 and 5. He as was also vaccinated at 15:08, with the first dose of diphtheria toxoid (+) Haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (unspecified carrier) (+) pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified) (+) poliovirus vaccine, inactivated (unspecified) (+) tetanus toxoid (DTAP-IPV HIB) (PENTACEL) vaccine (dose: 0.5 mL) IM, and at 15:09, with Hepatitis B Vaccine (Recombinant) (RECOMBIVAX HB) (dose: 0.5 mL) IM. On an unspecified date, the subject was also vaccinated with Haemophilus b Conjugate Vaccine (Tetanus Toxoid Conjugate) (HIBERIX) (dose details not reported). V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13) was administered as prophylaxis for pneumococcal disease; while, all other vaccines were administered as prophylaxis (unspecified).    On 10-SEP-2019 at 10:31, 10:32 and 10:33, the subject received second doses of Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent (ROTATEQ) and the second dose of V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13) (doses and route of administration as previously described) and diphtheria toxoid (+) Haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (unspecified carrier) (+) pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified) (+) poliovirus vaccine, inactivated (unspecified) (+) tetanus toxoid (DTAP-IPV HIB) (PENTACEL). On 12-NOV-2019 at 14:42, 14:44, 14:45 and 14:46, the subject received third doses of Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent (ROTATEQ) and the second dose of V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13)  (doses and route of administration as previously described), diphtheria toxoid (+) Haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (unspecified carrier) (+) pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified) (+) poliovirus vaccine, inactivated (unspecified) (+) tetanus toxoid (DTAP-IPV HIB) (PENTACEL) and Hepatitis B Vaccine (Recombinant) (RECOMBIVAX HB).  Since an unspecified date (reported since the subject was 4-month-old), the subject's mother reported that he had episodes of seizures that lasted several seconds; ^^the child did not present with seizures prior to randomization at 2 months age. There were no similar events experienced after the administration of the first and second doses of study vaccines, and there were no signs and/or symptoms prior to the administration of the third dose of study vaccines. No evidence of failure to thrive^^. On 12-NOV-2019, the subject was seen for his 6-month well child check. ^^During the clinic visit, his mother reported that a few weeks ago, the child started having episodes where he would be crying and then he would tighten his arms and his legs. This would only last for a few seconds and then he was fine. She reported that last week, the maternal grandmother noted that he did this, and eyes rolled to the back of his head and he seemed like he was not breathing. She blew in his face and then he started crying again. He was immediately fine after this and not lethargic or drowsy. At the WCC, the child was assessed as 6-month-old male with normal growth and development. The episodes of tightening his arms and legs were considered to be more like temper tantrums but it was discussed with the parent that if that was seizure, he would be needed to be evaluated further.^^ Moreover, the physician asked the mother to record a video of the seizures and they would be referred to a specialist for workup and possible treatment.  On 13-NOV-2019 at 13:15, the subject was in the grandmother's arms when he started crying and screaming for several seconds, his eyes rolled back, and he became limp and stopped breathing. The subject experienced seizure (severe). ^^There were no relevant signs / symptoms, apart from crying already noted, prior or concurrent to previous episodes of possible seizures^^. His grandmother took him to freestanding emergency room (ER) (outside the site facility). At the outside facility, the subject was found to be in asystole and apneic; became bradycardic down to 50's then coded. ^^On that day, his glucose was 246 mg/dl.^^ Cardio pulmonary resurrection (CPR) started with return of spontaneous circulation. He was transferred by ambulance to the site ER but lost the pulse again in route; 6 doses of epinephrine were administered prior to arrival. During transfer pulse less electrical activity noted and asystole on emergency medical services (EMS) monitors, CPR was performed while bagged, EMS attempted to intubate without success in route. An oral airway was placed and bilateral intraosseous lines in lower extremities. They arrived at the site ER with the subject in cardiac arrest and apneic. On arrival to the site, the subject was intubated, epinephrine, atropine, bicarbonate and naloxone (NARCAN) were administered ^^for cardiac arrest^^. An ultrasound for pulse check showed no cardiac activity. ^^It was reported that the subject was hospitalized^^. Core temperature was 94.6 Fahrenheit rectally, CRP continued with no success an at 14:19 (after 1 hour) the subject died due to ^^seizure^^ as per hospital records. ^^An autopsy was performed. No imaging testing to evaluate the seizures was carried out; no medications were given for previous episodes of possible seizures. The subject died in the ER before he could be admitted to the hospital; therefore, admission date, discharge date and discharge diagnosis were not applicable. There was no confirmed diagnosis of seizures prior to the day of death and no further information available regarding onset dates of 'episodes' reported by the mother^^. The action taken with the study therapies was reported as ^^dose not changed^^.  The investigator considered the seizure (severe) to be related to V114 or pneumococcal 13valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13), Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent (ROTATEQ), Hepatitis B Vaccine (Recombinant) (RECOMBIVAX HB), to diphtheria toxoid (+) Haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (unspecified carrier) (+) pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified) (+) poliovirus vaccine inactivated (unspecified) (+) tetanus toxoid (DTAP-IPV HIB) (PENTACEL) vaccine and Haemophilus b Conjugate Vaccine (Tetanus Toxoid Conjugate) (HIBERIX), but not related to the study procedure. ^^The investigator assessed the event related to administration of all vaccines due to temporal relationship and no other definitive cause of death^^. The investigator considered the seizure (severe) to be a life-threatening event.  Updated information received on 15-NOV-2019 from the investigator has been captured in between double caret (^^).  The record for this subject was unblinded on 18-NOV-2019. Company Causality Assessment: Although there is a family history of seizures and co-suspect use RECOMBIVAX HB (known to be associated with non-fatal seizure), based on the clinically relevant information currently available for this individual case, there is a possibility  that the reported serious adverse event of Seizure with a fatal outcome is related to the use of the investigational vaccines (blinded investigational vaccine [V114 or PREVNAR 13] and open-label study vaccine [PENTACEL and HIBERIX). The plausible temporal relationship, the known safety profiles of the blinded comparator (known to be associated with non-fatal seizure and apnea) and open label study vaccines (PENTACEL [known to be associated with non-fatal apnea] and HIBERIX [known to be associated with non-fatal convulsions]) support the possible relationship. Additional information regarding laboratory data due to increased glucose prior to CPR, autopsy report and the history of shoulder dystocia with unknown complications are needed for further assessment. Important missing information includes any record of fever accompanying the event. Febrile seizures have previously been reported in children who have received pneumococcal conjugate vaccines (PREVNAR 13).  An Analysis of Similar Events regarding this follow up report of the adverse reaction of Seizure with the serious criteria of hospitalization, life threatening and death was performed. This case refers to a 6-month-old male subject who experienced Seizure after the third dose of the investigational vaccines (blinded investigational vaccine [V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) PREVNAR 13] and open label study vaccines [PENTACEL and HIBERIX]). This is the first reported case of Seizure in association with the investigational vaccines (blinded investigational vaccine [V114 or pneumococcal 13 valent conjugate vaccine (CRM197) PREVNAR 13] and open label study vaccines [PENTACEL and HIBERIX]) submitted to the FDA.     The Suspected Adverse Reactions of Seizure does not alter the existing benefit-risk profile of the product. Merck and Co., Inc., known as MSD outside of certain countries, will continue to monitor this event and other serious adverse events reported in association with V-114 and will communicate any relevant changes to the protocol, Investigator's Brochure and/or Core Safety Information.; Reported Cause(s) of Death: Seizure
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 20191113; Test Name: glucose; Test Result:  246 mg/dl
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Seizures; Shoulder dystocia

A day after receiving this vaccine, Patient came down with a fever, nausea and severe cold symptoms, runny nose, cough, and felt like he couldn't breathe. The cough progressed more severe and he felt his airways constricted. He lost weight from not being able to hold down food, and was constantly nauseous.  He saw Dr. on 9/17/2019, where she examined him, and prescribed Ondansetron for nausea, and advised him to take claritin in addition to an over the counter antacid. He was instructed to use his Albuterol inhaler to open up airways. Patient's symptoms persisted and we came back in 10/23/2019.   His cough very persistent and his airways tight. He still has runny, stuffy nose and is still nauseous each day, especially in the morning. A chest x-ray was ordered. He was prescribed a round of Prednisone, Singular and Ondansetron.   Upon calling on 11/8/2019 to find out x-ray results, I was notified of hyperinflation of the lungs by the medical assistant. After speaking to the doctor, she referred him the Pulmonary department for further testing. He was prescribed more Ondansetron, Symbicort and Albuterol.

As previously stated, I received the Pneumovax vaccination on June 6, 2017.  That night, I awoke in the early hours of the morning with an urge to use the bathroom. I could not understand why the muscles in my entire body were so sore and painful when I moved or walked. I thought perhaps I caught a bug.    Unable to move, I remained in bed for two days and had to use a commode.  It was during that time, I realized my urine had changed color, resembling that of black coffee. As a nurse, I became worried and knew this was not just a bug and needed to go to the hospital.   On the third day, my husband and I arrived at the Emergency Room of Hospital, where I was admitted and given IVs throughout the day.  The soreness and muscle pain subsided gradually, and I had expected to be released, however they admitted me and remained at the hospital for a total of five days.   The doctors were extremely concerned regarding my liver enzymes which were elevated. I have never had any medical issue with my liver before and the doctors were trying to find the cause. The medical terms used during my stay were: ? Myositis? inflammation of muscles and muscle damage Transaminitis - refers to unusually high levels of a family of enzymes called transaminases. Myalgia ? mild to sever muscle pain   At the end of five days I was discharged and advised to see Doctor at the same hospital.  I saw him go through my records and requested that I go to the lab again and have blood drawn to check my liver enzymes.  The doctor ordered my blood drawn at regular intervals after that to continue to monitor my liver enzymes.    Over months my liver enzymes eventually stabilized and I was extremely relieved.  He gave me the news over the phone as he had since retired.
LAB_DATA: Admitted to hospital and was given IV fluids, workup showed liver enzymes were elevated. Ultrasound was performed which did not demonstrate a cause for high liver enzymes.  Ultrasound of heart showed heart failure but heart had same function as in October of the previous year. Heart not cause of elevated liver enzymes. Ruled out obstructive bile stone with MRCP, simultaneously getting an MRI of abdomen which did not show any cause for abnormal tests.
OTHER_MEDS: Aspirin 81 mg EC tablet by mouth daily Plavix 75 mg  daily LASIX 20 mg 1 tablet daily AMARYL 4 mg daily Metformin 1,000 mg daily Lopressor 50 mg daily Multi-vitamin daily

Occlusion of the left P2 segment of the left posterior cerebral artery; Acute left territory infarction; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation referring to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications were not reported. On or about 12-OCT-2017, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot #, expiration date, dosage and route of administration were not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On 12-NOV-2017, reported as one month after receiveing zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered right sided numbness in her arm, facial droop and paresthesias. The patient was hospitalized and diagnosed with acute left territory infarction and occlusion of the left P2 segment of the left posterior cerebral artery. The patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury.   Upon internal review, infarction and cerebral artery occlusion were considered medically significant.    Infarction and cerebral artery occlusion were considered to be disabling due to the severe, permanent and incurable injuries.

30 minutes after the vaccine patient developed body aches and chills. He had his blood drawn at that time as part of a routine office visit which showed at elevation in his white blood cells (see below). His condition continued to worsen (feeling more ill) at home and he was sent back to Urgent Care for a recheck. At this point his kidney and liver function tests had deteriorated (see below) and his leukocytosis had increased to 41.27 (see below). Hematology was consulted by Dr. the Urgent Care physician for Clinic and they advised him this was most likely an adverse reaction to the vaccine. Currently patient is having a new symptom of rectal bleeding and we cannot reach him by phone to check on his status. We may send police to his home if no answer to our emails and calls by closing today. If condition worsens he may be directed to the Emergency Department.

I have flu shots every year without any adverse reaction.  This is the first time I had the senior FLUAD  vaccine.  The second evening after the shot I could not sleep and I felt dizzy.  The next morning I started severely vomiting along with nonstop diarrhea.  I live alone and I was so dizzy and weak I could hardly make it  from the couch to the bathroom.  I was vomiting so hard, I though I might need to go to the emergency room.  I was also sweating profusely and extremely weak.  I was not running a fever.  It felt like a severe bout of food poisoning.  I had not eaten anything suspicious whatsoever.  The reason I am reporting this is that if I had been in more fragile condition, I think this event could have been extremely dangerous.  In 2013 I was treated for triple negative breast cancer and given Cytoxan and Taxotere.  If I had this reaction during that treatment, I think I would have been in the hospital.  The symptoms abruptly stopped in about 8 hours.  I was very weak for a day or two but there were no more symptoms.

At 1:15 PM, on Tuesday, November 19, 2019, I got the flu shot for this year, ("AFLURIA QIV PFS 2019-2020 INJ  0.5 ML", Quantity: 0.5).  I felt totally fine when I got the shot.  At about 7:15 PM, I started feeling nauseated (never actually vomited); I got chills, and I was shaking.  Also, my eyes were excreting a lot of gunk.  I felt like I had a fever, but we checked, and I did not.  Also, all the color in my face was drained - I was a pasty white.  I laid down on the couch with extra covers and the shaking subsided, and I sipped water.  We considered going into Urgent Care, but by 9:15 PM, I was feeling quite a bit better, and the color started returning to my face.  By the next morning, I was feeling fine.  I am a 64-year-old woman in good health, and I exercise regularly.  I have not had a negative reaction to any previous flu shots.  The reason I'm submitting this is that my reaction to this year's flu shot doesn't seem to be described in the pamphlet covering the possible reactions to the flu shot; and therefore, I thought I should let you know.  Thank you for your concern.

general pains around her heart; injection site pain in the left arm /injection site on her left arm is still painful; general pains down the left side of her neck; general pains on her left shoulder; General pain down her left arm /Arm pain; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of cardiac pain in a 82-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included rheumatoid arthritis (diagnosed at the of age 50). Concomitant products included tramadol.   On 12th September 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In September 2019, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced cardiac pain (serious criteria GSK medically significant), injection site pain, neck pain, shoulder pain and pain in arm. The patient was treated with ambiguous medication nos (Neurontin (Nos)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the cardiac pain, injection site pain, neck pain, shoulder pain and pain in arm were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the cardiac pain, injection site pain, neck pain, shoulder pain and pain in arm to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The patient received Shingrix in left arm. The patient reported that the Shingrix shot was the most painful vaccine she had received. The patient reported that within 3 to 4 days of receiving the first dose of the Shingrix vaccine, she began to experienced general pains around her heart, down the left side of her neck, on her left shoulder, and down her left arm. The patient went to her neurologist and was prescribed Neurontin.  The patient said that symptoms now come and go but he injection site on her left arm was still painful. During the call patient said she had pain around her heart. The patient felt that these symptoms were due to how the product was administered to her, not due to the product itself. The patient did not elaborate further. The reporter consented to follow up.
CUR_ILL: Rheumatoid arthritis (diagnosed at the of age 50)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Redness and pain around injection site, still there 36 hours later now. The night of the shot, all my joints and muscles in horrendous pain, skin super sensitive, could not sleep at all. In the morning, took 3 Advil and slept about 3 hours sitting up on sofa which helped a lot but didn't feel mostly better until late on Sunday. Today is Monday, and I am achy but functioning again. I have to travel by plane tomorrow and I feel I can do that where on Sunday morning I would not have been able to.
LAB_DATA: I didn't get any. Not that severe.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the immunization the mother noted a red, warm, swollen patch at the site of the immunization.  This worsened the following day, so the mother brought the child in for examination.  There was an indurated, erythematous patch about 10 cm in diameter present at the site of the injection

On November 9, 2019 at ~ 10:30 AM I was washing patient in the bathroom sink and I noticed his body became limp with decrease in muscle tone.  His eyes were half open and half closed and was extremely pale.  He did not respond to me and I began breastfeeding him.  At that time he started feeding and was able to track me, however, his color was still very pale.  We called on call pediatrician and recommended we take temperature and it was ranging from 96.5 - 97.5 rectally.  She recommended we go to ER.  We monitored him at home for a little bit and then due to him not being his normal chippy self we decided to take to ER.  Patient was very quiet and chill and not as excited as he usually is.  When driving to ER @ ~ 3:00 PM - 4:00 PM he went unresponsive again in the car seat and his head dropped down.  I (mother) took him out of his car seat and noted him arms and legs were limp and began breastfeeding.  He started feeding and was tracking me, but color was very pale again.  We called 911 and he was transported to Medical Center via ambulance.  During ambulance transport patient was stable and did not have any episodes. A 7-year-old patient of an unspecified gender received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date at single dose for immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.  The patient sustained a fall injury and got a fever within 24 hours. Patient was sent to the hospital. Once at the hospital, patient was diagnosed with strep pneumonia meningitis. Titers showed only significant antibodies were 6B and 18C. All other 21 strains tested, including 9 Prevnar 13 serotypes in the panel, were low or absent. Physician recommended booster of PCV13 and PPSV. Lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available, a lack of efficacy with pneumococcal 13-valent conjugate vaccine in this patient cannot be completely excluded. Fall represents an accidental injury unrelated to vaccine use.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Having pain when attempts to turn her arm; swelling and inflammation in same arm as injection; swelling and inflammation in same arm as injection; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable pharmacist. A 76-year-old female patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) (lot# AG8353, Exp date Jun2021, NDC 00005-1971-02), intramuscular in deltoid left, on 30Oct2019, at 0.5 ml single, for immunisation. Medical history and concomitant medications were none. The patient experienced swelling and inflammation in same arm as injection on 31Oct2019 with outcome of not recovered. The events were considered medically significant. The patient saw her doctor on 04Nov2019 and 06Nov2019. The doctor initially thought it was something else, but now believes it may be a reaction to the vaccination. The reaction started out as some swelling and irritation below the injection site and then it increased up toward the injection site and then went down to patient's hand. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events and included treatment with Clindamycin at 300 mg 3x/day, that was changed to Keflex at 500 mg 3x/day as well as Benadryl. The patient stated her arm was still swollen at this time and she indicated having pain when attempted to turn her arm.; Sender's Comments: There is a reasonable possibility that the events "swelling and inflammation in same arm as injection" were related to pneumococcal 13-valent conjugate vaccine based on known drug safety profile.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

large joints were quite painful-shoulders; fever; knees hurt like crazy / joints were quite painful / hip pain; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of fever in a patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 23rd July 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 24th July 2019, 1 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced fever (serious criteria other: serious per reporter) and knee pain (serious criteria other: serious per reporter). In August 2019, the patient experienced shoulder pain (serious criteria other: serious per reporter). The patient was treated with naproxen (Aleve) and meloxicam. On 26th July 2019, the outcome of the fever was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the knee pain and shoulder pain were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the fever, knee pain and shoulder pain to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had a serious reaction to the first injection and asked to advise him or her. The patient enquired about getting the second injection or the timing of that second injection. A day later both knees hurt like crazy when going upstairs. The patient also had a fever of 101. These symptoms were faded over a couple of days, but several weeks later (mid-August) all large joints were quite painful including knees, hips and shoulders. Treating with Aleve was only partially effective in relieving the pain, so patient visited to Internist. The Internist prescribed Meloxicam 25 mg for 2 weeks and patient then refilled that for an additional 10 days. That round of medication was just completed and patient's joints were much improved, but not back to normal. The Internist had suggested pushing out the second injection as late as possible, and had also referred patient to a rheumatologist. Rheumatologists were apparently in hot demand as the first available appointment would not until February. The patient would like to see the rheumatologist prior to getting the second injection, but wondered how long between doses was acceptable, and whether had any additional advice. The patient never had any reaction to a vaccine other than at the site. Unless the rheumatologist felt it was not recommended based on the reaction to the first one. This had been quite scary as patient felt like it added about 15 years of age. The patient was sure hope it continued to improve and that did not regret getting the Shingrix for the rest of life. The reporter requesting consent to follow up.

Around 9:50 AM patient received a flu shot and then her son received one. One to two minutes later after she received her shot, the patient felt dizzy and flush. I had the patient sit in a chair and propped the patient's feet up in another chair. The patient never had any breathing or vision problems. I gave her a bottle of water and employee fanned her with plastic blue cards. I got another employee to activate the ice packet and get it to working. The patient put the ice pack on her forehead. I had someone else call the switch board 129 for a code white and for a member of management. The patient requested us to call an ambulance. Talked to 911 and then to the ambulance service but then while on the phone with ambulance service the patient changed her mind and canceled the ambulance request. The patient kept feeling a little better and a little better. Manager filled out a report on the Ipad and I filled out a section as a witness. The patient left at 10:12 AM.

Next day, patient woke up and she told mother she was not feeling good and felt sore.  Patient was tired, sleepy, and had no appetite.    Parent noticed she was breathing heavily when sleeping  as if gasping for air but it was only lasted for a couple of minutes and went away.    On Saturday, rash evolved and worsen.  Parents contacted the doctor via email; told to use ice packs and give patient Zyrtec. Parents told that symptoms would subside over 48 hours. By evening, vaccine area was swelling, seemed to be retaining fluid and was not improving.  Parents contacted nurse, affected area was 4 inches wide, and directed to ER.  Patient was diagnosed with cellulitis and prescribed antibiotics (Cephalexin); patient released.  Patient will follow-up with PCP to see if symptoms improving.  So far, there is some improvement.  Received Flu vax in early October.
PRIOR_VAX: a little bit of a rash after same vaccine combination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: RNs notified that by CMA that patient was experiencing sweating, dizziness after administration of flu vaccine.  RN exam-patient was pale, pulse steady. Notified PCP re: diaphoretic, pale, reporting dizziness.   Assessed orientation, denied difficulty breathing or chest pain. patient reported prior vasovagal episodes post blood draws.    Patient became extremely diaphoretic, head began nodding back. Responded to verbal stimulation. PERRLA. Denied difficulty breathing or chest pain. Answered all RN questions appropriately. Weak bilateral grip strength. Drank apple juice. VS assessed throughout, PCP present and recommended patient returned to supine position, patient reporting blurred vision/weakness. Transferred to low bed. CBG checked, EKG completed. BP taken. MDs reviewed EKG, reassessed patient. Pt ambulated around clinic RN to confirm gait stability; pt had no impairment to gait, oriented to person, place, time. Denies CP, AMS, difficulty breathing, visual changes/disturbances, diaphoresis/pallor subsided. Patient discharged home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: intrauterine Growth Retardation; cyanotic; drug exposure in utero; Initial information received on 13 November 2019 regarding a solicited valid serious case received from a consumer/non-hcp, in the scope of post-marketing sponsored study. This case involves a male patient who had intrauterine growth retardation (Foetal growth restriction) and was cyanotic (Cyanosis) after birth, whose mother received FLUZONE QIV vaccine and received Benzyl Alcohol. The mother's age at the time of report was not reported. The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  Concomitant therapy included Benzyl Alcohol.  On an unknown date, the patient's mother received a dose of suspect FLUZONE QIV lot number not reported via unknown route. It was case of drug exposure in utero. On unknown date, the patient developed a serious event of intrauterine growth retardation (Before Birth) (foetal growth restriction), following administration of FLUZONE QIV to patient's mother. It was reported that the patient's mother stated that she went to 39 weeks and 1 day and then physician inducted her because the fetus was having intrauterine Growth Retardation (IUGR).  On unknown date, the patient developed a serious event of cyanotic (cyanosis) (After birth) following the administration of FLUZONE QIV to patient's mother.  The baby was born healthy an Apgar of 09, approximately 1 hour lately when the baby was attempting to breastfeed, he turned cyanotic and had to be watched in the nursery for the next 48 hours. The HCP attributed the cyanotic episode to an allergy to Benzyl alcohol. At the time f report the child in now 3 years old and seems to be doing well.  As per company, based IME list both the event considers as medically significant.  Final diagnosis was cyanotic, intrauterine growth retardation and drug exposure in utero. The Lab data not reported. It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment. The event outcome of intrauterine growth retardation and cyanotic was not reported. Relationship to investigational product according to reporter: not reported, The HCP attributed the cyanotic episode to an allergy to Benzyl alcohol. The child in now 3 and seems to be doing well. Relationship to investigational product according to company: reportable.; Sender's Comments: A neonate of adult female, who received a dose of study product during pregnancy, was diagnosed with intrauterine growth retardation and cyanotic. Which occurred after mother received a dose of study vaccine. Company causality taken as reportable for reporting purpose. The event cyanosis was assessed as related to Benzyl alcohol allergy. SYMPTOM_TEXT: After my son was born, he was taken from us and given unknown vaccines which we did not authorize.  He was over 10 pounds and beautifully healthy.  They came back later and said he was having trouble breathing and put him on a ventilator and he was in the NICU for 6 days.  He pulled out his tube twice; what newborn has the coordination or strength to do this?  Then they let us take him home.  He was having no trouble breathing after he was born and we are certain now that one or more of the vaccines he was giving caused this.  Six days of pain, suffering and anguish for all of us AND costing us thousands of dollars.  He was vaccine injured, we are sure of it.

He also complains that he is feeling "lousy". Doesn't think he has a fever. I have recommended that he apply a cool compress to the arm and alternate tylenol and ibuprofen for the swelling and pain. Pt suggested that he could take prednisone and I suggested that he should ask his doctor before doing that. Pt was worried that this is an infection, I assured him I do not believe that is what it is. I believe it is a common injection site reaction.

PRIOR_VAX: pt described extreme malaise and lousy feeling after flu shot last year.

After about 30 seconds, the client's face and lips got very pale and then she slumped forward and to the right, into her brother's lap, and then proceeded to slide down to the floor with this RN protecting and guiding client's upper body and head safely to the ground.  Client did not respond to name at that time. Once client was laying on ground, client started responding to her name being called by mother and RN within 15 seconds. Client oriented x3 upon responding, but feeling nauseated, color returning to face at this time. Client assisted to sitting position, with head between her legs. Client given water and orange juice and encouraged to move slowly after sitting for 10 minutes. Mother states client did not eat breakfast before appointment. Client felt better after sitting for the 10 minutes and was able to walk out of clinic.

He said right after receiving the vaccine two weeks ago, he had felt moderate to severe pain and muscle stiffness on his left arm where he had been vaccinated, causing him limited mobility on that arm and having pain moving and reaching across the opposite shoulder. He said there were nights that he can't sleep or wake up in the middle of the night because of the pain. He hasn't seen a doctor yet for these symptoms. Pharmacist suggested if he want to take NSAIDS like Advil or Aleve to help with the pain but he said he would only take NSAIDS if he feels it to be necessary. A Quality Assurance and Safety Report was already submitted on 11/22/19 about the patient's concerns and symptoms. He had been getting his yearly flu shot and this was the first time that he had experienced this shoulder pain. He understands this occurrence is usually expected after a vaccine administration but his symptoms still persist over two weeks after. He just wanted an assurance that these symptoms are just temporary and will be resolved soon. Pharmacy Risk Management Team had started working on this case and they will be reaching out to the patient to help him on this situation and fully address his concerns.
LAB_DATA: As per conversation with the patient last 11/25/19, he has not seen his doctor yet for these concerns and symptoms.

The patient's past medical history included end stage renal disease (On unspecified date in 2012, the patient had an initiated of hemodialysis), hepatitis b, viral hepatitis c, hiv infection and hemodialysis (On unspecified date in between July 2013 and August 2015).   In August 2015, the patient received Hepatitis B vaccine. Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a 50-year-old male patient who was vaccinated with unspecified Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to case 3 of table 1 reported in this literature article. The patient was identified from the medical history receiving hemodialysis and human immunodeficiency virus and hepatitis C virus coinfections. On unspecified date in 2012, the patient had an initiated of hemodialysis. At hemodialysis initiation at hospital A's outpatient clinic in 2012, his HBV serologic test results suggested a possible past resolved HBV infection with positive total anti-HBc (First known positive total anti-HBc on June 2012), positive anti-HBs ((before HBsAg seroconversion) October 2013), and negative HBsAg  (that First known negative HBsAg (June 2012); Last known negative HBsAg (July 2015). In December 2013, the patient lost HBV immunity and became anti-HBs negative while remaining HBsAg negative.  No information on patient's family history or concomitant condition was provided. On unspecified date in between July 2013 and August 2015, the patient was on hemodialysis (HD), the patient was on likely infectious and not on HBV isolation. On unspecified date in between December 2013 and June 2015, the patient potential exposure period was travel history. On unspecified date in August 2015, the patient had received unspecified Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided.  On an unspecified date in August 2015, unknown period after vaccination, the patient �s HBV Isolation was initiated. During hospitalization for hemodialysis (2015), the patient had an HBV serology, which showed First known positive HBsAg (August 2015); First known negative anti- HBs (December 2015); Last known negative anti- HBs (August 2015). On an unspecified August 2015, the patient's HBV serology showed that the 3,945,000 copies/m. On an unspecified March 2013, the patient's Highest known ALT/AST: 241/148. Repeat HBV testing for inpatient dialysis during an August 2015 hospitalization showed a weakly-reactive HBsAg testing by platform such as abbott in January 2016: positive; Siemens Advia Centaur XP: HBs assay: weakly-positive (August 2015); HBsII assay: positive (December 2015) and HBs assay: negative (June 2015 and September 2015), However, subsequent HBsAg testing on VITROS (August 2015 and January 2016) platform was negative, while HBV DNA levels were 3,945,459 IU/mL. From this point onward, HBV isolation precautions were initiated for this patient. HBsAg mutation was suspected as a possible explanation for the negative HBsAg result with concurrent high HBV DNA levels. The patient did not performed other HBV testing's: such as HBV genotype (H) and HBV molecular sequencing. Testing at CDC revealed positive HBsAg with Abbott ARCHITECT platform and negative HBsAg with VITROS platform, suggesting that it was a presumed HBsAg mutant strain, although attempts to sequence HBV DNA were unsuccessful due to low HBV DNA levels (500 copies/mL) at that time. The investigation launched in September 2015 revealed that the case patient received dialysis at 2 out-of-state hemodialysis clinics A and B in June 2015. At out-of state hemodialysis clinic A, he was dialyzed in an HBV isolation room because of serologic test results demonstrating potential HBV infectivity (hepatitis B e antigen positive and HBsAg negative). However, he was not dialyzed in an HBV isolation room at out-of-state hemodialysis clinic B because he tested negative for HBsAg (on Siemens Advia Centaur XP platform, using Siemens HBs assay, not the newer HBsII assay). Screening of potentially exposed hemodialysis patients did not reveal new HBV infections. The case patient was treated for HBV infection and his last HBV DNA levels were very low. He continues to receive hemodialysis with HBV isolation precautions in place. This case considered as suspected vaccination failure due to onset time was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure. The author commented, "To our knowledge, there has been no documented hemodialysis-related transmission of a mutant strain of HBV. Our patient had serologic evidence of previous HBV infection (total anti-HBc positive) before initiation of hemodialysis; therefore, their HBsAg seroconversions could have been the result of reactivation ofthan new infection." The author concluded "Mutant HBV infections should be suspected in patients who test HBsAg negative and concurrently test positive for HBV DNA at high levels. Dialysis providers should consider using HBsAg assays that can also detect mutant HBV strains for routine HBV testing." This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in this literature article. At unspecified time, the patient reported feeling numb, left arm started throbbing and crying due to the pain (hypoaesthesia and pain). It was also reported that the patient could not stand up or take a shower. The patient explained that she had a big red knot at the injection site (for pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) in her left arm) (injection site nodule and injection site erythema), swelling red bump which was hard at first, then red and hot (injection site induration, injection site mass and injection site warmth), and then swelling went down the left arm and stopped at the elbow (peripheral swelling). The patient reported that she experienced no reaction in her right arm where she got the unspecified "flu shot".   Ice and heating pad were put on patient's left arm and the patient took oxycodone. Unspecified osteoporosis test, blood work, thyroid test, vitamin d, urine study, bone markers (CTX (C-terminal telopeptide) and CVC (Cardiovascular Continuum)) and liver profile were performed, and the results were unknown. The outcome of pain in extremity, injection site warmth, injection site induration, injection site erythema, injection site discolouration, peripheral swelling, pain, injection site nodule, hypoaesthesia, dizziness, skin discolouration and injection site mass was reported as recovering. The pain was so intense it made me so weak in the knees I could not stand.  Thankfully my husband caught me.  This wave of pain was accompanied by severe dizziness and nausea.  I also had severe pain under my left arm.  I took 3 tablets, 650 mlgrams each, of Tylenol for Arthritis.  I drank a lot of water and applied a heating pad to the most painful area, my lower back.  I tried to rest.  By morning my fever had reduced and I was able to eat plain oatmeal and tea.  I seem to be steadily improving, feeling now like the "day after" a bad flu.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The first reaction was redness and swelling at the injection site.  Subsided within three days and did not occur with the second dose.  The second possible reaction was low kidney function tests during a July 2019 doctors office visit indicating the patient had Stage 4 kidney failure.  Increased hydration has improved these numbers to be almost back to normal .  Further blood tests will show if any additional improvement has occurred.
LAB_DATA: All test results can be obtained from the Doctor's office.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 24 hours after receiving her flu shot, patient had a seizure.  She was seen in the ER immediately and looking well.  Discharged home.   That night began having intractable seizures of unclear etiology.   Admitted to the ICU within a day and has been there since then.  Currently intubated and still no cause found for the new onset seizures.  I do not know if her flu shot causes this, but no other cause has been found and this was the only thing that was different in the 24 hours preceding her illness.  I am obligated to report this for the POSSIBILITY that it could be connected.
LAB_DATA: No tests have been conclusive in identifying the cause of her seizures.  She was completely well the day before her symptoms began and received only a flu shot the day before her symptoms began.
